<FIRST>r a PM-Proposition103     11-09 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Proposition 103,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Year Later Insurance Rates Still Not Slashed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first anniversary of California voters'
approval of Proposition 103 passed with citizens still waiting for
insurance rates to be slashed.
   Its author claims that while victory has been delayed, it has
not been denied.
   ``What's at stake here is democracy and who's in charge,'' the
initiative's author, Harvey Rosenfield, told a press conference
Wednesday at the headquarters of the Voter Revolt organization.
   The proposition, which has the force of law, called for 20
percent rollbacks from 1987 auto insurance rates. It also said that
geography should be less important to setting rates than drivers'
records and experience and made the office of insurance
commissioner an elected position.
   The major insurance companies, however, have not rolled back
their rates in the wake of a court battle over the referendum. An
estimated 700 companies were affected. They also have not begun
judging rates according to driving records.
   The insurance commissioner, at least, becomes an elected
position in the November 1990 election.
   On the anniversary day, Rosenfield and Conway Collis, an elected
state tax official who also is a candidate for the 1990 race for
insurance commissioner, stood behind boxes marked ``$1,000s''
symbolizing the 20 percent rollbacks still in insurers' coffers.
   They said Prop. 103's promises would soon be realized if
supporters keep faith. ``It's fair to say that for the first time
we can see light at the end of the tunnel,'' Rosenfield said.
   But they acknowledged frustration, and Rosenfield fired salvos
at state Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie.
   ``We are as frustrated as anybody else is,'' Rosenfield said.
``It is an absolute outrage that we are basically 11 months behind
schedule in the provisions of 103 that were supposed to go into
effect on election day.''
   Voters approved Prop. 103 on Nov. 8, 1988, on a vote of 4.8
million to 4.6 million. The next day insurers filed numerous
lawsuits against it and a day later the California Supreme Court
suspended implementation for a review.
   By December, the Supreme Court had lifted the stay on
implementing most of the measure except for the 20-percent
rollbacks.
   To add insult to injury, the largest seller of auto insurance in
California, State Farm, announced in January that it was raising
rates an average of 9.6 percent.
   Prop. 103 was upheld by the high court in May, but the court
said the commissioner should exempt a company from rollbacks if it
would not receive what the court called a fair and reasonable rate
of return.
   In early August the commissioner set the fair rate of return at
11.2 percent annually. By the end of August that figure had been
characterized as tentative and could be revised upward.
   In the meantime, more than 400 insurance companies had filed for
exemption from rollbacks and the commissioner said three of the
state's largest insurance sellers were among hundreds likely to win
exemptions.
   During summer hearings, insurance companies also told Gillespie
she should continue to allow territorial rating systems in which
prices are set according to neighborhood.
   As more rate hikes were announced and confusion over the status
of Prop. 103 mounted, Gillespie on Oct. 2 ordered rate increases
frozen for six months and said all issues would be taken up at
hearings.
   Collis sought to put the best face on the developments.
   ``It's really important for people to realize on this
anniversary of 103 that rollbacks have been delayed, the move away
from territorial rating system has been delayed but it's now in the
process and if we hang together awhile longer it's now going to
happen,'' Collis said.
   The insurance companies want people to become apathetic about
Prop. 103, Rosenfield claimed.
   ``If you talk to the insurance companies they gloat about the
fact that 71 percent of the people have said they don't ever think
that they ever have forced the insurance companies to give us those
rollbacks,'' he said.
   Asked if he would have done anything differently, Rosenfield
said he should have incorporated criminal penalties into the law.
</TEXT>
