<FIRST>r a PM-Hepburn's80th     11-09 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hepburn's 80th,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Decades for Kate the Great</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editors</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Life is a thief,'' Katharine Hepburn tells
Montgomery Clift in ``Suddenly, Last Summer.'' But life knew better
than to steal from Kate the Great.
   The voice Tallulah Bankhead once likened to ``nickels dropping
in a slot machine'' has grown tremulous with age. But nothing can
daunt that special Yankee strength that has seen 80 autumns.
Hepburn remains arrogant, bossy and tenacious, principled,
passionate and clever. Her viperish wit slices and dices. No, don't
mess with Kate.
   ``I think I'm very irritating to some people,'' she once said.
``It fascinates me, though, because I'm so sweet really.''
   Hepburn celebrated her 80th birthday Wednesday not quietly at
home as some her age would have it, but dashing about New York,
visiting ill friends. ``She's being a good Samaritan,'' her
secretary, Sharon Powers, said.
   ``Who cares about my birthday?'' the actress said recently. ``I
don't, as long as I can get around and think straight.''
   And she does think, about many things. She frets about the
backyard garden of her Manhattan brownstone, rails at youthful sex,
supports abortion and champions euthanasia for the elderly. If it
exists, Hepburn has something to say about it.
   ``I think there's sort of a terrible fear of death in this
country, and I just don't think you should fear something that is
absolutely inevitable,'' she said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
   ``I've been extremely lucky. I've got money and I can decide to
work or not work. I've been terribly lucky all my life.''
   Hepburn had a scare when a growth was discovered last year on
her vocal cords. A biopsy showed it was not cancerous, and she
recovered nicely from surgery.
   From the day RKO studio bosses first spotted her on the New York
stage in an abbreviated tunic playing an Amazon queen in ``The
Warrior's Husband,'' Hepburn has enchanted and seduced a moviegoing
public.
   Her first movie, ``A Bill of Divorcement,'' with John Barrymore,
was a success. Her next was a dud. The third, the stagey 1933
production ``Morning Glory,'' won her first Academy Award; three
others came in 1967, 1968 and 1981 for ``Guess Who's Coming to
Dinner,'' ``The Lion in Winter'' and ``On Golden Pond.''
   But after ``Morning Glory,'' Hepburn made several flops that
turned her into box-office poison. ``The Philadelphia Story'' in
1940 marked her resurrection from Hollywood's graveyard with her
champagney portrayal of a spoiled rich girl who marries and
remarries the man she loves.
   Playwright Philip Barry wrote it for her and the play was a
smash on Broadway.
   ``I bought the movie rights. They wanted to buy it for all my
rivals, but I already owned it. Very clever,'' she said.
   ``Then I stayed at Metro (MGM) and did all those pictures with
Spencer. I've done things for the honest reason that I like them.
You can't do things just to be successful. You have to do things
that affect you.''
   Spencer was Spencer Tracy, Hepburn's closest friend for 27
years. She was linked romantically with billionaire industrialist
Howard Hughes and producer Leland Hayward, and was married once _
in 1928 to Philadelphia socialite Ludlow Ogden Smith. They divorced
in 1934.
   Hepburn inherited her Yankee tenacity from her parents. Her
father, Dr. Norval Hepburn, was a urologist who campaigned for
public awareness about venereal disease. Her mother, Katharine
Houghton, was a suffragist and a crusader in the birth control
movement.
   Their tenacity, she said, freed her from fear. ``I wasn't afraid
to pay the price of saying what I thought. I wasn't cautious.''
   At Bryn Mawr College with its high academic standards and
mannered students, she survived on her wits. She almost flunked out
but buckled down to work so she could act in school plays. After
graduating, she plunged into stock and finally landed a bit role in
a Broadway flop.
   Lately, she's done some television work, including last year's
``Laura Lansing Slept Here.'' But mostly, she putters about in her
garden, visits friends, spends time in her home on the Connecticut
shore and looks for the right movie projects.
   ``It's terribly difficult to find interesting roles,'' she once
said. ``And a poor old thing dying in a rest home is not a terribly
interesting picture. I think it's just depressing.''
</TEXT>
