<DOCNO> AP891109-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-TerrorizedElections 1stLd-Writethru b0295 11-09 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Terrorized Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, b0295,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru's Shining Path Guerrillas Disrupting Local Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS typo in lead of b0295 sent Nov. 2 for use today. Sunday
in first graf is Nov. 12.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LIM1 sent Nov 2.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDAJES, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although high in the Andes and far from
anything else, this village of communal farmers has not escaped a
Maoist guerrillas' terror campaign to disrupt nationwide municipal
elections Sunday _ and in the long run the presidential election
next year.
   A column of 30 guerrillas of the Sendero Luminoso (Shining Path)
movement entered Andajes one stormy night and seized Mayor Heraclio
Segundo, four other local officials and a sixth man they accused of
cattle rustling. They then dragged them into the village plaza,
where they killed them with single gunshots to the back of the neck.
   As a result, no candidates are running for office Sunday in
Andajes.
   ``All that people think about is that they will come back, that
there will be more killings,'' said Andres Zuniga Bernabe, a young
farmer.
   The wave of assassinations of mayors and other local officials
in Peru has reached levels unprecedented in the Shining Path's
9-year-old insurgency.
   Latest available figures show that 263 mayors' posts around Peru
are unfilled, nearly all of them in small towns and villages with
little or no police protection.
   In Junin department, in the country's mining and farming
heartland 150 miles east of Lima, only 61 of 122 municipalities
have mayors.
   Some 4,500 candidates registered to run in the nation's nearly
2,000 mayoralty races, but an estimated 400 have resigned in fear,
and government officials expect many more to withdraw before
election day.
   So far this year the rebels have slain 45 mayors. They also have
killed 73 local judges, clerks, councilmen and municipal candidates.
   In October, 22 local authorities were slain. A total of 330
people died in armed clashes and political violence, one of the
highest monthly tolls since the Shining Path launched its
insurgency to topple Peru's elected government.
   Shining Path seeks to install a workers' and peasants' state
patterned on the ideas of the late Chairman Mao Tse-tung of China.
   Political analysts and counterinsurgency experts agree that the
rebels' campaign to disrupt the municipal elections is only the
first stage of their strategy to block the presidential election in
April and provoke a military coup.
   Shining Path's strategy then most likely would be to place
itself in the vanguard of a popular front against a military
dictatorship.
   Publicly, the populist government of President Alan Garcia has
guaranteed that municipal elections will take place throughout Peru.
   But privately a close Garcia aide, speaking in Lima on condition
he not be identified, said, ``The truth is we are not in a position
to guarantee the normal course of elections. I wonder how many
people are going to be able to vote.''
   He said Peru would need 300,000 policemen, not the 75,000 it
has, to provide around-the-clock protection to current authorities
and all municipal candidates.
   National election board officials are focusing their efforts on
guaranteeing that voting takes place in a normal fashion in Lima
and other major cities, where most of Peru's population of 21
million is concentrated.
   A third of the national territory is under states of emergency
that suspend constitutional guarantees and give the military broad
powers to fight guerrillas.
   It is in those areas that the elections are most in doubt, but
many critics of government policy say the contested regions cannot
be written off if Peru is going to defend its democratic system.
   Here in Andajes, situated on the dome of an 11,000-foot
mountain, people feel the government has knowingly let them pass
into the Shining Path's domain.
   Andajes is only 90 miles north of Lima in a straight line, but a
six-hour ride over bumpy roads that rise from the mist-shrouded
desert coast and climb the empty western slopes of the Andes.
   With its 2,000 inhabitants, its narrow cobblestone lanes and its
mud-brick houses, Andajes never received much attention in Lima.
But now the villagers feel totally abandoned.
   ``The people live with the fear that Sendero will return,'' said
village elder Ruben Torres.
   The 16-man police detachment sent to Andajes after its officials
were killed withdrew in June to the town of Churin, an hour's drive
away at the foot of the mountain.
   ``Most people did not sleep that first night,'' said Nancy
Jiron, a government health worker assigned to Andajes. ``They
gathered in small groups and waited for daybreak. They began to
realize they would have to accept being alone again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
