<HEAD>`Dorf' Goes to Court Over `Dorf Goes Auto Racing'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorf, a loveable buffoon played by comedian
Tim Conway, has played golf, witnessed the first Olympic Games, and
gone auto racing. Now, Dorf is going to court.
   A production company is suing Conway, who plays the 4-foot-tall
Derk Dorf character on videos, over the distribution of the tape
``Dorf Goes Auto Racing.''
   J2 Communications Inc., which claims to have the distribution
rights, alleges in a Superior Court lawsuit filed Wednesday that
Conway wrongly intends to sell ``Dorf Goes Auto Racing'' through
another company.
   J2 Communications seeks unspecified damages on allegations
including breach of contract, breach of good faith and fraud.
   The Dorf character was introduced in a J2-produced and
distributed video called ``Dorf on Golf,'' starring Conway's
diminutive alter-ego accompanied by a statuesque female assistant
named ``Boom Boom.''
   The video has sold more than 200,000 copies, making it one of
the seven most popular videos of all time, the lawsuit says.
   Other Dorf videos include ``Dorf and the First Games of Mt.
Olympus'' and ``Dorf's Golf Bible.''
   Conway's telephone number was not listed, so the entertainer
could not immediately be reached for comment.
