<DOCNO> AP891109-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-S&amp;LConvention     11-09 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L Convention,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weak S&amp;Ls Should Find Merger Partner or Face Regulatory Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrift regulator M. Danny Wall is issuing a
warning to weak savings and loan institutions: Find a merger
partner or face regulatory action.
   ``Thrifts that are undercapitalized are in very grave
jeopardy,'' Wall told the U.S. League of Savings Institutions on
Wednesday in closing its annual convention.
   His agency, the Office of Thrift Supervision, estimates that 800
of the nation's 2,600 solvent S&amp;Ls will fall nearly $20 billion
short of new, more stringent capital standards taking effect Dec. 7.
   The agency believes 223 of the 800 are practically hopeless and
within a year will join 260 failed institutions already under
government control. Another segment of the 800 will meet the new
standard and stay independent by retaining earnings or selling
assets, Wall said.
   But, about 300 will stay out of the government's hands only by
seeking a private merger partner. Wall said his agency stands ready
to help by finding suitors, including foreign firms and commercial
banks, starting with a special conference next week.
   ``We are calling this our `arranged marriage' program,'' he said.
   The new rules require S&amp;L owners to back their lending with more
of their own capital and are designed to provide a larger buffer of
private money between S&amp;L losses and government deposit insurance
funds. They are considered the cornerstone reform in S&amp;L bailout
legislation enacted Aug. 9.
   Wall warned weak thrifts not to be too choosy about merger
offers, adding, ``We will not hesitate to take regulatory action.''
   ``Go with what you've got ... not with the would have and could
have'' or it will be too late to find a merger partner, he said.
   Under the bailout bill, thrifts not meeting capital standards by
the end of 1994 face closure and Wall's agency is writing rules
that would permit it to seize an undercapitalized thrift early,
before its owners' investment is exhausted.
   One S&amp;L executive, Robert Duncan, chairman of Magnolia Federal
Bank for Savings of Hattiesburg, Miss., said some of his colleagues
at weaker thrifts haven't yet admitted they can't survive alone.
   ``There are a great number of people out there who are unwilling
to face it. ... But it's going to be difficult to face the siren
call of merger with a commercial bank,'' he said.
   Wall cited recent interest by Canadian and Japanese companies as
evidence of the thrift industry's positive outlook.
   ``The worst is really over. We have been through the fire and
emerged tempered by the experience,'' he said.
   In his speech, Wall did not mention the controversy swirling
around his agency's handling of the failure of Lincoln Savings and
Loan Association of Irvine, Calif., expected to cost taxpayers up
to $2 billion.
   However, at a news conference, he defended his decision to delay
seizure of Lincoln by nearly two years, saying he was legally
required to keep it open unless it was insolvent. The staff of the
House Banking Committee disputes that assertion, maintaining that
Wall need only have determined that Lincoln was operating unsafely
and dissipating its assets.
   ``We were advised at the time we did not have the (legal) basis
(to seize Lincoln). It was the best advice we could find,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-OilSpills Bjt   11-09 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spills, Bjt,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Preserves States' Power to Set Oil Spill Liability</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Pre-noon lead expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outrage over the Exxon Valdez oil spill helped
lead to the House's vote to let the states continue setting
unlimited liability for oil spill cleanups, environmentalists say.
   But the oil industry says the measure approved Wednesday could
do more harm than good to the environment and raise consumer fuel
costs.
   ``It was clear that the Exxon Valdez was such a national insult
to the environment that all the lobbying by the oil companies and
special interests couldn't overcome it,'' said Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif.
   Mike Matz of the Sierra Club said the spill demonstrated ``there
were some serious deficiencies in the bill'' as it was originally
written.
   Miller and Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., successfully inserted an
amendment into a massive oil liability bill that allowed stricter
state laws, despite strong oil industry opposition and several
attempts on the House floor to soften the measure. The measure
would track current law which also allows states to set stricter
liability limits.
   The House was scheduled to vote on the entire bill today, but
the key vote was on the Miller-Studds amendment, which passed
279-143.
   ``We are dismayed and distressed that the House has taken this
gigantic step backward in environmental protection,'' said a
statement issued by the American Petroleum Institute after the vote.
   ``Unless altered by conference committee action, we must
strongly urge that the president veto this legislation,'' the
industry lobbying organization said.
   The group said that allowing states to go beyond federal limits
on the amount a company should spend for oil spill cleanup will
make insurance costs for hauling oil prohibitive.
   ``If the House's plan is adopted into law, many responsible
transporters of oil will likely be driven out of business and
replaced by less financially responsible and capable shippers,''
said the institute.
   ``Operators involved in transportation of petroleum products may
feel it's not worth the legal risks,'' Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y.,
said during debate on the amendment. ``Home heating oil may
suddenly disappear.''
   A $2 billion price tag has been put on the Exxon Valdez cleanup
in Alaska. That state sets no limits on companies' liability for
repairing environmental damage.
   The House bill would limit oil companies' liability to $1,200
per gross ton, with a minimum of $10 million for large tankers and
$2 million for small tankers. However, it would let states set
higher limits. The Senate has passed similar legislation.
   Twenty-eight states now have their own oil spill liability
statutes, and 19 of them require unlimited liability.
   Studds accused the oil industry of using scare tactics.
   ``Make no mistake,'' Studds said. ``When it comes to state
pre-emption and the oil industry, the battle lines are clearly
drawn between those who are hurt by oil spills and those who cause
them, between the public interest and a narrow private interest,
between the average citizen and big oil.''
   Environmentalists were surprised at the size of the vote in
their favor, especially on a second Miller amendment that makes an
oil company or carrier liable for unlimited damages in cases of
simple negligence, rather than gross negligence as the original
measure required. That amendment, which had been expected to be
defeated, passed 213 to 207.
   ``What it means is that the high-priced lobbyists that the oil
companies brought in don't always do the trick,'' said Joe Mehrkens
of the Wilderness Society.
   The House for 14 years has repeatedly passed bills against
allowing states to pre-empt the federal law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
