<FIRST>r i PM-China-Executions     11-09 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Executions,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Executed For Rioting in Chengdu Following June 4 Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six people have been executed in the southwestern
city of Chengdu for participating in riots in June when the
government crushed the pro-democracy movement, a local official
said today.
   The executions brought to at least 18 the number of people put
to death following the military crackdown on demonstrators in
Beijing and other cities. Two people already had been reported
executed in Chengdu for roles in three days of rioting that began
June 4, when troops killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in Beijing
and police in Chengdu tried to break up a student sit-in.
   An estimated 30 people died in the Chengdu violence, and an
entire city block, including a large department store, was burned
down. It was the worst outbreak of violence in any city outside
Beijing.
   The six in Chengdu were sentenced to death at a public rally
Tuesday and immediately executed, said an official of Chengdu's
Foreign Affairs Office.
   Three were charged with ``beating, smashing, looting and
burning'' during the violence. The other three were charged with
theft and murder.
   At least 12 other people have been put to death for direct
involvement in anti-government demonstrations and riots throughout
China last spring.
   None of the previous 12 were students, and it was not clear
whether there were any students among the six executed in Chengdu
this week.
   China's press rarely reports arrests or court cases involving
the student-led pro-democracy movement. Reports that student
leaders and soldiers who refused to cooperate in the military
crackdown in Beijing have been executed cannot be confirmed.
   Executions in China are usually by a bullet to the back of the
head as the person sentenced kneels on the ground.
</TEXT>
