<FIRST>r w PM-SecordPlea     11-09 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secord Plea,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secord Pleads Guilty to Iran-Contra Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord,
awaiting sentencing on his guilty plea to an Iran-Contra charge,
promises to cooperate with the prosecution of other defendants such
as John M. Poindexter.
   Secord pleaded guilty Wednesday to one count of lying to
Congress and agreed to ``cooperate fully'' with prosecutors in
later cases in exchange for a government promise to seek dismissal
of 11 other criminal charges against him.
   Poindexter, whose criminal trial is to begin Jan. 22, is accused
of conspiracy, two counts of obstructing Congress and two counts of
making false statements.
   Secord has not yet spoken with government prosecutors and it
``remains to be seen'' what information he has to offer, said
prosecutor Reid Weingarten. The Secord case was to have gone to
trial on Monday.
   Secord, the Iran-Contra middleman enlisted by National Security
Council aide Oliver North, admitted to U.S. District Court Judge
Aubrey Robinson that he made a false statement on June 10, 1987,
when he denied to congressional investigators that he gave anything
of benefit to North.
   Poindexter has said he ``met with Gen. Secord, I guess, my whole
time in the White House maybe three or four times.''
   One of those times was in January 1986, when Poindexter said the
two discussed Secord's role in assisting upcoming arms shipments to
Iran.
   Just two months earlier, Secord had been involved at North's
request in the CIA-assisted shipment of Hawk missiles from Israel
to Iran. The presidential finding legalizing the CIA's involvement
in the shipment was written after the Hawks were transported.
   It is unclear whether Secord and Poindexter discussed the
previous shipments in January.
   Poindexter, the former national security adviser, is accused of
lying by telling members of Congress in a closed meeting that he
didn't learn until January 1986 that the November 1985 shipment
contained Hawks.
   North had sent Poindexter a status report on the November 1985
shipment just before it took place.
   Regarding assisting the Contras, ``I was aware that Dick Secord
was going to essentially set up and run a private logistics
organization,'' Poindexter told Congress 2{ years ago.
   Poindexter said he knew that overcharges on the sale of arms to
Iran ``would go into one of the accounts that Gen. Secord had that
he would then use to purchase arms to support'' the Contras.
   But Poindexter said that when he met with Secord it was for
``mainly what I would categorize as hand-holding. ... Col. North
was always telling me that he thought Dick was losing money.''
   Secord paid the bill in 1986 for a security system at North's
home, $7,000 in cash and $9,000 drawn on a U.S. bank from profits
of ``the Enterprise,'' the maze of companies and secret Swiss bank
accounts Secord and his business partner Albert Hakim used in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Hakim is charged with two counts involving gratuities that were
to be paid to North as well as alleged conspiracy, government theft
and wire fraud.
   Secord could face up to five years in prison on the false
statement plea. The judge, who asked both sides for court filings
on whether maximum fines applicable under the law are $10,000 or
$250,000, set no date for sentencing.
   To date, four people including Secord have pleaded guilty to
various crimes in the Iran-Contra affair. North is appealing his
jury conviction of three felonies and trials are pending for
Poindexter, Secord's business partner Hakim and former CIA station
chief Joseph Fernandez.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
