<DOCNO> AP891109-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Speaker-Intelligence     11-09 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Speaker-Intelligence,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Moving to Legitimize Intelligence Briefings to Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After technically violating its own rules for
years, the House is moving to give its speaker full access to the
nation's most sensitive secrets in files and hearings of the House
Intelligence Committee.
   Under House rules, no classified information can be given to
anyone who is not a member of the intelligence panel without a vote
of the committee and without a record being kept of the information
and to whom it is given.
   But over the years, speakers of the House _ who are not members
of the committee _ have apparently been given informal briefings on
government secrets, said Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the senior
Republican on the committee.
   ``Of course, because those rules were not adhered to, few
members of the committee were aware of some of these instances, and
perhaps no one knows how many times this has occurred,'' Hyde said
in testimony Tuesday before the Rules Committee.
   The Rules panel moved to change the rules and give House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and his successors blanket access to the
Intelligence Committee's business. The matter is expected to come
before the full House next week.
   Hyde said he favors the rules change, which has been proposed by
committee Chairman Anthony Beilenson, D-Calif.
   The issue was given prominence last year when former Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, disclosed to reporters that the Central
Intelligence Agency had sought to foment civil unrest in Nicaragua
to undermine the political stability of the leftist Sandinista
government.
   Sources later said that the information had come to the
Intelligence Committee and had been relayed to Wright through an
informal briefing.
   The matter has arisen again in connection with the publication
of a new book on Wright, ``The Ambition and the Power,'' by
Washington writer John Barry, which is due in bookstores this
month. The book refers to a Nicaraguan political assessment of
Congress, intercepted by U.S. intelligence and disclosed to the
House Intelligence Committee.
   The book asserts that Wright learned of the document in a
briefing from Rep. Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, then the chairman of the
intelligence panel.
   Hyde mentioned the passage from the book when he testified
before the Rules Committee and argued for additional changes to
toughen security. His suggestions included shrinking the committee
from its current 19 members to 13, requiring members and staff to
take a secrecy oath, and requiring both members and staff to
undergo security clearances.
   All of Hyde's suggested changes were rejected by the panel,
mostly along party lines.
   Foley, who took an active interest in intelligence matters when
he was a member of the panel as House majority leader, ran into
problems when he sought to continue his contacts with the committee
after he succeeded Wright as speaker earlier this year.
   Republican members objected that a Foley staff member, Michael
J. O'Neil, was being given full access to intelligence information
and feared it would lead to other requests for access outside of
House rules.
   ``I think the speaker has a constitutional right to any
information that is in the possession of any member of Congress or
any committee of Congress,'' Foley said Tuesday. He said he
believed when he was a member of the panel that it was his
obligation to provide Wright with any information he requested.
   ``If there is any member of Congress who should be fully
informed on matters within the purview of the Intelligence
Committee, it is the speaker, first,'' Foley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
