<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-09 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while the key barometer on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
recovered from its early setback and rose.
   The dollar closed at 142.70 yen, down 0.27 yen from Wednesday's
close of 142.97 yen. It started trading higher at 143.33 yen and
ranged between 142.67 yen and 143.33 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell
slightly during morning trading, made up its losses and gained
61.83 points, or 0.17 percent, finishing the day at 35,657.42.
   Dealers said the index started to recover when foreign
securities firms bought spot issues for option trading. Thursday
was the last day for trading November options.
   An estimated 800 million shares changed hands on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's first section.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate moved nervously due to
uncertainties over U.S. monetary policy after the currency's higher
start, traders said.
   The rate will move tightly but nervously ahead of a rescheduled
auction of U.S. Treasury securities, a dealer from the Bank of
Tokyo said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Treasury Department Wednesday rescheduled a quarterly
auction of $56 billion in securities to prevent the government from
running out of cash before it raised the federal debt limit.
</TEXT>
