<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChildCare     11-09 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Split Over Use of Vouchers for Child Care Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new debate over the use of vouchers for
children's programs is ensnarling a last-ditch effort by House and
Senate negotiators to salvage a child care bill before Congress
adjourns this year.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, insisted Wednesday that states be
allowed to issue vouchers to parents for both a new preschool
education program and new before- and after-school care services
that would be established in the legislation.
   Hatch, who has encountered wrath from the Bush administration
and conservative groups for joining with liberals on child care
standards, also wants governors to have more discretion on how the
new money is spent.
   ``This is it for child care,'' he told House negotiators. ``If
we can't put this together, then it's going to go down the drain.''
   The vouchers, which are supported by the administration, would
effectively allow a portion of the new aid to flow through parents
to churches and parochial schools which provide child care services.
   Most liberal Democrats, with support from unionized teachers and
other public employees, want the money to instead go directly to
care providers. They succeeded in getting a large portion of the
funds in both Senate and House versions devoted to making public
schools become day care centers for so-called ``latchkey'' children
of working parents.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., an adamant opponent of
vouchers, reluctantly agreed to allow a limited use of them in
subsidizing only day care services for pre-kindergarten children
and ``no one else.''
   Both the House and Senate have approved separate measures to
double the $1.5 billion to $2 billion now spent annually on direct
subsidies for child care services. They also would provide $11
billion to $13.5 billion in new tax credits over the next five
years to low-income families with children and require states to
regulate care providers.
   But the Senate version would give governors much more discretion
than the House measure on how the new direct aid is spent. It would
also allow them to dedicate a portion of the funds for issuing
vouchers that parents could use to pay the care provider of their
choice.
   The House version has no provision for vouchers. But upon
passing the bill last month, Democratic House leaders instructed
their negotiators to accept a limited use of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
