<FIRST>r w PM-OverseasAmericans 1stLd-Writethru a0444 11-09 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overseas Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Abroad Complain of Double Taxation Without Representation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores dropped material at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American citizens living and working abroad
say they are unfairly taxed and unjustly deprived of many benefits
available to all other Americans, including representation in
Congress.
   House members, in response, are setting up an unofficial
Congressional Task Force on Overseas Americans to provide a forum
to air the complaints.
   Andrew P. Sundberg, director of American Citizens Abroad and a
resident of Geneva, Switzerland, told a House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Wednesday that U.S. citizens living overseas could
be a great asset to their native land.
   ``And yet, in many ways, we find that the U.S. government is at
war with those of us who live abroad, and it is a war which we are
losing,'' he said.
   ``We view our overseas citizens as a threat, and as a liability
that needs to be carefully controlled,'' Sundberg told the
international operations subcommittee.
   Sundberg and other witnesses complained the United States is the
only country which taxes its citizens on income earned abroad,
exposing them to double taxation since they are also subject to the
tax codes of the countries in which they work.
   He said that such countries as West Germany, France and Japan
provide schools for their citizens living in other countries, but
the United States does not.
   Sundberg noted France also allows overseas citizens to
participate in the nation's legislative process, setting aside 12
seats in the French Senate for members elected by the overseas
French community.
   ``Many federal programs do not reach beyond the water's edge,''
Sundberg said, contending more than 100,000 Americans abroad are
denied Medicare benefits even though they have paid for them
through their taxes.
   He said there is a health benefit available to veterans, but it
cuts off at age 65 because Medicare is supposed to start.
   ``It doesn't overseas,'' Sundberg said, noting the health
benefits for veterans terminate anyway.
   Sundberg also said a provision of U.S. law cuts off monthly
supplemental Social Security benefits for people who live outside
the United States for more than 30 consecutive days.
   And he said children born to Americans living abroad are often
denied U.S. citizenship in their own right.
   Sundberg endorsed legislation introduced earlier this year by
Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., to permit Americans residing overseas
to be represented in Congress by a non-voting delegate to the House
of Representatives.
   He also endorsed bills introduced by Alexander to expand the
types of income earned abroad which may be excluded from U.S. taxes
and to make it easier for Americans abroad to pass on their U.S.
citizenship to their children.
   Witnesses for other organizations, including the American
Chambers of Commerce Abroad, contended that improving the tax
status of overseas Americans would help reduce the U.S. trade
deficit by making American companies more competitive with their
overseas rivals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gartner-VOA     11-09 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gartner-VOA,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>News Executive Wages Battle Against Voice of America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC News President Michael G. Gartner says his
``passion for openness'' drove him to wage an expensive,
little-publicized legal battle against the Voice of America, the
government's radio station.
   As a result, Gartner says VOA has changed its policies, giving
Americans more access to editorial material it broadcasts in 43
languages around the world. The Voice's charter prohibits it from
broadcasting inside the United States.
   ``They've changed their position on three fundamental issues,''
said Gartner, who built a file a foot thick in a fight that began
in the early 1980s when Gartner was editor of The Des Moines
Register and Tribune.
   ``I think that means there is more freedom of the press in this
country and I'm intensely interested in that,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   VOA officials challenge Gartner's contention they've shifted
positions, but acknowledge they have taken steps to ensure VOA
employees properly implement existing policies.
   Gartner was drawn into the case by Gil Cranberg, the Register's
former editorial page editor. Cranberg thought it would be
interesting to see what kind of editorials VOA was sending abroad
over the airwaves.
   When a Register staffer went to check the editorials, he ran
into ``severe obstacles,'' recalled Cranberg, now a journalism
professor at the University of Iowa. ``We were told they
(editorials) could not be disseminated.''
   Cranberg told his boss about the situation. ``Mike was pretty
incensed,'' he said.
   After years of trying to get the policy changed, Gartner filed a
lawsuit against the U.S. Information Agency _ VOA's parent _ in
June 1988 in Des Moines' federal court.
   The lawsuit was filed in Iowa because Gartner, a lawyer, also is
editor and co-owner of The Daily Tribune in Ames, Iowa, a newspaper
with a circulation of about 10,500.
   Although Judge Donald E. O'Brien dismissed the lawsuit last
month, Gartner said ``a funny thing happened on the way to the
ruling.'' Namely, the VOA now allows the following, he said.
   _Americans may publish any information they receive from VOA.
Only USIA employees are barred from disseminating the information.
   _The general public, not just special interest groups like
reporters, members of Congress and historians, is allowed access to
VOA materials, such as editorials.
   _Anyone can copy the information, although they aren't allowed
to photocopy it.
   Summing up the changes, Gartner said: ``One, is I can print it;
two, is the average guy can look at it, and three, is any of us can
copy, and that's a big, big change in my view.''
   Alberto Mora, VOA's general counsel, disputed Gartner's
statements. ``In general, that's not true. ... The court points to
no evidence that we've changed any interpretation of the statute,''
he said.
   Mora said, however, that Gartner may have received some
``confusing sorts of statements'' about policies from lower-level
employees. Gartner said the Voice is simply ``diplomatically
defending their change of position.''
   Meantime, Gartner said he considers his effort well worth his
time and money. Joining Gartner in the lawsuit were Ralph
Rosenberg, an Iowa state representative, and Partnership
Independent Press Inc., the Daily Tribune's parent company.
   ``I have this passion for openness and for freedom of speech and
for democracy,'' said Gartner, who became president of NBC News in
August 1988.
   While battles have been won, the war is not over.
   Gartner intends to push Congress to change VOA's legislation so
the public may photocopy editorials, instead of having to copy them
by hand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-PollProblems     11-09 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll Problems,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Election Poll Problems: Did Some Voters Lie?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Elections Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Closer-than-predicted margins in Virginia's
gubernatorial election and New York's mayoral contest may have a
simple explanation, some pollsters say: Survey respondents lied.
   That could explain why black candidates in the two races ran
less well Tuesday than expected. The theory is that voters who
opposed them hesitated to say so for fear of appearing bigoted.
   It even has a name: ``The Bradley effect,'' for Los Angeles
Mayor Tom Bradley, a black Democrat who led in the polls in his
1982 race for governor only to lose narrowly to his white opponent,
George Deukmejian.
   ``I think a lot of people cast their votes on race, and it's
something that's not easily measured by polls,'' pollster Brad
Coker said Wednesday. ``People are not going to freely admit
they're racists to strangers.''
   In unofficial returns, black Democrat L. Douglas Wilder led
white Republican J. Marshall Coleman by about 5,500 votes for
governor of Virginia, and black Democrat David Dinkins won New
York's mayoralty by just 2 points.
   Both led by greater margins in pre-election surveys, and even in
surveys of voters leaving their polling places Tuesday.
   Did some of those voters lie to the pollsters?
   ``You bet,'' said Steve Shaw, poll director for Media General
Inc. in Richmond, Va. ``There's a socially acceptable answer that
some people feel they should give. But when it comes down to making
a decision, they tend to vote using other criteria.''
   Other pollsters argue that the answers are more complex _ and
that most pre-election polls were not that far off. In Virginia,
the last three polls before the election put Wilder's support at 45
percent, 52 percent and 48 _ not that far from the roughly 50
percent he received.
   What they understated was Coleman's support, estimated at 36, 41
and 44 percent respectively; he also received about 50 percent in
the end.
   In New York, similarly, Dinkins had 51 percent in a final
pre-election poll by The Gallup Organization, about what he
received. White Republican Rudolph W. Giuliani, however, was polled
at 37 percent; he got 48 percent.
   ``The undecideds, or the people who weren't saying, broke
heavily for the Republican,'' said Gallup pollster Larry Hugick.
   Those people, almost all of them whites, may have been
uncomfortable saying they opposed the black candidate, Hugick said.
But he also raised another possibility: ``They truly hadn't made up
their minds.''
   Indeed, in many previous elections pitting a black and a white,
``the people who are undecided ... have traditionally moved toward
the white candidate,'' said Kathleen A. Frankovic, a pollster at
CBS News. If polls on Tuesday's election reflected that, she
suggested, they would have been near the mark.
   ``I think that people are choosing to ascribe an easy
explanation, i.e., lying, when there other methodological
explanations available,'' Frankovic said. ``They're just harder to
write about, harder to talk about, and the words are longer.''
   Still, Coker, who polled in Virginia, saw no other explanation
for his exit poll result Tuesday: It found a 55-45 percent victory
for Wilder among voters leaving their polling places, far
overstating the black candidate's showing and understating the
white's. But on two other races, in which there were no black
candidates, Coker's results proved almost exactly correct.
   ``The history of exit polling and other polling has been that
when there's no racial issue involved, they're pretty accurate.
When there is, you're never quite sure,'' said Coker. ``You can
only go with what the people tell you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
