<FIRST>r i PM-Haiti     11-09 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haiti,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haiti Paralyzed By Strike Protesting Alleged Torture Of Opposition
Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti, (AP) _ Most businesses and schools
remained closed on the second day of a widely observed 48-hour
strike to protest the arrest and apparent being in police custody
of three opposition leaders.
   Transportation in Port-au-Prince and all other major cities in
Haiti was paralyzed Wednesday, the second day of the strike.
Government trucks providing free transportation were virtually
empty.
   Almost all the estimated 15,000 factory workers at the
industrial park, on the north side of this city of 1 million, did
not report to work.
   No violence was reported.
   ``The success of the strike will give the army food for thought.
Human rights and the constitution have got to be respected,''
conservative politician Francois Latortue said in an interview.
   The goverment on Nov. 2 accused Jean-Auguste Mesyeux, co-leader
of Haiti's largest union; Evans Paul and Etienne Marino of
conspiring to assassinate Haitian ruler Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril and
superior officers and to blow up the presidential palace.
   The three were displayed on state television that night with
swollen faces, bandaged heads and bloodied shirts _ apparently
resulting from beatings.
   ``The aim of their appearance on television was probably to
terrorize the population,'' said Latortue, a former justice
minister and presidential candidate.
   ``We thought we had put an end to such police brutality in
1986'' when dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled into exile in
France, he said.
   Outraged by the television display, nearly 100 human rights,
political, civic and neighborhood groups rallied to the strike
called by Mesyeux's union, the Autonomous Central of Haitian
Workers.
   ``It is a strike of the revolted conscience,'' Communist Party
leader Rene Theodore said.
   ``Avril has no credibility left to govern with. He must release
the three prisoners, and he must resign,'' said conservative
political leader Louis Dejoie.
   Haiti's bishops, in a statement broadcast by the Roman Catholic
Church-owned Radio Soleil Tuesday night, expressed shocked at the
resurgence of police brutality and urged respect for human rights.
   The three men began a hunger strike at the National Penitentiary
Monday. Lawyers and relatives have been refused permission to visit
them, private Radio Haiti Inter said.
   Paul is leader of the Confederation for Democratic Unity party
and Marino is a member of the Popular Organization of September 17,
which was inspired by the September 1988 soldiers' coup that ousted
Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and brought Avril to power.
   The three were arrested Nov. 1, allegedly in possession of
weapons and explosives, a day after co-signing a communique of the
National Assembly, a coalition of 20 leftist and conservative
groups, calling for a month of anti-government marches.
</TEXT>
