<FIRST>r i PM-Poland'sGermans     11-09 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland's Germans,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Germans Seeking Greater Recognition From Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GORA SW. ANNY, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large sign lists all Masses in
Polish, but the hundreds of ethnic Germans headed for the
mountain-top monastery in this former German region are coming to
pray in their mother tongue.
   Franciscan monks have allowed celebration of Sunday Mass in
German since June, and word has spread quickly among the thousands
of ethnic Germans scattered throughout southwestern Poland.
   Although gasoline is in short supply, worshipers often drive
more than an hour each Sunday to gather at one of the few churches
in Poland to offer services in German.
   A tightly-knit community, ethnic Germans in Poland are estimated
by the International Red Cross to number 80,000. Most are
concentrated in the former German territories of Silesia and East
Prussia.
   Ethnic Germans had hoped for a large turnout on Sunday, when
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany was to attend a
German-language Mass at the Mount St. Ann monastery, known in
German as Annaberg.
   The trip to the monastery was scratched, however, because the
government was uncomfortable over a visit to the area, the site of
a fierce battle in 1921 between Polish and German partisans over
whether the area would go to Poland or Germany.
   Polish-German relations in the region have been strained since
the Nazi invasion of Poland in 1939, and Warsaw authorities
apparently feared a visit by Kohl, who arrived in the country today
for a five-day visit, would stir ethnic tensions.
   More than one-third of present-day Poland was formerly German
territory, and millions of Germans were expelled after the regions
were awarded to Poland after the war.
   An alternate site for Kohl to meet ethnic Germans was found at
Krzyzowa, known as Kreisau in German, a town where opponents of
Hitler met to map out resistance plans.
   Some of the Kreisau Circle members were later involved in the
abortive July 20, 1944, plot to kill Hitler at an East Prussian
bunker now located in northern Poland.
   Ethnic Germans blamed the Polish government for conflict over a
visit to Gora Sw. Anny and say they plan to make a strong showing
by organizing buses for the open-air Mass at Krzyzowa.
   About 500 people who attended Mass in German on Sunday were
urged by the priest, a Franciscan friar, to go to Krzyzowa and then
provided with detailed instructions on how to get there.
   ``The Poles are afraid of us. We don't want to hurt the Poles
but we want to feel German,'' said Richard Urban, one of the
leaders of the German Friendship Circle. The group maintains close
links with groups of Silesians in West Germany.
   As long as they can prove German heritage, ethnic Germans in
Poland can automatically receive West German citizenship if they
decide to emigrate. But the Germans at Gora Sw. Anny said they want
to remain in Poland.
   ``We want to stay here. We have been here for 600 years. This is
our homeland,'' said Urban. But he added: ``We want our children to
learn German and we want our own schools and churches.''
   All prayer books and guides sold at the monastery are in Polish.
But down near the parking lot, one elderly German-speaker did a
brisk business selling copies of the day's service and hymns in
German for about 65 cents.
   Like many other social and ethnic groups, the German minority
was forbidden to form independent associations under the previous
Communist government. That leadership has been replaced with a
Solidarity-led government.
   Ethnic Germans benefited from a law passed earlier this year
allowing the official registration of independent groups. At least
two associations for the promotion of German culture have been
formed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
