<DOCNO> AP891109-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-People-Koch     11-09 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Koch,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Mayor Koch to Have News Program After Leaving Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, who's talked freely and
for free while in office, has lined up another paying position to
offer his words.
   On Wednesday, he signed with WCBS-TV as a local commentator and
weekly news show host. Besides the new TV gigs, Koch already has
agreed to do a morning radio spot, lecture on urban affairs at New
York University and undertake a national speaking tour.
   ``Throughout his career, Ed Koch has never been at a loss for
words,'' said Roger Coloff, WCBS' president-general manager. ``In
this new role ... he will continue to speak out about issues of
interest to our viewers.''
   He'll do a Sunday morning news program and regular commentary on
the station's 5 p.m. weekday newscasts, Coloff said.
   Koch is slated to make his debut the week of Jan. 8, one week
after he leaves Gracie Mansion. Details of the mayor's contract
were not announced, but Koch observed recently that hearing him
speak once he leaves City Hall will no longer be free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
