<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abduction-Kids'Letters     11-09 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abduction-Kids' Letters,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Boy's Neighbors Send Letters to Other Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAYNESVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Middle school students near the town
where an 11-year-old boy was abducted last month are sending
letters to students around the country asking for help in finding
him.
   ``If somebody would see it, and they might see Jacob...'' said
11-year-old David Brinkman. ``They might be able to alert
somebody,'' added Cary Gottwald, 13.
   Paynesville is 30 miles southwest of St. Jospeh, the town of
3,000 people where Jacob Wetterling was kidnapped Oct. 22 while
riding bikes with two friends.
   Paynesville Middle School Principal Mike Lund said some children
are afraid to go outside alone and others have told of nightmares.
   ``We had a lot of our middle school students really concerned
much more than expected. We were surprised by how affected they
were,'' Lund said.
   On Monday and Tuesday, students made white yarn bracelets that
they will distribute to remind people to look for Jacob. The
children gethered in the gym Wednesday and formed circles, held
hands, and listened to a girls' choir sing ``Somewhere Out There.''
   Many of the children tied white ribbons around their ankles, or
wore white clothing. Some carried signs or wore T-shirts saying
``Jacob's Hope.''
   ``I think it helps get rid of some of that tension and fear,''
Lund said. ``I think it helps them feel they are doing something
positive for Jacob.''
   Each of the 430 fifth, sixth, seventh, and eighth graders at the
school wrote a letter to a middle school somewhere in the nation.
   The main body of each letter was already typed. Students filled
in information about themselves and included pictures of Jacob and
of a van that may be involved in the abduction.
   ``We are concerned that as each day goes by, Jacob's abductor
may be taking him further and further from his home,'' the letter
says. ``Each of the students in our school is trying to help out by
sending these flyers to schools in other areas of the United
States.''
</TEXT>
