<DOCNO> AP891109-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-09 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index gained
slightly after nervous ups and downs today, while the dollar fell
against the Japanese yen for the second consecutive day.
   The dollar closed at 142.70 yen, down 0.27 yen from Wednesday's
close of 142.97 yen. It opened at 143.33 yen and ranged between
142.67 yen and 143.33 yen. The dollar fell by 0.66 yen on Wednesday.
   On Thursday, it was falling on news that U.S. banks had cut
their prime lending rate, currency traders said. Lower interest
rates tend to make the dollar less attractive to foreign investors.
   ``Despite the narrowing interest rate gap between Japan and the
United States, the dollar has been bullish because of persistent
demand among Japanese investors,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a Daiwa
Bank trader.
   ``That's mainly because investors have been buying the U.S.
money prior to the auction of U.S. Treasury securities,'' he said.
   An estimated $6.71 billion changed hands today, down from
Wednesday's $7.76 billion.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained
61.83 points, or 0.17 percent, closing at 35,657.42.
   The index fell in the morning and slipped further in the early
afternoon as investors, including Solomon Brothers, sold spot
issues for technical adjustments, said Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer
with New Japan Securities Co.
   The Nikkei rose back when investors started to pick up issues
whose prices had fallen, he said.
   Buying from foreign securities firms, mainly Goldman Sachs and
Morgan Stanley, for option trading also boosted the index, Nomura
said. Today was the last day for November options.
   ``But today's major players were securities dealers, who tend to
buy and sell back issues frequently according to the fluctuation in
the index,'' Nomura said.
   ``That's why the Nikkei went up and down so nervously,'' he said.
   Trading was fairly active, with first section volume estimated
at 800 million shares, unchanged from the previous day.
   Among gainers were shipbuilding, electric power plant and steel
issues.
</TEXT>
