<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     11-09 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Envoy Getting Surplus VA Equipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's special envoy to Vietnam is
being allowed to have surplus medical equipment from the Veterans
Department for use in Vietnam.
   Don Smith, a Veterans Department spokesman, said Wednesday night
that all equipment turned over to retired Army Gen. John Vessey was
first offered to installations throughout the Veterans Department
system and to other government agencies.
   Two years ago, the United States agreed to ease the way for
private groups with medical expertise to help Vietnamese war
victims.
   That agreement was in return for Hanoi's help on resolving the
question of what happened to missing U.S. servicemen and recovering
remains of those killed in the war. There are 2,331 U.S. servicemen
unaccounted for, according to the Defense Department.
   ``If this can help Gen. Vessey make progress on the MIA issue, I
can't imagine the most hard-bitten Vietnam Veteran having a problem
with it,'' Smith said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Computer Chip Industry Executive Raps Foreign Competitors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is being warned that the U.S.
semiconductor industry is falling prey to foreign competitors
determined to gain a choke hold on the materials and equipment
needed to make computer chips.
   Robert Noyes, chief executive officer of Sematech, said
Wednesday that foreign competitors are ``determined to control the
supply lines, the manufacturing and the end products.'' He did not
name specific competitors.
   Noyes told a joint hearing of two House Science subcommittees
that while the United States has a 40 percent share of the
worldwide semiconductor market, its hold on the markets for
critical equipment and materials is below that.
   Sematech is a government-supported consortium of 14 companies,
established two years ago to help the U.S. computer chip industry
compete in the world market. Congress gave Sematech $100 million in
each of the last two years, and committees in both houses have
recommended paying the same amount for 1990.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Keep Ban on Courtroom TVs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has decided to continue its
ban on television cameras in its courtroom, but a lawyer for news
organizations is hopeful the justices will eventually change their
mind.
   ``It won't happen now. But I hope it will happen one day,'' said
Timothy B. Dyk, a lawyer representing a group of news
organizations. Dyk received an Oct. 27 letter from Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist that said a majority of the court's nine
members remain opposed to cameras in their courtroom.
   Rehnquist's letter did not offer any explanation for the
justices' decision, nor did it specify which members opposed
cameras in the court.
   But court sources have said some justices were turned against TV
coverage by the televised Senate Judiciary Committee hearings on
Robert H. Bork's nomination to the Supreme Court. His nomination
was rejected by the Senate.
</TEXT>
