<FIRST>r w PM-EnergyNominee     11-09 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Nominee,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nuclear Executive Tapped for Key Waste Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will nominate John Bartlett, a
former executive of a Massachusetts-based government contractor, to
manage the Energy Department's high-level nuclear waste program,
congressional and other sources said.
   The selection comes amid growing criticism on Capitol Hill of
delays in the department's efforts to build a permanent dump for
radioactive waste from nuclear power plants.
   Bush is expected to nominate Bartlett for the waste job later
this month, the sources said Wednesday, speaking on condition they
not be identified. If confirmed, Bartlett would fill a void in the
waste program that has plagued the Energy Department for two years.
   The current head of the waste management office, Sam Rousso,
holds the job on an interim basis.
   Bartlett would become a central figure in the federal
government's bitter struggle with Nevada over efforts to build the
nation's first permanent dump for high-level nuclear waste.
   Nevada Gov. Bob Miller has blocked the department's efforts to
begin studying Yucca Mountain, about 100 miles northwest of Las
Vegas, as the only candidate site for the proposed underground
dump. The standoff, with other problems, is expected to force
Watkins to announce a further delay in the target date for opening
a permanent waste dump. The current target date is 2003.
   Watkins is drawing increasing criticism on Capitol Hill for his
failure to break the waste impasse.
   In a letter released earlier this week, four influential House
members told Watkins they were ``appalled'' the waste management
office has been without a director for two years and that Watkins
appeared to be planning major changes in the waste program without
consulting Congress.
   The letter, dated Oct. 17, was signed by Reps. John D. Dingell,
D-Mich.; Morris K. Udall, D-Ariz.; James V. Hansen, R-Utah; and
Philip R. Sharp, D-Ind.
   Sources who declined to be identified said Watkins has decided
to bring Bartlett into the department as a special adviser until
routine FBI background checks are completed and he is confirmed by
the Senate.
   Both the White House and the department declined to confirm the
Bartlett selection, saying there would be no comment until a
nominee was announced.
   The company at which Bartlett had worked for the last decade,
The Analytic Sciences Corp. is an engineering contractor to various
government agencies, including the Energy Department. Bartlett was
manager of the company's office of nuclear engineering until he
quit earlier this fall, company officials said.
   The company declined to specify the work it had performed for
the Energy Department. Available department records list five
contracts _ all expired _ with Bartlett's former employer, but they
include no description of the work done.
   The total value of the contracts was $2.2 million. The most
recent one, valued at $491,840, was retired June 30, according to
the department records.
   Jim Kelly, director of business development at the Reading,
Mass.-based company, said in a telephone interview Wednesday he
could not comment on Bartlett's work there beyond confirming that
he had quit and that ``he did a good job for us.''
   Efforts to reach Bartlett this week were unsuccessful. In a
telephone interview last month, Bartlett said he had discussed the
waste job with Watkins and White House officials but that he had
been given no firm commitments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
