<DOCNO> AP891109-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     11-09 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Bans Testimony on Victim's Record in Miami Riot Shooting Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has banned testimony about the victim's
criminal record in the case of a Miami officer who shot and killed
a black motorcyclist, sparking three days of racial disturbances.
   Dade County Judge Joseph Farina ruled Wednesday that Clement
Lloyd's previous drug convictions, and defense contentions that he
was collecting drug proceeds the day of his death, were irrelevant
to the case.
   Roy Black, an attorney for suspended Miami officer William
Lozano, said the ruling hurt his effort to defend the 30-year-old
policeman against manslaughter charges. The defense wanted to show
Lloyd was desperate and drugged enough to try to run over Lozano.
   ``He's excluded our entire defense,'' Black said. ``Lloyd was a
drug dealer out collecting his profits; he didn't want to be
stopped.''
   Farina did allow evidence that Lloyd, 23, had 5.5 grams of
marijuana and $1,500 dollars in cash on him at the time of the
shooting. In his blood, Lloyd had alcohol and high levels of THC,
the active ingredient in marijuana _ evidence which also can be
introduced in court.
   The judge banned any mention of similar evidence concerning
Allan Blanchard, 24, Lloyd's passenger, who died when the motorcyle
crashed after the shooting.
   Lozano faces two manslaughter counts in the deaths.
   During the hearing, prosecutors told the judge the defense
should not be allowed to put Lloyd and Blanchard, both black, on
trial instead of Lozano.
   Lead prosecutor John Hogan remained cautious about his victory
in pretrial motions. ``We're happy with some of them, unhappy with
others,'' Hogan said. ``But obviously we won some motions that were
important to us.''
   Farina allowed the prosecution to use testimony about Miami city
police regulations to prove Lozano acted negligently and
unprofessionally when he shot and killed Lloyd on Jan. 16.
   Those regulations are much more restrictive than Florida's
``fleeing felon'' law, which the defense argued should be the
standard to judge the officer.
   Lozano fired one shot, hitting Lloyd in the head and killing
him, as the motorcyclist sped away from another officer. Lozano
contends the motorcycle was heading straight at him. Prosecutors
say Miami police policy dictated that he should get out of the way,
and should not have fired at a moving vehicle.
   In the riot that followed the shooting, one person was killed,
11 were wounded by gunfire and 13 buildings were burned down in
predominantly black neighborhoods.
   The defense on Wednesday also sought to introduce statements
contending the prosecution was racially and politically motivated,
and that some prosecutors had privately acknowledged that. But the
judge denied that testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
