<FIRST>r a PM-HeraldCenter     11-09 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Herald Center,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Center With Marcos Ties Sold at Auction for $25 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Manhattan shopping mall that attracted
interest from U.S. and Filipino prosecutors for its ties to former
Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos drew only one bidder at a
foreclosure auction.
   Real estate developer Morris Bailey led a group of investors who
bought Herald Center, a 10-story vertical mall across the street
from Macy's flagship store, for the minimum bid of $25 million
Wednesday.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, allegedly bought the mall and three
other Manhattan properties with money looted from their homeland's
treasury.
   Marcos died in exile in Hawaii in September, leaving his wife to
face numerous lawsuits in the United States and Philippines,
including a criminal indictment.
   The court-appointed special master of the auction, Stephen
Estroff, said he was disappointed that more bidders did not come
forward.
   ``Retailing in Manhattan is undergoing stress,'' Estroff said.
   Herald Center has suffered from poor business in recent years,
with retail and restaurant outlets dropping from a high of 70 to
the current 45 tenants.
   But Bailey was optimistic about its future.
   ``Herald Center is the premier retail location in the country
today,'' he said. ``If properly directed, we are going to have some
good response.''
   Bailey said his group would announce its plans for the center
soon.
   The auction of Herald Center was part of a foreclosure action by
the property's mortgage holder, Security Pacific Mortgage and Real
Services. Money from the sale will go toward a $58.65 million
foreclosure judgment awarded Security Pacific by U.S. District
Judge Pierre Leval.
   Leval, who presides over one of the Philippine lawsuits, allowed
the sale of three of the buildings and said any proceeds left over
would be held by the court pending the outcome of the litigation.
   One of the other buildings, 40 Wall St., was sold for $108.6
million at auction in August but the sale collapsed when the buyers
failed raise the money by the Oct. 10 closing date. That building
will be re-auctioned Monday.
   An auction date has not been set yet for a third property.
Foreclosure proceedings are under way for the fourth property and a
sale is expected soon.
</TEXT>
