<SECOND>PM-Pakistani Plot,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Attack Claims That Drug Defendant Tied to Zia Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose defense hinges on his
claim of involvement in a plot to kill Pakistan's former leader is
an internationally known heroin dealer trying to avoid prison,
prosecutors said.
   ``You would create any sort of story. You would say anything,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Kevin O'Regan said Wednesday as he began
cross-examining Mushtaq Malik.
   The 41-year-old defendant has testified that his involvement
with an accused drug dealer was merely an effort to track down a
man who double-crossed him in a plot kill Pakistani President Gen.
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq. The plot, Malik has said, was orchestrated by
officials in the Pakistan People's Party, whose current leader is
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto.
   Zia died in a mysterious plane crash Aug. 17, 1988. A Pakistani
official has denied the assassination plot.
   O'Regan reeled off a string of alleged heroin smuggling acts in
which he said Malik was involved, including a ``double-dipping''
scheme with a German official in which Malik dealt heroin and then
tipped off the official to the shipment, thereby reaping the sale
and reward.
   Malik called the allegations baseless.
   The defendant appeared to be at odds with his attorney, Stephen
Ferrarone, frequently telling the defense attorney to sit down when
he tried to raise objections to the prosecutor's cross-examination.
   Malik, who said he's of royal blood and known as ``The Black
Prince'' in Pakistan, has stopped short of saying he was involved
in the plane crash that killed Zia.
   Bashir Riaz, an adviser to Bhutto, has told The Associated Press
that Malik's claim of an assassination plot was ``another attempt
by the drug mafia to discredit the government because of Benazir
Bhutto's campaign against the drug trade.''
   Pakistani officials, including those who served Zia, at first
blamed the plane crash on Soviet and Afghan agents operating
against Pakistan and the United States for their support of Afghan
Mujahedeen. After Bhutto came to power, Zia's son, Ejaz ul-Haq, and
some opposition right-wingers blamed her ruling Pakistan People's
Party.
   Malik in early 1985 was convicted in Pakistan and served more
than two years in prison for heroin trafficking. He said those
charges were politically motivated.
</TEXT>
