<DOCNO> AP891109-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-RedWolves     11-09 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Red Wolves,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hugo May Be to Blame for Death of Rare Wolf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stress or injury from Hurricane Hugo
probably contributed to the death of the sole male red wolf in a
wildlife refuge, but four pups of the endangered species appear
healthy, the refuge manager said.
   The 7-year-old wolf had been released on Bulls Island, part of
the Cape Romain National Wildlife Refuge on the Atlantic coast,
with a female adult in an attempt to reintroduce the species, which
had become extinct in the wild.
   The male adult's carcass was discovered Saturday, about three
weeks after the animal died, said George R. Garris, the refuge
manager.
   ``We're not sure of the cause,'' Garris said. ``He probably
sustained injury during Hugo or the stress was too much for him.''
   The carcass was not found earlier because trees felled by Hugo
on Sept. 21 blocked island roads until last week. The hurricane,
with 135 mph winds, came ashore at Charleston, about 20 miles
southwest of Bulls Island.
   The four 6-month-old female pups appear healthy, and could be
transferred to Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge in North
Carolina within several months, once they learn hunting techniques,
Garris said. A Cape Romain employee is tracking them and giving
them food.
   Born in a zoo, the male adult and a female adult were released
on Bulls Island in 1987. An alligator killed the female less than a
year later and the male raised their two male pups. The pups later
were transferred to the North Carolina refuge, where they still
live.
   A second female wolf was introduced on Bulls Island last winter.
The pair produced five female offspring in the spring. Days later,
an alligator killed the mother, and one pup later was killed by
another alligator.
   The red wolf once ranged from Texas east to the Atlantic coast
and north to the Ohio Valley, but began disappearing because of
their inability to adapt to changes in the land and predator
control.
   In 1973, after the passage of the Endangered Species Act, the
entire red wolf population in southeast Texas and Louisiana was
captured to prevent its extinction.
   The red wolf is smaller than the grey wolf, with females
weighing 40-60 pounds and males weighing 60-80 pounds.
   The black-footed ferret is the only mammal that is rarer than
the red wolf in the United States.
</TEXT>
