<FIRST>r a PM-Hepatitis-Refugees     11-09 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hepatitis-Refugees,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Urges Hepatitis Vaccine for Babies of Southeast Asia Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies born to refugees from Southeast Asia are at
high risk of catching hepatitis B and should be routinely
vaccinated against the dangerous virus, U.S. health officials
recommended today.
   Long-time carriers of the virus have an increased risk of liver
cancer and chronic liver disease. The younger people are when they
catch the hepatitis virus, the more likely they are to die of these
diseases.
   Since 1975, nearly 1 million people have moved to the United
States from Southeast Asia, where infection with the hepatitis B
virus is extremely common.
   In today's study, doctors from the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control found that the children of Southeast Asian immigrants have
a substantial risk of catching the virus, even if they are free of
it at birth.
   The research, directed by Dr. Adele L. Franks, was published in
the New England Journal of Medicine. It was based on 196 refugee
families with 257 children who were born in the United States.
   The virus is frequently passed from mother to child before
birth. In the families studied, 55 percent of the children born to
mothers with infectious disease had the infection. However, 7
percent of the children whose mothers were free of the infection
also had the virus.
   The researchers concluded that child-to-child transmission was
responsible for at least some of the hepatitis B infections.
   Under current guidelines, vaccination is recommended only for
newborns of mothers with infectious disease. The researcher said
this should be expanded to include all newborn children of refugees
from Southeast Asia.
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Jay H. Hoofnagle of the
National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases
agreed with the proposal.
   ``This advice is sound,'' he wrote, ``and if followed, will
contibute materially to the good health of the children of these
first-generation Americans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
