<DOCNO> AP891109-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BreastCancer     11-09 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Breast Cancer,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Breast Cancer Linked with X-rays During Infancy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exposure to radiation even during infancy can
significantly increase women's risk of breast cancer when they
reach adulthood, a study published today confirms.
   The research was based on a long-term follow-up of women who
were given X-ray therapy shortly after birth for treatment of
enlarged thymus glands. Such treatment was common until the late
1950s, when doctors realized that seemingly enlarged thymuses were
actually normal.
   By age 36, the study found that those who had received the
treatment were nearly four times more likely to get breast cancer
than were sisters who did not receive the radiation.
   The researchers said their work ``suggests that irradiation of
the female breast at a very early age can have harmful effects that
do not appear until many years later.''
   Experts have long recognized that breast tissue is extremely
sensitive to the damaging effects of radiation. Until recently,
they believed that only those who received radiation during
adolescence or adulthood would be harmed. However, recent follow-up
of Japanese girls exposed to radiation from atomic bombs during
World War II found they also had an increased risk of breast cancer
later in life.
   The latest study, directed by Dr. Nancy G. Hildreth of the
University of Rochester School of Medicine and Dentistry, was
published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
   The doctors followed 1,201 women who received X-ray treatment
for enlarged thymuses and 2,469 of their sisters who did not get
radiation. There were 22 cases of breast cancer among the radiation
group and 12 among the sisters.
   Another study in the journal, conducted by Dr. Anthony B. Miller
of the National Cancer Institute of Canada, followed 31,710 who
received repeated diagnostic X-rays for tuberculosis.
   This study found the greatest risk of breast cancer among those
who got the X-rays between ages 10 and 14. The risk fell with
increasing age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
