<FIRST>r a PM-People-Heston     11-09 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Heston,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscar-Winner Cleared for Top-Secret Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Charlton Heston is in demand by
government producers who value his top-secret nuclear weapons
security clearance as much as his Academy Award.
   For six years Heston has held the nation's highest-level
security clearance because of his no-fee work narrating classified
instructional films and videotapes for the government.
   And the actor who claimed the Oscar for best actor in 1959 for
his work in ``Ben Hur'' knows what possessing the top security
clearance means: Keep quiet.
   ``I'm not trying to be dramatically secretive or anything,''
Heston said. ``But I can't get into that.''
   About 28,000 U.S. Department of Energy, Nuclear Regulatory
Commission and defense contractor employees involved in nuclear
weapons programs have the clearance that Heston has, Energy
Department officials said.
   He has worked on at least six highly classified productions,
according to the Energy Department. The latest was a video titled
``Trust but Verify,'' which reportedly showed both Soviet and U.S.
high-tech nuclear weapons.
   Heston, a staunch Republican and former six-term president of
the Screen Actors Guild, says the Energy Department isn't the only
government agency he's worked for, but he won't say what the other
agencies are.
   ``I do work for other agencies from time to time,'' he said.
``Most of the stuff that you do in this area is not designed for
public consumption.''
   The actor's film credits include ``The Ten Commandments,'' ``The
Agony and the Ecstasy,'' and ``Planet of the Apes'' and ``The Three
Musketeers'' series.
</TEXT>
