<FIRST>r i PM-India-Cyclone     11-09 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Cyclone,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Same Storm That Ravaged Thailand Claims At Least 11 Lives in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cyclone battered India's southwestern
coast India today, killing at least 11 people and leaving thousands
homeless as it uprooted trees and blew away hundreds of thatched
huts, news reports said.
   United News of India said the storm ravaged the district of
Nellore, 900 miles south of New Delhi.
   The agency quoted unidentified government officials as saying at
least 11 people were killed in the storm. Further details of damage
were not available because it had cut off communication links, it
said.
   The cyclone blew across the Bay of Bengal after killing at least
169 people in Thailand last week as Typhoon Gay. It crossed the
coast at Nellore, a district of 2.2 million people, at 1:30 a.m.
today, UNI said.
   The news agency said trains in the area were halted after strong
winds blew down trees and damaged railroad tracks.
   Press Trust of India, another news agency, said the military had
been alerted for rescue efforts and people were evacuated from the
coastal regions.
   The storm hit Thailand on Friday, and authorities in Bangkok
said at least 111 people were killed on the mainland and another 58
drowned at sea.
   Another 447 people, mostly fishermen out on the Gulf of
Thailand, have been reported missing.
   A cyclone from the Bay of Bengal left at least 150 people dead
across southern and western India in July.
   In 1977, at least 10,000 people were killed in a cyclone in
Andhra Pradesh.
</TEXT>
