<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms in Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched much of the East Coast today after storms spawned
tornadoes and flooded parts of the Southeast. From the Midwest to
the West Coast, the weather today was expected to be mostly mild
and dry.
   Tornadoes touched down Wednesday evening in Georgia, Alabama and
Mississippi, and rains continued in already flooded parts of
Louisiana. The storm caused two deaths, including a 3-year-old who
was in a mobile home in Pineview, Ga., smashed by a tornado.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 70 mph at Walnut Grove, Miss., and
to near 60 mph near Bastrop, La.
   A tornado touched down near Stonewall, Miss., on Wednesday
night, the National Weather Service said, but no details were
available.
   Two tornadoes hit two counties in southeast Alabama on Wednesday
morning. In Geneva County, a woman was hurt when her mobile home
was tossed into a fish pond.
   More than 7 inches of rain fell in some areas of southeast
Alabama on Wednesday, while 10 inches fell at Florala, Ala., over
parts of Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Rain today reached much of New England, New York, Pennsylvania,
Maryland, Delaware and parts of the South. Rain over Upper Michigan
changed to snow over eastern Minnesota. Snow was scattered over
western Wyoming and south-central Montana, and rain extended along
the northern Pacific Coast.
   Elsewhere today, skies were expected to be clear.
   Temperatures were unseasonably warm Wednesday in the deep South.
High temperature records for the date were set in Beaumont, Texas,
88 degrees; Corpus Christi, Texas, 93; Lake Charles, La., 87;
Meridian, Miss., 84; Monroe, La., 88; San Antonio, Texas, 90;
Shreveport, La. 87, and Brownsville, Texas, where 95 was the
nation's high Wednesday.
   Reports at 3 a.m. EST today:
