<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in early European trading
today, and gold was higher.
   Dealers expressed some surprise that the dollar was holding up
despite a quarter-point drop in the U.S. Federal Fund rate and
recent rate hikes in West Germany.
   According to Michael Scheffler, a trader at Bank of America in
Frankfurt, West Germany, the dollar's strength is related to a
fundamental weakness in the Deutsche mark.
   ``Interest rates don't help against psychology, and the
psychology is still directed against the mark,'' Scheffler said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 142.70 yen, down 0.27 yen from
Wednesday. Later in London, the dollar was still trading at 142.70
yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid morning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8447 West German marks, down from 1.8450
   _1.6173 Swiss francs, up from 1.6170
   _6.2560 French francs, up from 6.2510
   _2.0807 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0805
   _1,348.25 Italian lire, down from 1,349.50
   _$1.1676 Canadian, down from $1.1695
   In London, the pound traded at $1.5866, compared with $1.5860
late Wednesday.
   Gold traded at $387.40 at the mid-morning fixing in London, up
from late Wednesday's price of $384.75.
   In Zurich, the noon price was $387.75 per ounce, up from $384.00
late Wednesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong dropped the equivalent of $1.08 an ounce
today, to close at $386.72.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.28 a troy
ounce, the highest level since Aug. 27, from Wednesday's $5.25 an
ounce.
