<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StarTribune-Guild     11-09 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Star Tribune-Guild,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Star Tribune Guild Gives Lackluster Approval To Six-Year Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Star Tribune newsroom workers averted a
strike by approving a six-year contract, but a union leader called
the new pact a ``rotten deal.''
   The Twin Cities Newspaper Guild approved the pact Wednesday
night, hours after their second strike deadline passed in as many
days. Guild Chairwoman Margaret Zack said the vote was 233-70.
   The contract includes lump-sum bonuses in each of the first
three years, and pay raises of 3.2 percent in the fourth year, 3.1
percent in the fifth year and 3.0 percent in the sixth year, union
officials said.
   Union leaders said they recommended approval because other
unions at the plant were reluctant to support a strike, Many Guild
members feared they would be replaced in a prolonged strike, they
said.
   ``It's a bad deal. It's a rotten deal,'' said Jay Weiner, vice
chair of the workers' negotiating committee.
   ``It simply doesn't meet the needs of people trying to keep
their standard of living intact,'' said Steve Brandt, strike
coordinator for the Minneapolis unit of the Guild.
   John Dennison, vice president of labor relations for the Star
Tribune, said the company succeeded in its goal to freeze wage
scales for three years. But he said the company also ``made an
effort to accommodate some key needs of the Guild.''
   ``Sometimes you have a feeling you didn't get everything you
wanted,'' Dennison said. ``But both sides can walk away with their
head up.''
   For top scale reporters, photographers, copy editors and
district circulation managers, the bonuses will be $2,000 in the
first year, $1,750 in the second and $1,500 in the third, Brandt
and Dennison said.
   The pay raises for top-scale employees will amount to about $26
a week in each of the last three years, they said.
   Weiner said the package averages out to a 1.6 percent annual
increase in pay scales over six years. He called it ``worse by
far'' than the deal struck by Guild employees at the St. Paul
(Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch earlier this year.
   For the first three years of the new pact, top minimum weekly
salaries for Guild members will remain at $315.50 for copy aides;
$742.50 for circulation district managers; $812 for reporters,
photographers, copy editors and promotion personnel; and $895.75
for some editors.
   The Minneapolis unit has been working without a contract since
its three-year pact expired July 31. The unit covers about 300
newsroom employees and about 60 circulation and promotion workers.
</TEXT>
