<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseBudget 1stLd-Writethru a0470 11-09 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Bush Budget Stance a ``Disaster'' for Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes garble in 5th graf, `The automatic ...' and INSERTS 7
grafs of dropped material after 5th graf; picks up 6th graf, `We're in
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats are attacking the Bush
administration's willingness to accept automatic budget cuts that
would force the Defense Department to reduce the nation's armed
forces.
   ``It would be a disaster if Congress and the administration
decide to go over the cliff,'' Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, said Wednesday as Pentagon
officials described the impact of automatic reductions on the four
military branches.
   The 2.1 million active duty armed forces would have to be
reduced by about 229,000 in fiscal 1990 under the cuts, with the
Air Force cut by 80,000, the Navy by 76,000, the Army by 62,000 and
the Marine Corps by 11,000.
   Military contracts for such big-ticket items as the
multiple-warhead MX nuclear missile and the Advanced Tactical
Fighter would also have to be renegotiated, the Pentagon said.
   The automatic budget cuts are necessary because of Congress'
failure to pass a deficit reconciliation bill aimed at complying
with the budget-cutting requirements of the Gramm-Rudman
budget-balancing law.
   President Bush has said he would be willing to live with the
cutbacks in fiscal 1990 rather than accept a budget reconciliation
bill that does not result in real deficit reductions. The president
is seeking $14 billion in cuts; Congress has indicated a $12
billion cut is possible.
   House and Senate negotiators are still thrashing out
reconciliation legislation.
   Without the legislation, federal programs would suffer $16.1
billion in automatic cuts, with half targeting the Defense
Department.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee invited Pentagon officials
to Capitol Hill to describe the impact of the automatic budget
cuts. At the session, however, members of the panel fell into
partisan bickering.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., said he could not believe that Bush,
``the great defender of America,'' would accept the defense
reductions that would be ``absolutely devastating'' to the military.
   ``The effect of this decision would be to take us back to the
readiness levels of the mid-1970s,'' said Sen. Albert Gore Jr.,
D-Tenn., who indicated that the ``zillions of dollars'' spent
during the Reagan and Bush administrations on building up the
nation's defense would be for naught.
   But Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the
committee, said Congress must share some of the blame.
   ``We're in this hearing because Congress failed to do its job,''
Warner said. ``We've got a lot of faults. We didn't come into this
with clean hands.''
   In the House, Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, ranking Republican
on the Budget Committee, shrugged off the concerns expressed by
Senate Democrats, and told reporters the Bush administration is
``not paralyzed with fear like the last administration was'' over
the automatic cuts.
   Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., said that if ``defense had more
flexibility,'' he would favor the required budget cuts.
   During the session, the Defense Department's comptroller, Sean
O'Keefe, and representatives of the Army, Navy, Air Force and
Marine Corps described the steps they would have to take in
response to the 4.3 percent across-the-board cuts.
   O'Keefe urged Congress to approve a Pentagon request that would
give them the authority to move money around to minimize the effect
of the automatic budget cuts.
   Nunn said he supports that request but indicated other
congressional committees oppose the Pentagon's call and the
likelihood of approval is slim.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney will comply with the budget cuts
``however painful that may be,'' O'Keefe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
