<FIRST>r a PM-ContemporaryArt 1stLd-Writethru a0519 11-09 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contemporary Art, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Kooning Work Goes for $20.6 Million at Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CLARIFY that Mountain Tortoise is name
of company, that $4 million to $6 million was the predicted selling price;
tightens lead. PICKS UP 4th graf, ``(A</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abstract work by Willem de Kooning sold for
$20.6 million to a Japanese collector, setting an auction record
for a work by a living artist, Sotheby's said.
   The 1955 oil-on-canvas painting ``Interchange'' was bought
Wednesday by Shigeki Kameyama of the Mountain Tortoise Co. of Toyko.
   It had been acquired by Edgar Kaufmann Jr. in the year it was
painted and had been expected to sell for $4 million to $6 million,
said Matthew Weigman, a spokesman for the auction house.
   ``(Auctioneer) John Marion said, `Can I have a bid of $1.6
million?' and Bo Alveryd, sitting in the front row, immediately bid
$6 million,'' Weigman said.
   Alveryd, a Swedish dealer who lives in Switzerland, stayed in
until the bidding hit $15 million but a telephone bidder kept the
contest going, Weigman said. When the gavel fell, 4,000 hands burst
into applause.
   The previous records for an auctioned work by a living artist
were set when S.I. Newhouse Jr. paid $17 million for Jasper Johns'
``False Start'' last November at Sotheby's, Weigman said.
   Wednesday night's sale of works from various collections brought
in $91 million, which Sotheby's said was a record for any session
of contemporary art at auction.
   Records were set for 12 artists and 19 lots sold for more than
$1 million, Weigman said.
   Alveryd did win the bidding for Jasper Johns' oil-on-canvas
``Two Flags'' at $12.1 million.
   Frank Stella's ``Tomlinson Court Park (Second Version),''
concentric rectangles in black enamel on canvas, sold for $5.06
million.
   The top seller at Christie's auction Wednesday also was a de
Kooning, an oil painting called ``Woman in Landscape No. 10,''
which went for $825,000, said a Christie's spokeswoman, Dana
Micucci.
   ``Ultima Thule,'' a steel sculpture by John Chamberlain, drew
$253,000, a record for Chamberlain, Micucci said.
   And Ed Ruscha's oil on canvas ``The Sixties and Seventies'' drew
$203,500, also an artist's record.
   Records also were set for works on paper by Sam Francis, Cy
Twombly and Brice Marden, Micucci said.
</TEXT>
