<HEAD>7 Immigrant Workers Killed in Van Crash On Long Island Freeway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with driver saying tire blew out,
ADD background on workers. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Police said...'; ADDS
2 grafs with quotes from employer.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYOSSET, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A van carrying immigrant factory workers to
their jobs in the suburbs skidded off a damp highway in heavy fog,
crashed into a tree and exploded. Seven people died and eight
others were injured, two critically.
   Police said the driver told investigators the van blew a tire
before veering out of control just before dawn Wednesday on the
Northern State Parkway.
   ``It was wet and extremely slippery. It's like driving on ice,''
said State Police investigator Dale Faro. ``Frankly, I'm amazed
that we didn't have more killed.''
   The van's occupants, all Haitian, lived in Brooklyn and worked
in factories on Long Island, where there has been a shortage of
workers for entry-level jobs. They spoke little English,
complicating the investigation, police said.
   Police said they were investigating whether the van, registered
as a passenger vehicle, was being used illegally as a van for hire
or legally as a car pool.
   Police also were questioning the van's driver, who apparently
did not have a valid New York driver's license, The New York Times
reported.
   Five people were dead at the scene and two others died later of
their injuries, authorities said. Killed were four men, two women
and one person whose sex could not be determined.
   Two of the injured were in critical condition and the six others
were in fair to serious condition.
   Jack Siraucia, of Island Cosmetics, said that two of the workers
in the van, including one of those who died, had worked for him for
about two years.
   ``They were just good, hard-working people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
