<HEAD>Ethiopia Gets New Foreign Minister in Cabinet Shakeup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam has
appointed a new foreign minister and deputy prime minister, in a
further shakeup of the Marxist government leadership.
   Two senior government and party officials were retired for
unspecified health reasons, and there was speculation that further
Cabinet changes will be made in coming days.
   The new appointments and retirements came 24 hours after Prime
Minister Fikre-Selassie Wogderess retired for health reasons. He
was the most powerful official in government after Mengistu. He
also was the second-ranking member of the 15-member Politburo of
the ruling Marxist-Leninist Workers Party of Ethiopia.
   The new foreign minister, appointed Wednesday, is Tesfaye Dinka.
   Welle Chekol was named to replace him as deputy prime minister
for financial and economic affairs. He has served previously as
minister of external trade and finance.
   Mengistu appointed Lemma Gutema to the post of vice president in
the Council of State, a semi-legislative body. His last post was as
ambassador to East Germany.
   The former foreign minister, Berhanu Bayih, was named a vice
president in the Council of State. He held the foreign ministry
portfolio for about five years.
   Retired were Debela Dinssa, a Council of State vice president,
and Teka Tulu, who once coordinated intelligence services in the
former military government.
   The reshuffle comes when the Marxist government is under
battlefield pressure from the Tigrey Peoples' Liberation Front and
is talking peace with the Tigreans and Eritrean rebels.
   Although the government and the Tigreans began preliminary talks
in Rome on Saturday, the rebels have showed no sign of halting
their current offensive.
</TEXT>
