<HEAD>Con Man Who Testified Against Former Congressman Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A con man whose testimony helped convict former
U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall of perjury has been sentenced to four years
in prison for money laundering.
   Charles LeChasney, 35, pleaded guilty in 1988 to conspiring to
launder money in Atlanta, Washington and Puerto Rico.
   In Atlanta, he admitted receiving $710,000 from an undercover
agent and helping launder the money through banks. Chasney was told
the money came from drugs.
   Swindall, a Republican, was found guilty last spring and
sentenced to a year in prison for lying to a federal grand jury
about his negotiations with LeChasney and an undercover IRS agent
who was running a money laundering sting.
   Prosecutors said LeChasney's testimony also helped obtain guilty
pleas from two other defendants.
   U.S. District Judge Robert L. Vining Jr. said Wednesday he would
have given LeChasney at least three more years if prosecutors had
not suggested a lighter sentence.
