<HEAD>Cyclone Kills 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with 50 dead; picks up 4th pvs:
It said ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cyclone churned across the coastal
areas of south India today, killing at least 50 people and sweeping
away crops, power lines and mud-and-straw houses, news reports said.
   United News of India said most deaths were reported from Andhra
Pradesh state's Nellore district, about 900 miles southwest of New
Delhi on the eastern coast.
   About 50,000 people were homeless, the news agency said, quoting
state relief officials.
   The news agency said 25 fishermen who ignored the cyclone
warning drowned in the Bay of Bengal off Machilipatnam, 140 miles
north of Nellore. United News also reported 25 other deaths.
   It said property damage could not be immediately determined
because most communication links with the area had snapped.
Preliminary reports said hundreds of power poles and huts had been
swept away, it said.
   The cyclone hit Thailand last week and left at least 169 people
dead before moving westward into the Bay of Bengal. The storm hit
Nellore and neighboring Prakasam district at about 1 a.m.
   A cyclone from the Bay of Bengal left at least 150 people dead
across southern and western Indian in July.
   In 1977, at least 10,000 people were killed in a cyclone in
Andhra Pradesh.
