<SECOND>PM-Obit-Holland,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longtime Trenton, N.J., Mayor Dies at 71</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Arthur Holland, former president of
the U.S. Conference of Mayors, died of cancer today. He was 71.
   Holland, one of New Jersey's longest-serving mayors, died at St.
Francis Medical Center, where he was admitted Sept. 12.
   He was mayor for 26 of the last 30 years. He lost re-election in
1966 but he returned to office four years later. Trenton mayoral
elections are non-partisan, but Holland described himself as a
Democrat.
   To demonstrate the sincerity of his commitment to civil rights,
Holland in 1964 moved his family into a racially mixed neighborhood.
   In June, he completed a one-year term as president of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, serving as a national spokesman for the needs
of urban America.
   Holland spent six years at a seminary, but did not enter the
priesthood. He began his city government career in 1951 as deputy
director of public affairs. He was elected to the City Council in
1955 and became mayor in 1959.
   Survivors include his wife, Betty, who unsuccessfully ran for
Congress last year; three sons, and two daughters.
</TEXT>
