<FIRST>r a PM-BankSuit     11-09 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Suit,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>$50 Million Judgment Against Bank of America Reversed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court threw out a $50
million judgment won by a farmer who said a bank defrauded him by
enticing him to borrow millions and then cutting off credit when
his business went sour.
   In a ruling seen as a victory for banks on the issue of ``lender
liability,'' the court Wednesday said Robert Stanghellini failed to
prove the Bank of America committed fraud.
   A jury in 1987 awarded Stanghellini, his elderly mother and aunt
$20 million in compensatory damages and $30 million in punitive
damages. The award was reduced by $3 million, the amount
Stanghellini owed the bank.
   Stanghellini had argued that the bank got him to borrow heavily
to expand and then cut him off after his tomato-growing business
suffered heavy losses in the early 1980s.
   The appeals court cited errors by the trial judge and misconduct
by Richard Murphy, Stanghellini's lawyer.
   Murphy had tried to ``vilify the bank unfairly, both in and out
of court'' make his case ``through sources beyond properly
admissible evidence,'' the court said.
   Murphy was unavailable for comment, a spokeswoman said Wednesday.
   Recent decisions by appeals courts have reversed several rulings
against banks that abruptly cut off credit to long-standing
customers who began losing money.
</TEXT>
