<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica     11-09 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Tells White Extremists Reforms Will Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President F.W. de Klerk today told
leaders of two white extremist groups that he rejected their
proposal for a whites-only homeland and will continue to pursue
power-sharing with blacks.
   The meeting was the first ever between a South African head of
state and Eugene TerreBlanche, leader of the neo-Nazi Afrikaner
Resistance Movement. It is the country's most powerful
white-supremacist group.
   TerreBlanche, who wore a khaki uniform to the hourlong meeting,
was accompanied by Robert von Tonder, head of the Boerestaat Party.
   Both organizations advocate creation of a whites-only nation in
the northeastern third of South Africa, to be controlled by the
Afrikaners who make up 60 percent of the country's 5 million white
population.
   ``I don't think the proposals of those two parties are realistic
or very workable,'' De Klerk, also an Afrikaner, told a news
conference after the meeting. ``I sincerely believe Eugene
TerreBlanche does not represent a substantial number of people in
South Africa.''
   TerreBlanche declined comment and left the president's office in
the company of 10 bodyguards in khaki uniforms bearing the
movement's swastika-like emblem. He was expected to talk about the
meeting at a speech scheduled for tonight in Boksburg, a
Johannesburg-area industrial town controlled by the far-right
Conservative Party.
   The president said TerreBlanche did not warn that his movement
might take up arms against the government. But, ``should
revolutionary forces be allowed to take over, they would take up
arms,'' de Klerk said.
   He said TerreBlanche and von Tonder also expressed concern about
the possible consequences of releasing prominent black security
prisoners, such as jailed African National Congress leader Nelson
Mandela.
   The meeting was requested by TerreBlanche, a charismatic orator
who often ends his speeches with Hitler-style salutes.
   De Klerk, who took office in mid-August, has offered to meet
leaders across the political spectrum. He conferred last month with
three prominent anti-apartheid church leaders, including Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   In Bloemfontein, provincial capital of the Orange Free State,
seven members of TerreBlanche's movement went on trial today for
allegedly tar-and-feathering Mayor Gus Gouws of the town of Welkom
because he permitted a multiracial foot race.
   Also today, leaders of the African National Congress said
government reform moves are being undercut by action against the
news media and a threat to suspend a leading anti-apartheid
newspaper.
   Home Affairs Minister Eugene Louw has accused the New Nation
newspaper of ``promoting the public image'' of the ANC and warned
the newspaper it could face a suspension of up to three months.
   The weekly newspaper, published by the Southern African Catholic
Bishops Conference, was shut down for three months in 1988 but
maintained an aggressive anti-government stance after returning to
newsstands.
   ``The South African government is mounting a campaign against
the press,'' said Andrew Mlangeni, one of seven ANC leaders
released from prison last month.
   Such a crackdown will undermine any government attempt to create
a ``climate that can make meaningful negotiations possible,''
Mlangeni said on behalf of the ANC leaders.
   Under state of emergency regulations the government has wide
powers of censorship and may close publications for up to three
months without having to justify its action in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
