<SECOND>PM-Bosch,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Free Anti-Castro Militant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to release Dr. Orlando
Bosch Avila, an anti-Castro militant fighting deportation as a
terrorist.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler on Wednesday described
Bosch as a hero of the anti-Castro resistance whose efforts
``became sullied by his extremes.''
   The 62-year-old pediatrician regarded by the FBI as Miami's
``No. 1 terrorist'' has been held in prison here since his return
from Venezuela in 1988.
   Bosch was convicted in a 1968 bazooka attack on a Polish ship in
Miami and fled the United States while on probation in 1974.
   The Justice Department has linked him to bombing raids in Cuba
in the 1960s and bombings throughout the United States and Latin
America in the 1970s.
   He was jailed for 11 years in Venezuela in the bombing of a
Cuban airliner that killed 73 people.
   Bosch's lawyers say he now repudiates violence, and his family
believes he will be killed if deported.
   The question of whether the Justice Department has the authority
to issue a final exclusion order is still before Hoeveler.
</TEXT>
