<FIRST>r a PM-FoleyMemo     11-09 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foley Memo,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>RNC Staffer Who Took Blame for Memo Now Says He Didn't Write It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican National Committee staffer
who quit after taking blame for a memo linking House Speaker Thomas
S. Foley's voting record to that of a gay congressman now says he
didn't write the document.
   Mark Goodin resigned as RNC communications director in June over
the memo, which compared Foley's ``liberal voting record'' to that
of Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass. The memo was titled ``Tom Foley: Out
of the Liberal Closet.''
   Goodin took responsibility for the four-page memo, which was
circulated to GOP congressional leaders, but said in an interview
published today that he did not write it. He said he took the blame
because it came from his division.
   ``Where I fell down was in not paying enough attention to it,''
Goodin told The News and Courier.
   In June, he told RNC Chairman Lee Atwater, ``I did not envision
the way it (the memo) would be perceived. And for that reason
alone, I am guilty of extraordinarily bad judgment.''
   Leaders of the Republican and Democratic parties were outraged
by the document. Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., called it ``garbage,''
while Democratic chairman Ron Brown insisted President Bush fire
Atwater.
   Goodin said Wednesday the incident ``took a lot of wind out of
my stomach,'' but he maintained he never intended to denigrate
Foley.
   ``I'm not the slash-and-burn type,'' he said.
   Goodin, 34, is a self-employed communications and government
relations consultant in Washington.
</TEXT>
