<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     11-09 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibian Guerrilla Group Complains of ``Acts of Desperation'' by
Rival</HEAD>
<HEAD>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South-West Africa People's
Organization, favored to win Namibia's pre-independence election,
today accused its main rival of ``acts of desperation'' as the
five-day voting period passed its halfway point.
   SWAPO spokesman Hidipo Hamutenya said bogus pamphlets intended
to discredit the party were dropped over Katutura, the main black
neighborhood of Windhoek. He also said three-pronged spikes were
placed outside SWAPO offices, damaging the tires of party vehicles.
   ``These are acts of desperation by the DTA, who know they are
doomed,'' he said, referring to the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance.
   Officials of the United Nations contingent that is monitoring
the elections have cited the alliance for several possible
infractions of the election code, including incidents of
intimidation and the display of party posters too close to polling
stations.
   Gerhard Roux, a spokesman for the territorial government, said
today that 60.4 percent of the 701,483 registered voters had cast
ballots Tuesday and Wednesday.
   ``This is quite remarkable _ a figure that speaks well not only
of the system but of the enthusiasm of the Namibian people,'' Roux
said.
   Roux earlier predicted that the turnout could approach 100
percent by the time voting ends Saturday.
   Namibians, many of them first-time voters, are electing a
72-seat assembly that will write a constitution and make Namibia
independent of South Africa after 74 years.
   Voters have been willing to wait for hours in temperatures up to
108 degrees to cast their ballots.
   Election officials said results could be released by Wednesday.
Assembly seats will be allocated according to the proportion of
votes received by each party, and the assembly is to convene one
week after the results are final.
   SWAPO, a leftist movement which waged a 23-year war against
South African rule, could write the constitution on its own if it
wins two-thirds of the assembly seats.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, a multiracial coalition that
favors a capitalist economy, was part of the transitional
government installed by South Africa.
   Also today, authorities launched a search for a missing reporter
from The Republican, a Windhoek newspaper published by the
alliance. The reporter, Martin Erastus, was last seen Monday and
his abandoned car was found later near Namibia's northern border
with Angola.
   South Africa captured the vast, mineral-rich territory from
Germany in World War I. It resisted U.N. efforts to get it to leave
Namibia but finally agreed to grant independence under U.N.
supervision.
</TEXT>
