<FIRST>u i PM-Turkey 1stLd-Writethru   11-09 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0544,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Sworn In As President, Names Parliament Speaker As New Premier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT number voting for Ozal from
283 to 263; picks up 4th graf `Ozal, 62,...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turgut Ozal, premier for the past six
years, was sworn in as president today in a Parliament ceremony
boycotted by opposition parties. He named Yildirim Akbulut, speaker
of Parliament, as the new premier.
   In his inaugural address, Ozal said one of Turkey's main aims
should be ``to occupy its distinguished place in the European
Community,'' and he called for reform he said is necessary to
become an EC member.
   All 155 opposition deputies also stayed away from the 450-seat
Parliament when Ozal was elected president Oct. 31. All but 20 of
the 283 deputies of Ozal's Motherland Party voted for him.
   Ozal, 62, swore to be free of all bias and to uphold the secular
republic, all its laws and democracy. Cannons fired 101 salvos to
mark his inauguration.
   Ozal proposed that a standing committee on human rights be
established in the Parliament and that judicial reform be
undertaken.
   The appointment of Akbulut, a member of the governing Motherland
Party who has served as speaker since 1987, came as a surprise. He
had not been mentioned among the frontrunners for the job.
Parliament must approve the appointment and is likely to vote next
week.
   Ozal appointed the 54-year-old lawyer apparently because he was
hard-pressed to find a candidate acceptable to all factions of the
party that includes liberals, Moslem fundamentalists and
ultra-nationalists, political analysts said.
   The premier-designate is considered a moderate and exteremely
loyal to Ozal. He served as interior minister in one of Ozal's
Cabinets before the 1987 general election.
   Ozal succeeds Kenan Evren, leader of a 1980 military coup. In a
speech at a second ceremony, Evren proposed that the constitution
be changed to allow voters to elect the president directly.
   Ozal sought and won the presidency at a time when popular
support for his free-market policies had plummeted to about 17
percent, according to recent public opinion polls.
   The opposition, which includes the Social Democrat Populist
Party and the centrist True Path Party led by former premier
Suleyman Demirel, contended that Ozal lacked a popular mandate and
could not be the nonpartisan president required by the constitution.
   The presidency is a highly respected post but has little
executive power. He can veto legislation but Parliament can
overturn his vetoes. He can refuse to appoint Cabinet ministers
suggested by the premier, but this authority has been used
sparingly in the past.
   However, Ozal's successor as premier is hand-picked, and he
remains the power in Turkey.
   Ozal served as premier after his Motherland Party won the 1983
general elections that ended three years of military rule. He is
credited with the success of Turkey's 1980 economic rescue program
and liberalization that brought export-led growth.
</TEXT>
