<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneVandalism     11-09 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Vandalism,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vandalism Interrupts Phone Service to 361,000 in Southeastern New
York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals sliced two telephone cables
today, leaving up to 361,000 customers with limited service in the
biggest such incident in the 3-month-old strike against NYNEX, the
company said.
   Repair crews hoped to have service restored by noon in the four
counties north of New York City, said Peter Muller, a spokesman for
NYNEX susbidiary New York Telephone.
   Service was disrupted to up to 300,000 New York Telephone
customers after the cables were cut in Highland, Muller said.
Vandals sawed through a copper cable and hacked away a 30-foot
section of newer fiber optic cable, he said.
   Customers can make local calls but are having trouble calling
long-distance, Muller said.
   Service also was disrupted to up to 61,000 customers of Contel
of New York, which provides local phone service, said company
spokeswoman Debbie Mazzone.
   More than 520 cases of vandalism to company lines have been
reported since 40,000 members of the Communication Workers union
walked off the job Aug. 6 in a dispute over health benefits, Muller
said.
   Two other phone lines were cut Wednesday night in Hyde Park and
Poughkeepsie, disrupting service to about 800 customers, phone
company officials said. That service was expected to be restored by
tonight.
</TEXT>
