<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Jordan     11-09 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jordan,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Fundamentalists Score Major Electoral Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem fundamentalists scored a major
victory today in Jordan's first general election in 22 years,
capturing at least 26 seats in an 80-member Parliament. Former
government officials faired poorly.
   The Islamic fundamentalists, who call for stricter Moslem laws
and the elimination of Israel, swamped their opponents in districts
throughout the country, according to early results.
   The victory appeared to be a setback for King Hussein, who had
appealed to voters to separate religion from politics. Islamic
activists and leftists easily outnumber declared pro-government
deputies.
   Among the victors was Mansour Murad, convicted in Greece of
participating in the 1969 grenade attack by Palestinian guerrillas
on the Athens office of Israel's state airline, El Al, that killed
a child and wounded 14 other people.
   Greece freed him in 1970 to win the freedom of 55 hostages
aboard a hijacked Olympic Airways jetliner.
   Murad edged a member of the fundamentalist Moslem Brotherhood to
win the seat in Amman's 3rd District reserved for Circassians, a
group of 19th century Caucasian refugees who settled in Jordan.
   Most results had been officially reported this afternoon, but
those for several large districts remained unclear.
   Official announcements gave the Moslem Brotherhood 19 seats and
they were expected to pick up another five when all results were
tallied.
   Independent Islamic activists, some allied with the Brotherhood,
won seven seats and were expected to pick up about three more.
   Although parties have been banned in Jordan since 1957, the
government allowed the Brotherhood to operate as a charitable
organization, in part to counter the influence of leftist groups.
   Radical leftists won only four to five seats and leftist Arab
nationalists at least nine. Pro-government figures, tribal leaders
and centrists got about 20 seats and were likely to pick up a few
more.
   More than 62 percent of the 877,000 eligible voters cast
ballots, Interior Ministry spokesman Salameh Hamad said. The
elections involved 647 candidates, including 12 women who were able
to vote and seek office for the first time. None seemed likely to
win.
   Women's rights activist Toujan Faisal, who won international
attention when Islamic fundamentalists filed a lawsuit accusing her
of abandoning her faith, was trounced 4-1 by a Moslem Brotherhood
candidate.
   Several prominent pro-government figures were defeated,
including former Public Works Minister Shafiq Zawaideh and former
Industry Minister Hamdi Tabaa.
   By far the biggest winners appeared to be Brotherhood candidates.
   ``The people want Islam and it is not strange for our country
and our people to have such a large number of Moslem candidates
winning,'' said Brotherhood spokesman Ziad Abu Ghanimeh.
   The last nationwide election occurred in April 1967, two months
before Israel captured the West Bank, represented by half the
deputies in the old Parliament.
   It was the first nationwide election since Jordan renounced
claims on the West Bank in favor of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   The Parliament must pass all laws and budgets and can reject
cabinets _ something previous legislatures have done several times
in the past.
   The king remains the center of authority. He can dissolve
Parliament at any time and for 22 years has ruled by martial law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
