<FIRST>r i PM-Thailand-Ship     11-09 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thailand-Ship,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Crew Members Charge Ship Not Fit For Rough Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SONGKHLA, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former crewmen of a oil-drilling ship
that capsized during a typhoon said the flat-bottomed vessel was
not fit for rough weather. The ship's U.S. owners blamed faulty
weather forecasting.
   The 5,373-ton Panamanian-flagged Seacrest, operated by Unocal of
Los Angeles, overturned Friday as Typhoon Gay rolled through the
Gulf of Thailand, killing more than 300 people.
   The storm was the worst to hit the country in 35 years.
   Only six of the 97 people aboard Seacrest are known to have
survived the typhoon. Twenty-five bodies have been found, but the
rest of the crew remains missing. All seven American crew members
were feared dead.
   ``That drill ship was made for moderate tropical waters _ it was
never designed to withstand the sort of excessive seas that it took
on Friday,'' said Douglas Whittaker, a crewman on the Seacrest for
10 years.
   He said he was called to help in the rescue operation because of
his knowledge of the ship's layout.
   Whittaker, another Seacrest crewman and relatives of men lost
aboard the ship also accused Unocal of disregarding weather
forecasts and of failing to mount effective rescue efforts.
   The Bangkok newspaper The Nation reported today that some
relatives of missing or dead crewmen were considering legal action
against Unocal.
   Unocal has denied the Seacrest was unseaworthy. Senior company
executives have cited poor weather forcasting as a reason for the
loss of the ship and admitted some shortcomings in rescue attempts.
   John F. Imle Jr., chairman of Unocal Thailand, said at a news
conference Wednesday no company boats were able to approach the
Seacrest until about eight hours after it capsized.
   The Nation quoted Kriangkrai Korwattana, head of the
meteorological center in the southern port of Songkhla, as saying
Unocal had ignored repeated storm warnings.
   ``They had three days to decide what to do,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   The other former Seacrest crewman, a relative of a man missing
in the disaster, accused Unocal of being complacent about weather
conditions in the normally calm gulf.
   ``If this was the North Sea the safety standards would be very
different,'' he said.
   The Seacrest capsized in the Platong field, one of several being
explored for natural gas by Unocal.
</TEXT>
