<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Contras 1stLd-Writethru a0433 11-09 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Contras, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0433,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Intent On Dismantling Contras At Risk Of More War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to recast lede, UPDATE with Contras forming
new governing body; picks up 8th graf, `The most ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government enters
bargaining with the Contras today with an offer to free all
political prisoners _ but only after half the rebel force is
dismantled and all Sandinista captives are freed.
   The leftist government's revised plan for disbanding the
U.S.-backed rebels offers few new elements. It goes part of the way
toward meeting Contra demands, but carries a threat of renewed war.
   At the heart of the talks is a 3-month-old regional pact to
demobilize the Contra force _ about 12,000 fighters based in jungle
camps in Honduras _ by Dec. 5. President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua
is determined the deadline be met.
   National elections are scheduled for next Feb. 25 and could be
at risk if fighting resumes after 19 months of relative quiet.
   The negotiations are taking place at U.N. headquarters in New
York and include a joint U.N.-Organization of American States
commission as well as Sandinista and Contra delegates.
   The commission was set up by the Aug. 7 peace accord signed in
Tela, Honduras, by Ortega and four other Central American
presidents. Its mission is to supervise and verify the
demobilization.
   In Miami today, the Contras announced the formation of a new
``civilian-military commission'' to act as the governing body in
place of the old directorate, several of whose members have
returned to Nicaragua.
   Contra spokesman Alejandro Acevedo said the U.N. negotiating
team headed by the Contra's military commander, Enrique Bermudez,
has recognized the new commission, which includes only one of the
former directors, Aristides Sanchez.
   As part of the peace accord, in exchange for the dissolution of
the Contras, Ortega moved up the election date from 1991 and
pledged free and fair campaigning and balloting under the
supervision of international observers.
   The most significant items in the Sandinistas' new 15-point
proposal were an offer to release all political prisoners and a
statement guaranteeing the Contras their human and civil rights.
   Even so, these offers are conditional. The political prisoners
would be released only after half the Contra force has been
demobilized and after all Nicaraguans claimed by the Sandinistas to
have been kidnapped by the rebels have been freed.
   Similarly, the human and civil rights guarantee is for those
rebels who lay down their arms and return to Nicaragua.
   Contra leaders say they distrust Sandinista promises. They
demand an unconditional general amnesty and so far have made no
move to demobilize.
   Among nine point in the Sandinista proposal that are not new is
one urging the U.S. Congress to put toward Contra demobilization
the non-lethal aid it has approved to maintain the rebels as a
fighting force.
   ``If the Contras don't accept this plan, they will be voting for
war,'' Ortega told a news conference.
   The Sandinistas also have offered to suspend arms imports until
April 25.
   The Soviet Union said in May it stopped shipping arms to
Nicaragua at the end of 1988, but Paul Wolfowitz, a U.S. Defense
Department undersecretary, said last week that other Soviet bloc
nations and Cuba have continued sending weapons.
   The Sandinistas have also offered to reinstate the cease-fire
Ortega suspended on Nov. 1 and to withdraw the huge military
machinery the government has since deployed so Contras in Nicaragua
can return to Honduras.
   The reverse of this offer is that if the Contras don't agree to
demobilize, the Sandinistas could launch an offensive to wipe out
the 6,500 Contras the government says are in Nicaragua, 4,000 of
whom are said to have infiltrated in the past month.
   Stepped up fighting could make campaigning for the elections
difficult if not impossible in many places. And disrupted balloting
could fuel opposition claims that the Sandinistas were never
serious about free elections.
   The U.N. Security Council is sending a 625-member border patrol
force to stop the Contra infiltration from Honduras and to
interdict shipments of Nicaraguan and Cuban weapons the State
Department says are being made to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   The pact that Ortega and the presidents of Honduras, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Costa Rica signed calls for the
``voluntary'' demobilization of the rebels force, but the Contras
were not a party to the agreement.
   Honduras, the only party that could force the Contras off its
territory, rejected Ortega's invitation to take part in the
negotiations, saying it never has recognized the Contras legally as
an insurgent force.
   It later relented and sent a delegation to the talks, but only
as observers.
   By attending only as an observer, Honduras apparently hopes to
project an image of cooperation in the regional peace effort while
avoiding a decision on the Contras and possibly angering its ally,
the United States.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the Roman Catholic archbishop of
Managua, also was to attend as an observer. He is the only figure
in Nicaragua whose moral authority is recognized and respected by
both sides.
   Ortega has told his negotiating team it must not leave the U.N.
meeting without a signed accord.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Doralisa Pilarte is the AP's Managua
correspondent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
