<FIRST>u w PM-Archives-Morris 1stLd-Writethru a0455 11-09 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Archives-Morris, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Group Protests Morris Role in Bill of Rights Commemoration</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs pvs grafs 5-6, Bingaman, a ... unsuccessful, with 6 grafs
to include Philip Morris comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer health group today asked Congress
to revoke an agreement between a cigarette manufacturer and the
National Archives which the group says ``smears the Bill of Rights
with the blood of all Americans killed as a result of smoking.''
   The August agreement makes Philip Morris Companies Inc. part of
an Archives campaign to commemorate the bicentennial of the Bill of
Rights.
   A nationally televised public service announcement that is a
part of the campaign includes the voices of President Kennedy and
Martin Luther King over images of the Bill of Rights and scenes
from civil rights demonstrations. The announcement identifies
Philip Morris as the sponsor.
   ``This joint venture smears the Bill of Rights with the blood of
all Americans killed as a result of smoking Marlboro and other
Philip Morris cigarettes,'' said Sidney Wolfe, director of Public
Citizen Health Research Group, in a letter to Sen. Jeff Bingaman.
   Bingaman, a New Mexico Democrat, heads the Government Affairs
Committee's subcommittee on government information which has
jurisdiction over the archives.
   ``The campaign has nothing to do with cigarettes. It's about the
celebration of the Bill of Rights,'' Guy L. Smith, vice president
of corporate affairs for Philip Morris, said today.
   We are only identified at the very end (of the announcement) and
we consciously separated the identification of the company from the
messages about the themes of the Bill of Rights,'' Smith said. ``
We're just sponsoring the messages and the archives is helping us
to make sure they're historically accurate.''
   Smith added that as of this morning, 200,056 people had
requested a copy of the Bill of Rights offered by Philip Morris.
   ``The Bill of Rights belongs to everybody,'' said Smith,
likening his company's sponsorship of the campaign to that of
American Express raising money to refurbish the Statue of Liberty.
   Efforts to reach national archivist Don Wilson by telephone were
unsuccessful.
   The agreement is the first such cooperative effort and
``launches the National Archives' endeavor to engage the corporate
world in supporting events related to America's documentary
heritage,'' Wilson said in a Nov. 1 announcement.
   The agreement with Philip Morris allows the company to ``obscure
its deadly role in American and worldwide society'' and should be
reversed, said Wolfe, who founded the Health Research Group in 1971
with consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
   Under the agreement, Philip Morris donates $600,000 to the
National Archives Trust Fund and is permitted to publish or
broadcast announcements as part of the Bill of Rights bicentennial
commemoration, using voices of prominent Americans such as former
presidents.
   ``What would Martin Luther King or Harry Truman think if they
knew their voices were being made available by the National
Archives in order to improve the image of a company with the deadly
record of Philip Morris?'' asked Wolfe in his letter.
   Wolfe said Archives staff have told him $475,000 of the
company's contribution will go to build an exhibit gallery in the
National Archives building and the remaining $125,000 will give the
company the first charter membership in an association, yet to be
established, that will solicit corporate donations to do the work
of the Archives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-AerosolSmog 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 11-09 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aerosol Smog, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0546,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Orders Deodorant Makers to Solve Aerosol-Caused Pollution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd graf pvs with industry reaction;
SUBS last graf with 9 grafs with industry reaction and background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California has ordered deodorant
makers to give up smog-forming aerosol propellants or find a way to
reduce the pollution they create.
   ``This landmark action requires manufacturers to use more
environmentally acceptable substitutes if they choose to continue
selling aerosols and will likely set a precedent for other consumer
product actions that follow,'' Jananne Sharpless, chairwoman of the
state Air Resources Board, said in a statement.
   Manufacturers and industry experts said the move against
underarm sprays could open the door to restrictions on other
aerosol products such as hair spray and prompt some manufacturers
to pull their products out of California.
   Hydrocarbons are used as a propellant to spray many products.
They became popular after 1978 when chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs,
were banned in the United States because of their danger to the
ozone layer. Hydrocarbons cause no known damage to the ozone but
combine with other pollutants to create smog.
   The Air Resources Board on Wednesday gave manufacturers of
antiperspirants and deodorants until 1992 to reduce smog-creating
hydrocarbons by 20 percent. The order also calls for an additional
60 percent cut by 1995.
   Manufacturers will be given the option of providing a plan to
comply with the ruling by 1999, using yet-to-be developed products
that spray without polluting. The delay will allow time for safety
testing.
   The board suggested the use of substitute propellants and such
mechanical features as pumps.
   The order could lead manufacturers to concentrate on sales of
roll-on and solid antiperspirants and deodorants, which account for
75 percent of sales in California.
   ``There already are more environmentally acceptable alternatives
for aerosol deodorants that are being purchased by three out of
every four Californians,'' Ms. Sharpless said.
   Manufacturers said they were not sure of the ruling's impact but
suggested board members were opening the way for restrictions on
other products.
   ``Their intention is to ban aerosols. This is step No. 1. The
only reason they aren't putting an outright ban is because there
would be a hundred lawsuits,'' said George C. Dietrich, president
of Diversified CPC International, a manufacturer based in Illinois.
   Edward Haiden, an economic consultant from Washington, said some
manufacturers may simply decide not to do business in California.
   ``Most companies couldn't have a two-product distribution system
_ one for California and another for the rest of the nation,'' he
said.
   Deodorant makers had earlier appealed to the board because they
felt the restrictions would cost millions of dollars and have
little effect on pollution.
   ``We believe the emission reduction is so small that it doesn't
warrant this kind of treatment,'' said Ralph Engel of the Chemical
Specialty Manufacturers Association.
   The board has authority over the quality of California's air,
and its order on aerosols does not need the Legislature's approval.
   The action was taken in conjunction with the first phase of a
20-year, three-part plan approved in August to help smoggy Southern
California meet federal clean-air requirements. The first phase
also will include a ban on barbecue lighter fluid and restrictions
on smokestack emissions.
   Spray underarm deodorants and antiperspirants release about five
tons of pollutants into the air statewide every day, the board said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0098 </DOCNO>
