<SECOND>PM-Leukemia-Theft,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Indicted on Accepting Donation's for Daughter's Unneeded Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school employee falsely claimed her
daughter had leukemia and collected $1,400 in donations from
faculty and PTA members, authorities say.
   Donna Leeper, 43, who worked in a PTA-funded position at the
Hopkins Elementary School clinic, was indicted Tuesday on charges
of theft and making a false statement. She had been arrested in
June and was free on bail.
   Authorities said Ms. Leeper told her colleagues last spring that
her 9-year-old daughter had leukemia and needed experimental
surgery.
   Investigators later learned that the woman had been convicted of
manslaughter in Maryland in 1978 for shooting her husband and
served a year in prison.
   Dan Parks, chairman of the Gwinnett Board of Education, said the
PTA does not fall under board control.
   ``You don't want to make people who volunteer, and people who do
so much good for the school system, you don't want to upset those
people by telling them, `You can't come in and help until we do a
background check,''' he said.
   ``They help out tremendously with volunteers in the schools.''
