<FIRST>r a PM-ContraLeaders     11-09 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Leaders,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Announce New Leadership Commission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua-Contras, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan Contras today announced the
formation of a civilian-military commission to lead the rebels as
peace talks get under way at the United Nations.
   The old seven-member directorate had virtually ceased
functioning after three of its members returned to Nicaragua and
the Bush administration cut off financial support to its
headquarters here.
   The new four-member ruling body, which has set up a temporary
office in Miami, was chosen by military commanders, said Commander
Franklin, one of the members of the commission and the Contra's
military chief of staff. Contra military leaders traditionally
employ pseudonyms.
   Only one member of the now-defunct directorate, Aristides
Sanchez, will participate in the new commission, said Franklin. The
other two members are military leaders like Franklin, known only as
Commanders Dimas and Ruben.
   In addition to Contra and Sandinista delegates, the talks that
begin today at U.N. headquarters in New York include a joint
U.N.-Organization of American States commission.
   The Contra representatives at the U.N. have recognized the new
commission's authority, said Contra spokesman Alejandro Acevedo.
The leader of the negotiators, Enrique Bermudez, was a former
member of the directorate.
</TEXT>
