<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p PM-ElectionsRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0424 11-09 0980</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elections Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Celebrate; Republicans Argue About Impact of Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 graphs new to update with Wilder and Dinkins appearing
at Capitol; picks up 4th graf pvs, In Virginia.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victorious black Democrats toured the Capitol
today and L. Douglas Wilder said his triumph in the Virginia
governor's race proved ``Americans have come of age.'' Republicans
were debating whether their 1989 election debacle was an ominous
sign about their prospects for the much heavier ballot slate in
1990.
   During a meeting with Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, Wilder joked about the narrowness of his margin _ a
majority his Republican opponent still questions.
   Turning to David Dinkins, the mayor-elect of New York City,
Wilder congratulated him and other Democrats, ``some of whom had
landslide victories like I did.''
   Wilder was asked if racism was the reason he ran behind other
Democratic candidates for statewide office and he replied, ``It
says I had a very negative campaign being waged against me and my
ticketmates didn't.''
   ``Americans have come of age,'' Wilder said. ``What was preached
and practiced for some time has come full cycle.''
   ``I don't think Doug is saying that racism is not a factor'' in
elections, said Dinkins. ``But I do believe that tremendous
progress has been achieved. But things are not perfect in our land,
to be sure. It's (racism) on the wane. It's not as great as it
was.''
   Democrats were jubilant as they tallied gains that included the
governor's mansion in New Jersey as well as the State Assembly and
the election of blacks as governor of Virginia and mayor of New
York City.
   Analysts of political trends among blacks hailed not only the
results in Virginia and New York, but also in such cities as
Seattle, New Haven, Conn., Cleveland and Durham, N.C., as ``a new
direction.''
   Democratic Party Chairman Ron Brown, appearing with Wilder and
Dinkins, said he believes the election demonstrated that the
Republican Party's stance on abortion is ``an untenable position.''
He said he believes President Bush has ``painted himself into a
corner'' by taking a strong anti-abortion position.
   Brown said Tuesday's election results show the Democratic Party
``is not only alive and well, but strong and getting stronger.''
Standing between Wilder and Dinkins, the chairman praised the two
blacks as men who projected themselves as ``mainstream Democrats''
whose appeal transcended race.
   ``We've built tremendous momentum,'' he said. ``We think it's an
important building block'' as the party looks to the 1990
congressional elections and the 1992 race for the White House.
   In Virginia, Republican J. Marshall Coleman said the outcome of
the governor's race was ``still in doubt.'' He said that if the
official vote tally, due in four more days, shows Wilder's victory
margin in the governor's race is as narrow as expected, he will ask
for a recount.
   The unofficial tally showed Wilder leading Coleman by about
5,500 votes out of a total of 1.78 million cast. Virginia law
authorizes recounts if the difference is less than one half of 1
percent.
   ``There's no way for the Republican Party to find any silver
lining at all in what happened yesterday,'' Brown said Wednesday.
   ``No time in my lifetime do I ever remember waking up the
morning after an election where one party had won everything, all
over the country.''
   ``The Democrats are on a roll,'' said Rep. Beryl Anthony of
Arkansas, the chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee. ``We have recruited better candidates. Our candidates
have better mainstream messages. And the voters are responding.''
   Many Republicans followed the lead of party chairman Lee Atwater
in brushing off GOP losses with the comment that ``all politics is
local.''
   ``It's hard to see a message,'' said Rep. Mickey Edwards of
Oklahoma, chairman of the House Republican Policy committee.
   But House Republican whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia saw the
results as a clear warning.
   ``Any Republican who looks honestly at yesterday's results has
to be very sobered up and has to be willing to rethink exactly what
we're going to do in 1990 if we're going to have a successful
year,'' said Gingrich after a White House post-mortem on the
elections.
   Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, one of the Republican Party's
strongest supporters of abortion rights, emerged from the meeting
and said that if abortion is an issue in 1990 ``we will just get
the bejabbers kicked out of us.''
   Gingrich called abortion ``a very small part of the equation.''
   ``We as a party, we're not big enough, we don't run aggressive
enough campaigns, we don't stay in the game full-time,'' said the
Georgia congressman.
   Defections on the abortion issue already are beginning. In
Massachusetts, Republican gubernatorial candidate William Weld and
a number of GOP state legislators joined Democrats in signing a
petition seeking a state constitutional amendment guaranteeing the
right to abortion.
   Kate Michelman, director of the National Abortion Rights Action
League, said the results demonstrated that ``if George Bush and
members of his party remain beholden to the anti-choice minority,
they will pay a tremendous price at the polls.''
   ``The lesson that will be learned ... is that pro-life
candidates cannot waffle and pro-life candidates must run as
aggressively on this issue as pro-abortion candidates,'' said David
O'Steen, executive director of the National Right to Life Committee.
   Bush campaigned for the losers in Virginia, New Jersey and New
York City. His only comment on Wednesday was ``wait 'till next
year.''
   Roman Popadiuk, a White House spokesman who normally specializes
in foreign affairs, handled political questions in the absence of
press secretary Marlin Fitzwater and told reporters, ``Suffice it
to say, this election's over with. We're pleased with the victory
that our candidates have achieved in certain elections and we're
looking forward to the 1990 elections. We're looking forward
optimistically to 1990.''
</TEXT>
