<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Report     11-09 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Report,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Full Report on Hugo Puts Damage at $4 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first comprehensive report on
Hurricane Hugo's assault on South Carolina puts the damage at $4
billion and estimates more than 40,000 people will need counseling.
   The two-inch-thick report produced last week by the state Budget
and Control Board gives a snapshot of the state through Oct. 27,
five weeks after Hugo blew ashore. It covers preliminary damage
assessments and relief efforts from 25 agencies.
   The report is expected to be updated as more precise assessments
become available.
   Hugo hit South Carolina on Sept. 21, killing 18 people in the
state and 11 others elsewhere on the U.S. mainland.
   Among the report's findings:
   _Damage was put at $4 billion, although that will undoubtedly be
adjusted once tax assessors and insurance companies refine their
figures. Gov. Carroll Campbell's spokesman, Tucker Eskew, has
quoted estimates of $5 billion to $6 billion.
   _The Federal Emergency Management Agency expects to spend $149.3
million in assistance to state and local governments. South
Carolina will dispense $8.2 million in such aid.
   _Damage to the agriculture economy, including timber, soils and
crops, is estimated at $1.4 billion or higher.
   _Forty percent of the state's 3,000 public water systems were
affected.
   _The Department of Mental Health estimates 40,069 people
statewide will need some form of counseling.
   _The value of homes destroyed was estimated by the Red Cross at
$539 million.
   _FEMA spent $16.5 million in housing aid and grants.
   _The Ports Authority estimated damage to equipment, docks and
other facilities at $12.5 million.
   _Southern Bell put damage to its phone network at $50 million.
   _Damage to schools was estimated at $55 million.
   _While the unemployment rolls swelled to nearly 300,000
immediately after the storm, only 30,000 people have applied for
unemployment compensation.
</TEXT>
