<FIRST>r a PM-GalileoManeuver     11-09 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Galileo Maneuver,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Galileo Makes its First Course Correction En Route to Jupiter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Galileo fired its thrusters today to
start the first of about 30 course corrections the craft will make
during its six-year, 2.4-billion-mile journey to Jupiter.
   ``So far everything is going just fine,'' said Neal Ausman,
Galileo mission director at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   During the three-day maneuver, which started at 8:31 a.m. PST,
Galileo will fire its thrusters in pulses of no more than two
minutes each.
   The maneuver is meant to aim Galileo for its flight past Venus
in February. The spacecraft will swoop by Venus once and Earth
twice so the planets can act as ``gravity slingshots'' to propel
Galileo toward Jupiter during the $1.9 billion mission.
   Galileo was launched from space shuttle Atlantis on Oct. 18.
   In 1995, it will separate into an orbiter and a probe. The
orbiter will circle Jupiter for 22 months, and the probe will
plunge into the planet's atmosphere to take measurements for 75
minutes until it is crushed by intense pressure.
   Galileo was about 4.55 million miles from Earth today and 58.5
million miles from Venus. It was traveling at 60,376 mph relative
to the sun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
