<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Shelter     11-09 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Shelter,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Informal Tent City In Quake-Damaged Town Frustrates Relief Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Romero took one look inside
the army tent at the Santa Cruz County Fairgrounds and walked back
out.
   ``Thank you, but the ones over there seem very isolated, and in
my personal opinion I say no,'' she told Red Cross worker Ray
Sanchez.
   ``It's too cold here, and sometimes I work until three o'clock
in the morning. I'd have no place to keep my children,'' said Marlso declining
Sanchez's invitation to move from their
informal tent camp in town to the Red Cross shelter three miles up
Routeia
Hernandez, a 152.
   The other six people Sanchez brought from the quake victims'
camp at Callaghan Park to see the shelter also said no.
   Too far from work, one said. No privacy inside the fairgrounds
gym, said another. Too cold in the tents scattered across the
grounds, said a third.
   ``It's their prerogative,'' Sanchez said. ``I'd like to see them
come out here, but I'm in no position to force them.''
   Their refusal highlighted the challenges relief workers and city
officials face in trying to provide for an estimated 480 people in
this largely Hispanic city still displaced from the Oct. 17 quake.
   About 150 of them have refused to leave their informal tent city
in Callaghan Park, distrustful of authorities, div for meals.
   ``Unfortunately, the first night he served corned beef and
cabbage,'' said Loretta Nestor, a shelter supervisor. Relief
workers are soliciting donations from vendors of Latin American
foods.
   Meanwhile, families of five or more people to a tent make do at
the park, cooking over donated barbecues and eating at a long
picnic table on the basketball court. The nearest shower is at the
YMCA two blocks away.
   Mrs. Hernandez, who works at a cannery, spoke briefly with some
residents at the fairgrounds shelter before calling her 2-year-old
daughter and going back to Callaghan.
   ``There's more privacy, and we are taking care of each other
there,'' she said.
   ``I'm going to keep trying,'' sighed Red Cross worker Sanchez.
</TEXT>
