<FIRST>u p PM-Ravenel-Party 1stLd-Writethru a0543 11-09 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ravenel-Party, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0543,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede COLUMBIA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rep. Ravenel Denies Plan to Switch Parties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Ravenel denial; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Arthur Ravenel Jr. today
dismissed speculation he is quitting the GOP for the Democratic
Party.
   ``If I was going to switch parties, I would hold a press
conference and I would tell the people at home I was switching
parties and why,'' the lawmaker said. ``I wouldn't make a switch
unless I had a compelling reason.''
   The State newspaper in Columbia today quoted unidentified
sources as saying the 62-year-old, two-term congressman feels out
of step with the Republicans and is considering becoming a Democrat
but wants assurances he can keep his committee assignments.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press from his
Washington office today, Ravenel said he is frustrated because he
has been unable to obtain a seat on the Merchant Marine and
Fisheries Committee. He called the appointment ``extremely
important to the health and wealth'' of his district.
   Ravenel said if he is rebuffed in his effort to get on the
committee, ``certainly I would consider my options.''
   He declined to say what those options might be, but when asked
if they would include defecting to the Democratic Party, he said:
``I wouldn't go that far.''
   In an interview earlier this week, Ravenel, whose coastal
district includes Hilton Head, Beaufort and Charleston and was
battered by Hurricane Hugo in September, expressed disenchantment
with the GOP, The State reported.
   He said he had been criticized by conservatives in South
Carolina for his recent support of funding for abortion in cases of
incest or rape and for backing some spending measures.
   ``I'm just not a right-winger. I'm a moderate, and it just
drives some of the Republicans back home up the wall,'' Ravenel was
quoted as saying. ``I could just as easily be a Democrat as a
Republican.''
   But Ravenel said today those comments were ``a lot of old stuff
I've been saying for a long time.''
   The congressman said that he draws on support from Democrats as
well as Republicans at election time. His district had been
historically Democratic before it went for Ronald Reagan in 1980.
   If Ravenel switched parties, it would be a coup for the
Democrats, in part because it would happen in GOP National
Committee Chairman Lee Atwater's backyard.
   A switch by Ravenel also would come on the heels of the
Democrats' sweep of Tuesday's major elections in New Jersey,
Virginia and New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Abortion     11-09 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Abortion,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Hold Unusual Abortion Protest in Soviet Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two dozen Americans held posters, lighted candles
and heard speeches outside the U.S. Embassy in a protest of the
U.S. government's abortion policy that drew puzzled looks and
laughter from Soviet passersby.
   ``It's incomprehensible! It's absurd!'' one elderly woman said
after stopping to read a poster that said in Russian, ``Return my
Body!''
   The Americans, who are studying Russian or working in Moscow,
called the demonstration in advance of more than 1,000 rallies and
other events by abortion rights activists in 150 U.S. cities
scheduled Sunday.
   The protesters assembled on the sidewalk outside the embassy's
main entrance, an area crammed with Armenians and Jews who want to
emigrate to the United States. The timing of the protest, during
the evening rush hour, also drew curious passersby.
   One woman stopped to ask what the protest was about and when
told it concerned restrictions on abortions in the United States,
she said with a laugh and smile, ``Come to us. We'll do it.''
   Abortion is the primary form of birth control in the Soviet
Union and each woman has an average of nine abortions.
   One speaker said that like Americans, Soviet women have been
deprived of the choice to have an abortion. Here, the woman said,
Soviets must have abortions because they have no contraceptives.
   Soviet police guarding the embassy entrance watched without
trying to stop the protest.
   Laurie Essig, 24, a protester who studies at the Pushkin Russian
Language Institute, said the rally was held outside the U.S.
Embassy so government representatives inside could see the
opposition to the Bush administration's abortion policies.
   With demonstrations common in Moscow on issues ranging from
democracy to emigration, one woman remarked after stopping by the
abortion protest, ``It's become so interesting here! You never get
bored.''
</TEXT>
