<FIRST>r a AM-SovietsDefect     11-09 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets Defect,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soviets Defect During Visit to Milwaukee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet men who came to town to see the
unveiling of a Russian mural have defected.
   ``We have received two asylum applications from Soviet citizens.
Those applications are pending,'' Ronald B. Swan, officer in charge
of Immigration and Naturalization Service in Milwaukee, said
Wednesday.
   He declined to identify the men but said they defected late last
week.
   They will be allowed to stay in the United States pending a
review of their applications, which could take weeks, Swan said.
   The baked clay mural, brought here as part of an art exchange
program, was unveiled last week at the Milwaukee Art Museum.
   The two men who defected were not part of the delegation of
artists and musicians who arrived here by ship with the Russian
mural, said Jim Ohlschmidt, a Milwaukee participant in the
US-Soviet exchange.
   The men flew here for the unveiling at the invitation of two
women, Ohlschmidt said.
   The men had played host to the women when a delegation from
Milwaukee presented a mural to the residents of Leningrad in July,
and the women were returning the favor, officials said.
   ``We had no idea this was going to happen. It took us by
complete surprise,'' Ohlschmidt said.
   Joel Pfeiffer, organizer of the art exchange, was quick to
distance the men from the project.
   ``They are two grown men who made a choice,'' Pfeiffer said.
``They were not part of the project. It should have absolutely no
effect on the project.''
</TEXT>
