<DOCNO> AP891109-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GlaucomaAwareness     11-09 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glaucoma Awareness,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Groups Urge Glaucoma Awareness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of national health groups launched
a campaign Thursday to raise awareness of glaucoma, especially
among blacks for whom the disease is the leading cause of blindness.
   Glaucoma is the second-leading cause of blindness among
Americans overall after diabetic retinopathy, but blacks are four
to six times as likely to get the disease as whites, medical
experts said at a news conference.
   ``Awareness is essential because glaucoma has few, if any, early
symptoms and if it is detected early blindness can be prevented,''
said Dr. Roger Mason, an associate professor at the Howard
University School of Medicine.
   An estimated 2 million Americans have glaucoma; at least 1
million have lost some sight and 80,000 are blind because of it.
   The National Society to Prevent Blindness announced a new effort
to reduce blindness from glaucoma by focusing screening and public
education on high-risk groups. The program will try to get
physicians to identify those at risk and refer them for complete
eye exams.
   Congress designated Nov. 12-18 as National Glaucoma Awareness
Week.
   Blacks, the elderly, diabetics, people who are nearsighted and
those with a family history of glaucoma are at high risk for
developing the disease, caused by a buildup of fluid pressure
inside the eye. The fluid buildup eventually damages nerve cells in
the eye.
   A recent Gallup survey found that a majority of adults
incorrectly believe that a feeling of pressure in the eyes is a
sign of glaucoma and that eye damage from the disease can be
corrected.
   Medical experts say that when detected early, the disease
usually can be controlled and vision loss prevented with drugs in
the form of eye drops, laser treatment or surgery. However,
whatever vision is lost cannot be restored.
   The disease usually has no early warning signs, though it
sometimes causes loss of side vision, difficulty in adjusting eyes
to the dark and a frequent need for new glasses. In its later
stages, glaucoma can cause eye pain, blurred vision, seeing halos
around lights, nausea and vomiting.
   Mason said a study he conducted found glaucoma occurs in blacks
at four to five times the rate in whites, while a survey by Dr.
Harry Quigley of Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine found
the rate as much as six times as high in blacks.
   Neither study identified the reason blacks are at higher risk
than whites.
   Mason said the best way to detect glaucoma is through a
comprehensive eye exam. Measuring fluid pressure in the eye _ the
most common test used in glaucoma screening _ doesn't always detect
the disease, he said.
   The coalition launching the campaign includes the National Eye
Institute, National Council on the Aging, National Medical
Association, American Diabetes Association, Lions Club
International and Lighthouse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
