<FIRST>r a AM-Sullivan-AIDS     11-09 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan-AIDS,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Chief Reaffirms Commitment to Anti-Discrimination Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling discrimination against AIDS patients
``absolutely unacceptable,'' Secretary of Health and Human Services
Louis Sullivan issued a new call Thursday for anti-discrimination
legislation.
   Sullivan, speaking at a conference on AIDS and minorities, said
the Bush administration is committed to seeing acquired immune
deficiency syndrome covered under legislation pending in Congress,
the Americans With Disabilities Act.
   ``This administration is committed to enacting legislation to
prohibit such discrimination,'' he said.
   Sullivan said AIDS has become a ``special problem'' of the
nation's poor and minorities, but added, ``This sort of
us-versus-them thinking _ this is dangerous.''
   The secretary was on friendly turf at the conference, which was
sponsored by the Morehouse School of Medicine. Sullivan, an alumnus
of Morehouse College, was founding president of the medical school
before he was appointed to the Cabinet by President Bush.
   Sullivan said part of the onus of stopping AIDS _ transmitted
chiefly through sex or drug paraphernalia _ rests with individuals,
to ``think and behave in a more constructive way'' with
``moderation, self-control and discipline.''
   He called for a ``new ethic of personal responsibility, a new
culture of character,'' not just for AIDS but for other problems
such as teen pregnancy and homicide. ``It cannot be brought about
by federal mandate,'' he said.
   He also addressed the overload of AIDS patients at medical
facilities from coast to coast.
   ``AIDS has not caused a crisis in our health care system,'' he
said. ``AIDS has simply revealed the pre-existing cracks in the
system.
   ``We have not yet made health care sufficiently available to all
American citizens. ... We must work to put our entire health care
system in order.''
</TEXT>
