<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     11-09 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>African National Congress Opens Washington Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress, an
anti-apartheid organization outlawed in South Africa, opened an
office here Thursday trying to improve relations with the United
States.
   Thabo Mbeki, the ANC's Director of International Affairs, said
the Washington office would seek to persuade the Bush
administration to impose additional economic sanctions against
South Africa.
   Mbeki told reporters the Bush administration, in marked contrast
to its predecessor, believes the existing sanctions have already
forced the South African government to liberalize its policies
toward the country's black majority.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen said recently that
while the administration opposes harsher sanctions at this time, it
would be willing to consider them if no progress is made toward
black-white negotiations in South Africa by next summer.
   Mbeki said the Bush administration differs with its predecessor
on another point. ``Clearly the Bush administration has moved away
from the notion that the South African government must be pacified,
pampered, pleased,'' he said at a news conference.
   While Bush's meetings with prominent anti-apartheid leaders such
as Archbishop Desmond Tutu and Albertina Sisulu are important,
Mbeki said, ``the greatest contribution Bush could and should make
is further sanctions.''
   The sanctions were imposed in 1986 by Congress, after it
overrode a veto by former President Reagan.
   The ANC opened a similar office in Moscow last year, and already
has about 40 representatives abroad, Mbeki said.
   Mbeki, whose father Govan Mbeki was one of seven top ANC
officials released from prison last week after 25 years in
captivity, said the United States appears committed to pushing for
an end to the racial discrimination policies in South Africa.
   He said the ANC had been encouraged by administration officials
to open its office here ``because they know we are central to the
solution of the South African problem.''
   The ANC is concerned the United States may let up pressure on
newly elected President F.W. De Klerk, who has been liberalizing
his government's policies toward blacks but has rejected giving
them the vote and maintains wide powers of arrest and censorship.
   If that turns out to be the case, Mbeki said, ``we have to
resurrect'' the pressure.
   Conservatives in Congress contend the ANC is funded by the
Soviet Union and that its armed wing is supplied by the Soviet
bloc. Mbeki said there would always be ``those who don't like us''
but that the question of Soviet support was ``not an issue'' with
the administration.
   In 1987, then-Secretary of State George Shultz met with ANC
leader Oliver Tambo. Regular meetings have been conducted with the
group's representatives ever since.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
