<FIRST>r a AM-Teen-Killing     11-09 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen-Killing,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Spares Teen From Jail in Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBRING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old mother of three who had been
abused most of her life was spared prison for the beating death of
her son by a judge who said putting her behind bars would only
continue the cycle of abuse.
   Tammie Janette Loray was sentenced Wednesday to three years in a
juvenile center on a no-contest plea Aug. 30 to second-degree
murder in the beating death of her 5-month-old son, Christopher
Cook Jr.
   ``If I take some other action now, I will not be breaking the
cycle of abuse. I will be perpetuating it,'' acting Circuit Judge
Dick Prince said.
   The girl had been sexually abused by her adoptive father from
age 4 to 11, abandoned twice by her adoptive mother and given to
other men before age 10.
   The judge told the teen-ager that her case ``involves the death
of two children because it seems to me you never had a childhood.''
   He sentenced her as a juvenile on the murder charge and as an
adult for aggravated child abuse. With 15 years' probation on the
abuse count, Miss Loray will be under the court's jurisdiction
until age 34.
   The prosecution wanted Miss Loray sentenced as an adult to 17
years in prison, and the defense asked that she be placed in
treatment for three years with no probation.
   Miss Loray and Christopher Cook Sr. took Christopher Jr. to an
emergency room March 4, 1988, where he died four days later,
authorities said.
   Her other son, Cameron Cook, was born Oct. 7, 1988, the day she
was indicted. Her first child, Marcia Cook, suffered brain damage
in September 1986. Authorities said the 3-month-old had been
violently shaken. No charges were filed.
   Psychologists, foster parents and state social workers testified
that Miss Loray is immature and suffers from severe depression and
low self-esteem.
   The judge warned the girl she faced prison if she failed to
cooperate during treatment or refused to complete programs thought
necessary by her parole officer.
</TEXT>
