<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BerthoudTunnel     11-09 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berthoud Tunnel,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Action Halts Berthoud Tunnel Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTER PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed federal tax restrictions have
halted and may collapse plans to build a tunnel under Berthoud Pass
to this ski resort.
   The Berthoud Tunnel Authority had hoped to sell $247 million in
tax-exempt bonds in December for planning and construction of the
4-mile tunnel, which would spare motorists from having to drive a
fearsome, zigzag road over the 11,315-foot gap.
   But Ronald Drake, authority president, said Wednesday that a
budget bill passed by the House in October requires that 85 percent
of tax-exempt bonds be used within five years of sale. ``That stops
the project dead in its tracks,'' he said.
   Construction isn't scheduled to start until 1992 and the tunnel
isn't due to open until 1996.
   Drake has asked members of Colorado's congressional delegation
to seek an exemption to the restrictions. A Senate version of the
bill does not include the restriction.
   The tunnel would cut 20 minutes off the 90-minute, 55-mile drive
from Denver to Winter Park. Supporters say it will bring more
skiers to Winter Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
