<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Ferry     11-09 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Ferry,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferry Owners Say Crash Could Have Been Worse</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HBG3,BRE2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREMERHAVEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferry passengers Thursday
recounted the panic after a freighter hit their ship and killed
three people, but the owners said more may have died if an
after-dinner dance had not been delayed.
   The Hamburg, a Danish ferry bound for Harwich, England, with
nearly 400 people aboard, was rammed by the 8,206-ton
Panama-registered Nordic Stream in high winds and rough seas south
of the North Sea island of Helgoland on Wednesday night.
   Three passengers _ two Britons and one German _ died and 11
people were injured when the container ship's bow punched a 60-foot
gash into the ferry's hull, according to the vessel's owner, Danish
Scandinavian Seaways.
   ``I was in the lounge just having a drink. The next thing we
knew we were flying through the air and tables and chairs and glass
were flying about,'' said Bill Peart, one of a group of British
passengers.
   ``There was a lot of panic, people were picking themselves up
off the floor and dashing to the nearest exit and trampling over
everybody,'' said Peart, 37. ``People thought it was going to
sink.''
   Witnesses said parts of the ferry's dance lounge were hanging
out of the hole in the hull. The freighter's deck was littered with
cocktail chairs from the ferry.
   The lounge was nearly empty when the crash occurred because the
leader of the ship's band was feeling sick and had postponed a
scheduled dance by half an hour, Seaways officials said. The ferry
was only about one-third full.
   The West German Transport Ministry said sea traffic controllers
had warned both boats they were sailing dangerously close to one
another. The cause of the crash was still under investigation, a
ministry statement said.
   Six seriously injured people from the ferry were flown by
helicopter to land for treatment before the Hamburg limped into
Bremerhaven.
   West German authorities said the crash occurred as the Hamburg
was steaming out to sea and the Nordic Stream was headed toward the
Elbe Channel in the direction of Hamburg harbor. A storm warning
was in effect at the time.
   Scandinavian Seaways said the ferry was carrying 96 crew members
and 277 passengers, including 60 Britons, 192 Germans, 16 Danes and
nine others of unidentified nationality.
   The ferry, which can carry 1,000 people, sails every two days
between Hamburg and Harwich.
</TEXT>
