<FIRST>r a AM-Virgin-Voyage     11-09 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virgin-Voyage,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virgin Records Chairman Announces Planned Balloon Crossing Of Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two balloonists who became the
first to cross the Atlantic Ocean in a hot air balloon announced
plans Thursday to make the first such voyage across the Pacific
Ocean.
   Richard Branson, chairman of Virgin Records and Virgin Atlantic
Airways will be co-pilot of the unnamed 19-story high silver
balloon with balloonist Per Lindstrand beginning sometime from Nov.
15 to Dec. 15, depending on weather.
   They will take off from Miyakonojo, Japan, rise 36,000 feet to
catch the jet stream and travel at speeds of 150 mph to 200 mph for
about three days before landing, if all goes as planned, somewhere
along the West Coast of the United States.
   Branson and Lindstrand became the first to successfully cross
the Atlantic in a hot air balloon flight in 1987 for a world record
distance of 3,072 miles. The Pacific journey could be as long as
6,200 miles.
   They are undertaking the journey in part to call attention to
the environment and the problems of global warming. The balloon
will carry a slogan ``Save the Planet.''
   ``It will be a great personal adventure for both of us, one of
the last great personal adventures left of this kind,'' said
Branson at a news conference in the Santa Monica Air Museum at the
city's airport.
</TEXT>
