<FIRST>r a AM-JealousySlaying     11-09 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jealousy Slaying,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Ex-Dairy Princess to Stand Trial in Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former dairy princess Lori Esker was ordered
Thursday to stand trial in the strangling of a former schoolmate
during a quarrel over a boyfriend.
   Ms. Esker, 20, of rural Hatley, is charged with first-degree
intentional homicide. The 1989 Marathon County dairy princess is
accused of strangling Lori Cihaski, 21, of Birnamwood during an
argument Sept. 20 in Ms. Cihaski's car. She resigned as dairy
princess after being charged and is free on bail.
   Ms. Esker smiled as she entered court Thursday. She wrote in a
notebook during the proceedings and visited with several friends
afterward.
   Marathon County Circuit Judge Michael Hoover set a Dec. 1
hearing for Ms. Esker to make a plea to the charge.
   Her attorney, Steven Glynn, said the three-week delay in
entering a plea was granted because prosecutors may decide to file
a different charge. No plea negotiations have started, Glynn said,
``but that doesn't mean we are not going to have conversations.''
   Glynn has filed court documents contending that statements Ms.
Esker gave detectives violated her constitutional right against
self-incrimination.
   Sheriff's Detective Randall Hoenisch testified Thursday Ms.
Esker told authorities Sept. 29 that she killed Ms. Cihaski after
Ms. Cihaski ``grabbed her and shook her.''
   Hoenisch said Ms. Esker sobbed as she recounted how the fight
between her and Ms. Cihaski broke out while the two talked about
their relationships with Eland dairy farmer Bill Buss, 25.
   Friends have said Buss, Ms. Esker's one-time boyfriend, was
about to become engaged to Ms. Cihaski. The two women were in a car
parked outside a Wausau hotel where Ms. Cihaski worked when the
fight erupted, authorities said.
   Ms. Esker, a junior at the University of Wisconsin-River Falls,
told detectives she implied she was pregnant by Buss and Ms.
Cihaski responded angrily and ``grabbed at her hair and grabbed at
her neck,'' Hoenisch testified.
   Hoenisch said Ms. Esker told him she feared for her life.
   Ms. Esker told investigators at one point she pulled Ms. Cihaski
down on the seat of the car and ``pinned her there by putting a
forearm around her throat,'' Hoenisch said.
   Ms. Esker said she saw a belt in the back of the car, grabbed it
and ``put it on Lisa Cihaski's neck,'' Hoenisch said, adding that
Ms. Esker dumped out a purse and found a mirror to check whether
Ms. Cihaski was breathing.
   ``She told us she didn't mean to hurt her,'' the detective
testified.
   More than 150 people packed the courtroom Thursday, including
Buss, Ms. Cihaski's parents, Ms. Esker's parents and Christopher
Jacobs III, a Medford dairy farmer recently acquitted on charges he
participated in the 1987 Kunz family killings in nearby Athens.
</TEXT>
