<FIRST>u w PM-US-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru a0663 11-09 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0663,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Applauds East German Decision on Travel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 9-13, On Capitol Hill, with senators quotes.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said today a decision by the
East German government to allow its citizens to travel freely was
an important step toward democratic reform.
   ``We have always called for and supported freedom of movement,''
said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``The East German decision would be an important step in the
direction of peaceful and evolutionary democratic reform. It would
seem to be a positive response to the wishes that the East German
people have voiced so strongly in the last few months,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said free travel for East
Germans would be a ``very positive development'' that the United
States would welcome.
   ``We've been talking a long time about freedom of travel being a
basic human right. We've been talking a long time about open
borders. We've been talking a long time about the importance of
seeing the wall come down,'' Baker said.
   He spoke to reporters after hosting a luncheon for Philippines
President Corazon Aquino.
   East Germany said today it was opening its borders to the rest
of the world and that its citizens can travel or emigrate anywhere,
including through the 28-year-old Berlin Wall.
   Fitzwater said, ``The country appears to have been moving in
that direction, but I think it was a surprise when it happened. At
least we had no advance warning.''
   On Capitol Hill, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, ssaid the East German decision amounts to ``the symbolic
destruction of the Berlin Wall.''
   Mitchell urged East Germany and Gorbachev to ``take the final
step and tear that wall down.''
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas said ``the Berlin
Wall and all that it represents are crumbling, even as the
communist state which built it crumbles, too.''
   He said the United States should make clear its desire that the
East German people achieve freedom and that the country's communist
government be replaced by a functioning democracy.
   ``But we should not do anything at this point which might
needlessly add fuel to the fire,'' Dole said.
   Fitzwater said providing food, clothing and housing for the
refugees does ``present problems.''
   ``I think all the countries of the world, certainly the allied
countries, stand ready to watch and help as necessary. But at this
point that hasn't been required,'' said the White House spokesman.
   So far, he said, ``the West German government has been managing
this exodus into their country pretty well.'' He said Bush and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl have talked previously about the situation.
   ``We have always urged movements toward democracy. President
Reagan called for tearing down the Berlin wall. We have been
supportive of the border release of its citizens and we think those
are important moves.''
</TEXT>
