<DOCNO> AP891109-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CatholicBishops     11-09 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catholic Bishops,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishops Urge Palestinian Homeland, Approve AIDS Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops Thursday
called upon the United States to press for Middle East talks
leading to an independent Palestinian homeland. The statement drew
immediate criticism from Jewish leaders.
   On the last day of its fall meeting, the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops also approved a statement on AIDS that rejects
condom education in public schools and the distribution of clean
needles to drug addicts.
   The bishops unanimously approved a statement on the Middle East
that declares Palestinians have a right to participate as equals in
negotiations affecting their destiny and a right to territory.
   The statement called upon the Arab states and Palestinians to
recognize Israel's right to exist, and said there must be limits
negotiated on Palestinian sovereignty to protect Israel's security.
   The bishops urged the administration to increase talks with
Palestinians, ``clearly'' express its support for a Palestinian
homeland, press Arab states to normalize relations with Israel and
urge all foreign nations, including Syria and Israel, to withdraw
from Lebanon.
   Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston said the statement is a ``sorely
needed invitation to dialogue for the cause of peace in the Middle
East.''
   But it drew criticism from American Jewish groups, including the
Synagogue Council of America, which said the bishops' report
``prejudges what can only be achieved through the process of
negotiations.''
   Rabbi A. James Rudin and Judith H. Banki of the American Jewish
Committee said the bishops' call for sovereignty ``removes
incentives for flexibility and accommodation on the part of
Palestinian leadership.''
   The AIDS statement approved in a 219-4 vote by secret ballot
rejected the bishops' conference's earlier conditional support for
condom education in public schools, urging that youngsters be
taught chastity instead.
   ``We caution young people not to be trapped into the `safe-sex'
myth, which is both a lie and a fraud,'' said Archbishop Roger
Mahony of Los Angeles, chairman of the committee that drafted the
statement.
   The statement also opposes universal mandatory AIDS testing,
calls for increasing federal funds for AIDS research, and denounces
violence and discrimination against AIDS patients.
   The statement said it builds on a 1987 document approved by the
conference's Administrative Board, but it drops a controversial
assertion in the earlier document that the church could tolerate
education about condoms in public school AIDS-prevention classes,
as long as sexual abstinence outside marriage was presented as the
``only morally correct and medically sure way'' to prevent the
deadly disease.
   Some bishops said the assertion could be misinterpreted as
condoning extramarital sex and artificial birth control.
   Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk of Cincinnati, newly elected
conference president, said in an interview that priests could still
counsel condom use in individual cases if it seemed the only
recourse, but the bishops decided against a general statement.
   On similar grounds, the bishops said supplying clean needles to
drug addicts to prevent infection from contaminated needles could
encourage drug abuse.
   Jay Blotcher, a spokesman for the AIDS Coalition to Unleash
Power in New York, said not giving youngsters information about
condoms is ``abandoning them to death.''
   Much of the debate Thursday focused on whether God should be
thought of as having a role in determining who gets AIDS. In the
end, the bishops rejected several proposed amendments on the matter.
   ``Without condoning self-destructive behavior or denying
personal responsibility, we must reject the idea that this illness
is a direct punishment by God,'' the bishops said.
   In other business Thursday, the prelates voted 175-12 to give
bishops the discretion to allow laypeople to assist at marriages
where priests or deacons are not available.
   Earlier in the week, the bishops approved a rite allowing
laypeople to conduct Sunday services, though not Mass, in the
absence of a priest. Both rules still must be approved by the
Vatican.
   Also earlier in the week, the bishops:
   _Approved a strong anti-abortion resolution, making a special
plea to Catholic legislators to work to eliminate legalized
abortion and saying that no Catholic could responsibly take a
pro-choice position.
   _Approved a statement on food policy that decried the loss of
the family farm, said the growing concentration of farmland in the
hands of large corporations threatens the common good, and called
for more rights for farmworkers and less use of chemical
fertilizers and pesticides.
   _Endorsed a plan to increase the participation of black
Catholics in the church.
   _Elected Pilarczyk, who had been confererence vice president, to
a three-year term as president. Archbishop William Keeler of
Baltimore was elected vice president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
