<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Legionnaires'Outbreak Bjt   11-09 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Legionnaires' Outbreak, Bjt,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disease Outbreak Leaves Ill Effects in Colorado Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAMAR, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of Legionnaires' disease
suspected of causing 17 illnesses and three deaths after a class
reunion has scarred the image of this agricultural community as a
wholesome convention site.
   ``There's concern, grave concern, over what this will mean to
the community,'' said Darlene Hamilton, manager of the Chamber of
Commerce of Lamar, population 8,600, which depends heavily on
tourism and conventions.
   City administrator Roy Lauricello said the town still was
reeling from a decision by a bus manufacturer to lay off 200 people
last year.
   Eighty-five people were laid off Monday when the Best Western
Cow Palace Inn closed voluntarily while health officials took more
than 200 samples from air conditioning ducts, water and the cooling
system, breeding grounds for the bacteria that cause the disease.
   The samples are being analyzed at the federal Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta, which expects to have preliminary
results next week. Health officials expressed confidence that the
Cow Palace will then reopen, after any sources of the bacteria are
sterilized.
   More than 250 people from 21 states attended a Lamar High School
reunion Sept. 22-24, held for classes of 1941 and earlier at the
Cow Palace. The motel has about 300 guests per night and brings an
average of one convention a week to Lamar, a highway crossroads
town 220 miles southeast of Denver.
   Six cases of Legionnaires' disease have been confirmed among 17
people who came down with pneumonia-like symptoms after attending
the reunion. Three of those stricken have died, and two of the
deaths involved confirmed cases of Legionnaires'. The other four
people with confirmed Legionnaires' disease recovered.
   Two other people got the disease after staying at the motel
prior to the reunion. However, health department officials said
Thursday those cases cannot be linked directly to the motel.
   Health Department spokeswoman Ann Lockhart said all of the cases
are suspected to involve Legionnaires' disease, but the health
department has to await laboratory confirmation.
   The health department canvassed those who attended the reunion
or worked at the motel, but is not trying to track down other Cow
Palace guests.
   Dr. Dan Rodrigue of the state Health Department said hundreds of
people may have been exposed, but only those with compromised
immune systems, such as the elderly, catch the disease.
   Symptoms usually appear in two to 10 days and include fever,
headache, appetite loss, muscle aches, coughs, abdominal pain and
fluid in the lungs, which sometimes leads to the disease being
misdiagnosed as pneumonia. A doctor must confirm the diagnosis with
a blood test.
   Dave Edelman, manager of the motel, said he has lived there for
14 years and neither his family nor employees became ill. Neither
have local civic leaders, who attended meetings at the motel.
   Nevertheless, the motel sat vacant this week, the indoor pool
and hot tub empty. A pale green light streamed in through a
skylight on dozens of empty tables set for guests.
   ``I don't know what we're going to do. I don't know if we can
survive this,'' said Edelman.
   Hamilton said the Business and Professional Women of Colorado
canceled its convention after news of the disease broke, costing
Lamar the money that would have been spent by 250 people. She is
worried about the Colorado Cattlemen's Association and state
convention of the Knights of Columbus next spring, but those groups
say they have made no decisions to cancel.
   Hamilton said the town is considering an expensive advertising
campaign to rebuild its image.
   ``These things stick in people's minds,'' Hamilton said. ``It's
not going away next week or next year.
   ``The damage is already done. No matter what the outcome of the
investigation, the damage is done.''
   Rodrigue, who worked without a mask while collecting samples in
the motel, said he would not be afraid to stay there once the
source of infection is discovered.
   Dr. Timothy Mastro of the CDC said a contamination usually is
neutralized with heat or chlorine, but may require continuing
periodic treatment.
   The bacterium is found in soil and grows in water, such as
air-conditioning ducts, storage tanks and rivers. Legionnaires'
disease takes its name from an outbreak at a Pennsylvania American
Legion convention in Philadelphia in 1976 that killed 34 people.
   This was the first case in Colorado, the Health Department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
