<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Border     11-09 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Border,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Electronic Barriers Removed From Hungary's Western Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has completed the dismantling
of the electronic barrier along its westernmost border, an official
said Thursday.
   Hungary began dismantling the electronic signaling devices and
barbed wire fencing along its 220-mile border with Austria on May
2, physically dismantling part of the Iron Curtain between East and
West.
   Brigadier-General Janos Szekely, the national commander of the
Hungarian border guards, told representatives of 14 political
groups that the electronic signaling devices had been removed
completely, the state MTI news agency reported.
   It was not clear from the brief report whether the barbed wire
and other fencing has also been removed completely. The removal of
all barriers originally was scheduled to be completed by Dec. 1,
1990.
   Hungary's move to dismantle the border barriers followed
legislation allowing Hungarians to travel freely. This summer, tens
of thousands of East Germans used the open stretches of border to
flee to the West until Budapest announced it would allow the East
Germans to cross legally.
</TEXT>
