<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     11-09 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Activist, Capture Members of Guerrilla Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fatally shot an armed
Palestinian in a roundup of the Red Eagles guerrillas Thursday and
killed a masked Arab activist during violent protests that erupted
after the raid, the military command said.
   Fifteen other Arabs were shot and wounded in demonstrations as
Palestinians marked the end of the 23rd month of a revolt against
Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   A general strike called by underground uprising leaders
paralyzed business and traffic and shut schools throughout the
occupied lands.
   The army command said a military force on routine duties in the
West Bank town of Nablus spotted a ``suspicious movement'' near a
house in the Jneid neighborhood before dawn Thursday.
   Israel media said troops surrounded the one-story house and used
a loudspeaker to order the suspects to come out. When they refused,
soldiers broke in through a metal door.
   ``There were six young men inside and one pulled out a pistol.
He was shot and killed, and the others were arrested and taken for
interrogation,'' an army statement said.
   The army said the victim, Iman Mohsein Al Ruzeh, and the
detainees belonged to the Red Eagles, a guerrilla group backed by
the radical Syrian-based Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, a PLO faction that opposes Yasser Arafat's peace
initiative.
   The army said Al Ruzeh, 23, was wanted for alleged involvement
in the assassinations as well as for firebomb attacks, kidnappings
and violent interrogations of suspected collaborators.
   It said Jaber Mohammed Suleiman Fuash, 19, wanted by security
forces for involvement in the killing of eight Arabs, was among the
detainees.
   The Red Eagles are believed responsible for the slayings of nine
Nablus Palestinians suspected of ``moral offenses'' or assisting
Israeli authorities, as well as of other attacks against Israeli
troops, the army said.
   ``The nine were killed after severe torture, including killings
by axes and knives,'' the statement said.
   Nablus has been the site of a large portion of slayings of Arabs
accused of helping the Israeli authorities since the uprising
began. Of 143 Arabs killed on such charges, 23 were slain in
Nablus, with most of the slayings blamed on the Red Eagles or
another guerrilla group, the Black Panther Brigades.
   Israeli officials claim some of these gangs operate under direct
orders of the PLO, but Palestinians say at least some of the
murders were carried out in defiance of Arafat's orders.
   The raid was followed by violent clashes in Nablus in which one
Palestinian was killed and four others wounded. An Israeli border
policeman suffered moderate injuries in a stone-throwing attack
after which the army clamped a curfew on the city of 120,000, the
largest in the West Bank.
   Eleven other Palestinians were shot and wounded in Gaza,
hospital officials said.
   Thursday's deaths brought to 613 the number of Arabs killed by
Israeli gunfire in the uprising. Forty Israelis have also been
slain.
</TEXT>
