<FIRST>r w AM-Walker     11-09 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walker,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Judicial Nominee, Under Fire, Vows Fairness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A San Francisco attorney criticized for his
one-time membership in a club that excludes women told senators
Thursday he fought to ease that restriction and vowed to be fair if
confirmed as a federal judge.
   ``I am more sensitive now than I was about the need for a
federal judge to conduct the courtrooms of the United States in a
way to insure fairness,'' Vaughn Walker told the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
   The vow came at a hearing into the long-stalled nomination of
Walker as a judge in the Northern District of California.
   Walker has been fighting for confirmation for almost two years
while critics have argued that his former membership in the
exclusive Olympic Club should disqualify him.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., has asked the committee not to
recommend confirmation of Walker, who has strong support from Sen.
Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio and the acting chairman of the
committee, told Walker he has doubts as to whether the resignation
from the Olympic Club, dated Feb. 15, came soon enough to indicate
Walker really disapproved of discrimination practiced by the club.
   Until 1968, the club barred blacks from membership. Critics say
it now has few blacks among its 4,700 active members. It still
refuses to admit women to full membership.
   Supreme Court Justice Anthony M. Kennedy was a member but
resigned when his name was mentioned as a possible nominee for the
high court.
   In testimony before the committee, Judge Diane Wick of Municipal
Court in San Francisco called Walker ``a fair, thoughtful and
compassionate human being.''
   Judge Ina Gyemant of Superior Court in San Francisco said Walker
helped her with her first campaign, even though her opponent was a
Republican man.
   ``I have never found him to be unfair and I do believe that he
would be unbiased,'' she said.
   Metzenbaum questioned Walker closely on why his resignation
letter was not marked as received by the Olympic Club until April
15 when he said that it was dated Feb. 15. Walker said he gave the
letter to a former club official, David Dawson, to deliver and
never saw it again.
   Republican senators expressed dismay at the two years that the
Walker nomination has been pending.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said the questions about when
Walker's nomination became effective were ``to me just
extraordinary.''
   ``What's going on here is unethical, it's unfair and it's just
dirty politics,'' Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., declared.
</TEXT>
