<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     11-09 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advisers Cite Possible Major Drawback to Linear Accelerator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advisers told Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins on Thursday that they have found a possible major drawback
to using a linear accelerator instead of nuclear reactors to make
tritium, a key ingredient in nuclear warheads.
   The 12-member Energy Research Advisory Board said in an interim
report to Watkins that the need for huge amounts of electricity to
run an accelerator could offset the machine's environmental, safety
and possible cost advantages over nuclear reactors.
   The panel is still studying the matter and is due to issue a
final report next February.
   If substantiated, the panel's interim finding could add weight
to the Bush administration's argument _ challenged by some members
of Congress _ that new nuclear reactors, not an accelerator, are
the best answer to the nation's tritium needs. The administration
has proposed spending $6.8 billion to build two new reactors.
   A linear accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which
subatomic particles are whipped at high speeds until they crash
into a target, in this case lithium clad in aluminium. The
resulting collision produces tritium, a radioactive gas used in
nuclear weapons to boost the warhead's explosive power.
   Government-owned nuclear reactors at the Savannah River Site in
South Carolina are the only source of tritium for U.S. nuclear
warheads. Those reactors, built in the early 1950s, have been idled
for repairs and safety improvements, and they are not expected to
last much beyond 2000.
   The administration says new production capacity is needed to
assure the readiness of the U.S. nuclear arsenal, although some
nuclear scientists dispute that.
   In the face of the administration's opposition to the
accelerator option, scientists at the Brookhaven and Los Alamos
national laboratories and at Westinghouse-Hanford Co. in Washington
state said earlier this year that an accelerator could produce
needed amounts of tritium more cheaply, quickly and safely than new
reactors.
   Watkins then asked the advisory board for an independent
assessment of an accelerator's potential.
   In its report, the board said one of its chief concerns is that
a linear accelerator would require between 800 megawatts and 900
megawatts of continuous power _ roughly equal to the entire
electric output of a large commercial power station.
   The board called that ``an amount that is not only costly but
may not be readily available in the time frame of the years 2000 to
2040'' when the accelerator would be working.
   It said a new power station, possibly a nuclear reactor, might
have to be built just to provide electricity for the accelerator.
In that case, the evironmental and safety advantages of an
accelerator would be ``totally submerged,'' the panel said.
   ``It may be simpler, in fact, to use a nuclear reactor to
produce tritium directly ... rather than have it, or a fossil
plant, produce electricity to operate the accelerator,'' the report
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0158 </DOCNO>
