<FIRST>r a AM-TumblewoodInvasion     11-09 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tumblewood Invasion,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tumbleweeds Keep Tumbling Into South Dakota Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBRIDGE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing winds Thursday blew more
tumbleweeds into town, while the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
contemplated how to stop an invasion that buried homes and blocked
streets.
   ``They're still coming,'' said Police Chief Brooks Johnson.
``The wind is picking up. They've been baling this morning, but
they're losing ground now.''
   Johnson said some streets that were blocked by tumbleweeds were
cleared Thursday. Officials were worried about fires from the
tinder-dry brush and traffic accidents, but Johnson said none had
been reported.
   ``Most of the people slow down and let the thistle blow across
the road before they drive through,'' he said.
   Two years of drought exposed the banks of the nearby Oahe
Reservoir, providing a perfect spot for the Russian thistle
commonly known as tumbleweed to flourish. High winds Tuesday night
launched the invasion; Thursday's forecast called for northwest
winds gusting to 35 mph.
   Crews have been trying to bale the weeds already in town, but
corps officials said Thursday they're not sure how to battle the
brush left along the reservoir.
   One option is a controlled burn, but the extent of the weeds and
the cool, windy weather could pose problems, said Mike George, a
natural resource specialist with the corps.
   Another is to chop the stringy weeds so they won't wrap around
one another into mounds that grow, snowball-fashion, as they're
tossed across the prairie.
   He estimated that several hundred acres of weeds remain on the
banks of the Missouri River.
   George said a combination of weather and geography led to the
flurry of tumbleweeds, which buried some homes in the north-central
South Dakota town of about 4,000 people.
   ``They grow all summer long, and at the first frost they die,''
he said. ``They break off right at ground level and get blown
around by the wind.''
   Other town need not worry he said, adding, ``Mobridge is fairly
unique in that it sits right on the river.''
   George said the weeds first appeared in the United States during
the late 1800s in South Dakota. The scrubby tumbleweeds have a
prairie charm that captivates the imaginations of tourists, he said.
   ``We get visitors to the lake all the time, and the two things
they just freak at are prairie dogs and tumbleweeds,'' he said.
``Only in South Dakota would you have a town taken over by
tumbleweeds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
