<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ProgramTrading     11-09 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Program Trading,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Execs Discuss Program Trading with Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Treasury Secretary Donald Regan told a
House panel Thursday that a planned bill to limit computer-driven
stock trading doesn't go far enough and suggested a ban on one form
of the market strategy.
   He targeted index arbitrage, in which speculators try to take
advantage of inconsistencies between the stock and futures markets
by simultaneously buying in one while selling in the other.
   Critics claim index arbitrage widens price swings and drives
small investors out of the market.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, plans to introduce
legislation to restrict program trading during times of extreme
market turbulence.
   But Regan, the former head of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said the
proposal ``is more of a partial solution to the problem and, if
enacted, may not cure it.''
   He told the subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee that the problem is stock index futures _ futures
contracts tied to the performance of large groups of stocks.
   Regan suggested doing away with the commodity aspects of index
futures ``to lessen volatility'' or making ``the stock market
derivatives have the same rules as stocks.''
   Regan, who now heads the Alexandria, Va., investment firm of
Regdon Associates, told the panel, ``There are just a few traders
who are selfishly rigging the market for their own benefit,'' said
   Regan, head of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. before becoming Treasury
secretary under then-President Reagan, was part of a panel of
investment company executives that called for restraining program
trading.
   The witnesses split in their recommendations of what action
Congress should take.
   ``The problem we're addressing is volatility, not the program
trading problem,'' Philip J. Purcell, chairman of Dean Witter
Financial Services Inc., said.
   Although his firm has halted index arbitrage for customer
accounts, Purcell noted: ``The public should recognize that any
steps taken to curb program trading will not cure volatility.''
   Program trading _ almost instantaneous transactions through
computerized buy and sell programs _ has been a topic of dispute
for years but the debate heated up after the Oct. 13 stock market
slide.
   When the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks dropped more
than 190 points last month, many critics said the situation was
worsened by program trading _ especially index arbitrage.
   The panel members agreed that market volatility scares investors
out of the market, making it more difficult for U.S. companies to
raise capital through the sale of securities.
   Most of Wall Street's large investment houses recently have
revised their policies on index arbitrage.
   And the New York Stock Exchange has called on large,
institutional investors to curb program trading while ways to
handle the bursts of stock orders it generates are considered.
   Markey's plan would grant emergency powers to the Securities and
Exchange Commission to temporarily halt program trading during
extreme market turbulence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
