<DOCNO> AP891109-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GalileoManeuver     11-09 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Galileo Maneuver,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrusters Fire as Galileo Starts First Trajectory Change on Jupiter
Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three weeks after its launch from a
shuttle, the Galileo spacecraft fired its thrusters Thursday to
begin the first of about 30 course changes needed for its
roundabout six-year trip to Jupiter.
   ``We've started the first trajectory correction maneuver,''
mission director Neal Ausman said after the three-day series of
thruster ignitions got under way at 8:31 a.m. PST.
   During the maneuver, Galileo is firing four of its 12 thrusters
in a series of pulses, he said. No individual pulse exceeds two
minutes, each set of pulses takes about 45 minutes, and the entire
maneuver will be completed Saturday night.
   Two other thrusters may be used to correct the spacecraft's rate
of spin and the direction toward which it points, said Ausman, of
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The trajectory change is meant to aim Galileo for its flight
past Venus in February. The spacecraft, launched from space shuttle
Atlantis on Oct. 18, will swoop by Venus once and Earth twice so
the planets can act as ``gravity slingshots'' to propel Galileo
toward Jupiter during the $1.9 billion mission.
   On Thursday, Galileo was about 31 million miles into its looping
2.4 billion-mile journey to the solar system's largest planet,
Ausman said. It was about 4.6 million miles from Earth and 58.5
million miles from Venus, traveling at 60,376 mph relative to the
sun.
   In July 1995, Galileo will separate into an orbiter and a probe.
The orbiter will circle Jupiter for 22 months starting in December
1995, the same month the probe will parachute into the Jovian
atmosphere, making measurements for 75 minutes until it is crushed
by intense pressure.
   About 30 course corrections involving thruster firings spread
over 135 days will be required en route to Jupiter, Ausman said.
   Galileo has ignited its 3.5 inch-long thrusters on other
occasions, but those firings were to adjust spin or direction,
Ausman said. The three-day maneuver that started Thursday is
Galileo's first trajectory correction, he added.
   Ausman said the West German-built thrusters have to fire in
pulses to avoid contaminating sensitive parts of Galileo. The
thrusters are attached to the spinning part of Galileo, and can
fire only when they are not above sensitive areas on the
non-spinning section of the spacecraft.
   The thrusters also are fired in pulses because NASA fears
continuous firing might make them overheat and burn through, a
problem that developed on the same type of thrusters on two
satellites in recent years, Ausman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     11-09 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Names Loyal Supporter to Head New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turgut Ozal was sworn in as Turkey's
second civilian president Thursday and named a loyal follower to
succeed him as premier in an apparent attempt to maintain control
from his new, weaker post.
   Ozal named Parliament speaker Yildirim Akbulut just hours after
he was inaugurated.
   Elected by Parliament, Ozal assumed power from Kenan Evren,
leader of the 1980 military coup, who completed a seven-year
presidential term and by law could not run for re-election.
   The choice of Akbulut was dictated in part by fear that
factional fighting could disintegrate the governing Motherland
Party that has been held together by Ozal's leadership, political
analysts said.
   Akbulut quickly announced a Cabinet almost identical to the
previous one. Two state ministers were left out and seven new ones
were added.
   The 450-member Parliament, where the Motherland commands a
majority of 283 seats, will have a vote of confidence on the new
government sometime next week. The legislature will also elect a
new speaker.
   Included in the Cabinet were just about anyone likely to mount a
campaign for party leadership, which is to be decided in a
convention Nov. 17.
   Ozal, 62, was elected Turkey's eight president on a third ballot
Oct. 31 with the votes of 263 Motherland deputies.
   Opposition Social Democrat and centrist True Path parties
boycotted the inauguration ceremony just as they did the Parliament
sessions for the election of the president.
   The opposition has maintained that Ozal, blamed for 75 percent
inflation two years running and his popularity shrunken in the wake
of charges of nepotism and corruption in government ranks, lacked a
clear mandate necessary for the presidential post.
   They also claim he would transform the job with little executive
power into an imperial presidency, running the Motherland Party
from behind scenes, in violation of the constitution.
   In the presidential oath, accompanied by a 101-salvo cannon
salute, Ozal pledged to be free of bias. He said later, in an
inauguration address, that he would be true to his oath ``at the
cost of my life'' if necessary.
   Ozal first acquired political fame as deputy premier of the
military government when he initiated the 1980 economic rescue
program. He became premier in 1983 general elections restoring
civilian rule and Turkey enjoyed export-led growth under his
free-market economic policies.
   But high inflation, the price of the boom, has made economic
planning difficult, the poor have become poorer and the middle
class has shrunk.
   When he was elected president Ozal's public support was around
17 percent, according to public opinion polls.
   Akbulut, 52, served as interior minister in one of Ozal's
Cabinets until he was elected parliament speaker following 1987
general elections.
   The premier-designate is known as a moderate in the party which
includes liberal, Moslem fundamentalist and ultra-nationalist
factions.
   Akbulut raised the number of ministers to 30 from previous 25,
adding five more state ministerships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq     11-09 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq to Open Waterway Linking Basra, Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers have dredged a 14-mile river to
open Iraq's largest port to major commercial traffic from the
Persian Gulf for the first time since the war with Iran began in
1980, an official said Thursday.
   Millions of tons of silt were removed from the Shatt-Al-Basra
River to make it navigable for medium and small-size vessels from
the southern port city of Basra to the gulf, said Sami Ajmi Kadum,
director-general of the government-run al-Muthana Irrigation Co.
   He said cargo ships with hulls up to 33 feet deep will be able
to navigate the waterway beginning Nov. 15, opening up the
war-battered south to expanded trade under Iraq's postwar
reconstruction drive.
   The waterway, which connects with the 30-mile-long Khor
Al-Zubair River that leads to the gulf, is an alternative to the
disputed and still-blocked Shatt-Al-Arab waterway, Iraq's main
outlet to the gulf before the war. It is also about half the
distance.
   The $12 million project was launched in October 1988 in a drive
to reopen Basra to commercial shipping, two months after the
cease-fire in the 8-year war with Iran. The port was shutdown when
the war began in September 1980.
   Kadum said millions of tons of silt have been dredged from the
channel between Basra's Maqal port and Khor Al-Zubair to the south.
There the waterway links with the Khor Al-Zubair river that runs
into the northern waters of the gulf through Umm Qasr, near the
Kuwaiti border.
   Kadum said the Shatt-Al-Basra was widened to 315 feet and its
depth increased by 19{ feet. It is fed by the Euphrates River and
Iraq's southern marshes.
   Iraq has demanded the Iranians allow the Shatt-Al-Arab, the
southern boundary between the two countries, to be reopened under a
United Nations cease-fire resolution.
   But Iran has refused to do so until Iraq agrees to abide by a
1975 treaty that draws the border down the middle of the waterway,
which is still blocked by war debris.
   Iraq says it abrogated the treaty a few days before war broke
out and insists that the border runs down the eastern, Iranian
shore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-US     11-09 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-US,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Says U.S. Release of Some Frozen Assets Not Sign of Good Will</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iranian official said Thursday
that Washington's decision to release $567 million in frozen
Iranian assets was not a sign of U.S. good will.
   Since the repayment was ordered by a claims tribunal, ``it has
nothing to do with the U.S. administration's good will,'' Mahmoud
Vaezi, deputy foreign minister for European and American affairs,
said in Iranian news reports monitored in Cyprus.
   Iran has linked any effort to help free 18 Westerners held
hostage by Islamic groups in Lebanon to the U.S. releasing Iranian
assets frozen since 1979.
   The assets which Washington said Monday that it would release
are only a small portion of what Iran claims. President Bush said
Tuesday he hoped the action will prompt Iran to obtain freedom for
U.S. hostages, though administration officials said the decision to
transfer the money was unrelated to the hostage issue.
   Iran says the assets frozen a decade ago are up to $12 billion,
including the value of weapons purchased before the 1979 Islamic
revolution but never delivered.
   The assets were frozen after militants stormed the U.S. Embassy
in Tehran Nov. 4, 1979, and held American diplomats and other
personnel hostage. Fifty-two captives were released 444 days later.
   Earlier Thursday, in the first public reaction to the U.S.
decision, the Tehran Times newspaper said in an editorial that the
release was insufficient.
   The newspaper, which is close to Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani, did not elaborate on the ``goodwill'' Iran is seeking
before mediating a release of the hostages held by Shiite Moslem
zealots.
   Rafsanjani, leader of the so-called pragmatists in Iran, told a
news conference last month that Iran would help secure the release
of the captives, including eight Americans, if Washington unblocks
Iranian assets.
   The money was held in a fund to guarantee American bank claims
against Iran. Most of those claims were settled in the past few
weeks, U.S. officials said.
   In addition to the Americans, the hostages in Lebanon are four
Britons, two Swiss, two West Germans, an Irishman and an Italian.
</TEXT>
