<DOCNO> AP891109-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Homeless     11-09 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Homeless,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Creates A Different Kind Of Disaster Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake that tore through Northern
California has been a postgraduate school for veteran Red Cross
worker Al Green, who says the disaster has produced a ``different
kind of clientele.''
   ``This has been a real learning experience for me,'' said Green,
who runs an Army base shelter that opened after the Oct. 17
earthquake.
   Shelters normally are designed to close quickly, said Green, 64,
a volunteer from Camden, Ohio, who has worked on 24 disasters.
   ``We figure a shelter will be closed in four days,'' he said in
his office at the Presidio while children played on the barracks
porch. More than three weeks have passed since the 7.1-magnitude
quake struck, killing 66 people and causing an estimated $7 billion
damage.
   In other disasters, said Green, the victims belonged to
``families where their houses were destroyed. They received
temporary shelter and then were gone. Here, it's also people who
lived in hotels, apartments, maybe on the streets. Some keep coming
back.''
   Red Cross officials estimated about 6,000 people needed help
after the quake. There are about 300 people now at the three
shelters on the Army base and fewer than 200 in a downtown shelter.
   While Green talked, a woman wearing a robe walked down the hall,
apparently after washing her hair. Outside, a man, his wife and
another woman watched children playing.
   The scene was almost pastoral compared to the more tense
atmosphere in the Red Cross shelter in downtown San Francisco,
where single men are housed and were shouting matches and even
brawls are not unknown.
   ``We only have men here,'' shelter manager Norma Brandt said.
``The bed count is now 125, down from a top of 300. Some of the
people we helped have gotten jobs and everyone staying in the
shelter has been verified as a quake victim.''
   No questions were asked in the immediate aftermath of the quake,
said Red Cross spokesman Bob Page.
   ``We just helped anyone one who needed it,'' said Page. ``A few
days ago, we started to limit shelter to those who could prove they
lived in a residence before the quake. Then again, your home before
the quake could have been a park bench.''
   As if to underscore the new limit on who may live there, a man
who had recently been told to leave yelled at Page as Page walked
to his car, telling him it would be ``smart'' to check under the
hood for explosives.
   Other men outside ticked off a list of complaints, ranging from
the food to the lack of showers.
   Michael McCabe, 37, has lived in the shelter since Oct. 25 when
he returned from a trip to find his Marina apartment destroyed.
   ``I lost everything, even my car,'' said McCabe, taking notes
for a book on the earthquake.
   McCabe said some of the men's gripes were legitimate.
   ``We had just cold cereal for breakfast this morning. Last night
it was chicken patties. We get lots of potatoes _ even had them
three times a day once.''
   San Francisco had a homeless problem before the quake and
officials have warned that unless low-income housing wrecked in the
disaster is replaced, the situation will only get worse.
   An estimated 80 percent of the housing left uninhabitable was
marked for the poor. Brad Paul, deputy mayor for housing, said
1,170 housing units were declared unsafe and 3,000 more were found
to need repairs.
   Worse still, city spokesman Erik Shapiro said the earthquake
destroyed ``a good part of the city's homeless program.''
   The program paid for a night's lodging for transients at certain
hotels. Shapiro figured the quake demolished 25 percent of those
hotel rooms.
   It isn't as if San Francisco hasn't gone through this before.
The massive quake in April 1906 left far more homeless.
   By winter, some 25,000 people still lived in tents around the
city. The Army Corps of Engineers eventually designed wooden
``earthquake shacks.''
   Why not again?
   For one thing, a lot in 1906 cost only $250.
   ``The opportunities for finding cheap land are much reduced from
those days, when many parts of the city were totally undeveloped,''
said Paul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Archives-PhilipMorris     11-09 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Archives-Philip Morris,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Criticizes Cigarette Company's Link to National Archives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer health group asked Congress on
Thursday to cancel immediately a contract that makes Philip Morris
Companies, Inc. part of a National Archives campaign to celebrate
the 200th anniversary of the Bill of Rights.
   ``This joint venture smears the Bill of Rights with the blood of
all Americans killed as a result of smoking Marlboro and other
Philip Morris cigarettes,'' said Sidney Wolfe, director of Public
Citizen Health Research Group in a letter to Sen. Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M.
   Bingaman heads the Government Affairs Committee's subcommittee
on government information which has jurisdiction over the Archives.
   Guy L. Smith, vice president of corporate affairs for Philip
Morris, said in a telephone interview, ``The campaign has nothing
to do with cigarettes. It's about the celebration of the Bill of
Rights.''
   Don Wilson, archivist of the United States, said in a brief
written statement, ``The dialogue regarding our relationship with a
private corporation is a prime example of why the Bill of Rights is
important.''
   Wilson said he entered into the agreement because he wanted ``to
make this charter of freedom available to all Americans'' and
Philip Morris could support the educational effort.
   Philip Morris' Smith said his company already has gotten more
than 200,000 phone requests for copies of the document which Philip
Morris will provide.
   Wolfe, who founded the Health Research Group in 1971 with
consumer advocate Ralph Nader, said, ``The National Archives'
decision to formally join Philip Morris' effort to wrap itself in
the Bill of Rights and obscure its deadly role in American and
worldwide society must be reversed.''
   The campaign gives Philip Morris the opportunity to be ``back on
the air again,'' despite a government ban on broadcast
advertisements for tobacco products, he said at a news conference.
He acknowledged the campaign doesn't include explicit advertising.
   Under the agreement, Philip Morris will donate $600,000 to the
National Archives Trust Fund and be allowed to publish or broadcast
announcements and promotional materials referring to the Archives.
The Archives will assist by providing recordings of famous
Americans' voices to be used in the campaign.
   A nationally televised public service announcement that is a
part of the campaign includes the voices of the late President
Kennedy, former Sen. Barry Goldwater and the late Martin Luther
King Jr. over images of the Bill of Rights and scenes from civil
rights demonstrations. The announcement identifies Philip Morris as
the sponsor.
   ``We are only identified at the very end and we consciously
separated the identification of the company from the messages about
the themes of the Bill of Rights,'' said Smith.
   ``What would Martin Luther King or Harry Truman think if they
knew their voices were being made available by the National
Archives in order to improve the image of a company with the deadly
record of Philip Morris?'' asked Wolfe in his letter.
   Wolfe said Archives staff members have told him $475,000 of the
company's contribution will go for an exhibit gallery in the
National Archives building and the remaining $125,000 will give the
company the first charter membership in an association, as yet to
be established, that will solicit corporate donations to do the
work of the Archives.
   Wolfe criticized commercialization of ``space in the building
which houses the symbols of our nation'' and said the formation of
``a National Archives Corporate Boosters' Club'' raises questions
about the importance Congress places on the basic documents of
American history if it won't provide adequate public funding for
the work of the government repository.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0170 </DOCNO>
