<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     11-09 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels: Kabul Release of List of Slain Prisoners a Ploy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas on Thursday said
the Afghan government resurrected a 9-year-old list of executed
political prisoners as a ploy to distance themselves from their
Marxist predecessors.
   Lord Nicholas Bethell, a British member of the European
Parliament, turned over a copy of the list to officials of the
insurgents' Afghan government-in-exile in Pakistan.
   Bethell said Afghan President Najib gave him the list containing
thousands of names on a visit to Kabul last week where he secured
the release of three rebel prisoners.
   An Afghan rebel spokesman in Pakistan, Najibullah Lafrey, said
the list was first published in 1980. ``I'm not sure what the
purpose of this is, except to try to distance themselves from the
past,'' he said.
   It contained names of thousands of people secret police executed
in the 20 months after the April 1978 coup that brought Communists
to power. It included two former prime ministers, Noor Ahmad
Etimadi and Mohammad Musa Shafiq.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979. They
installed a new leader, then remained to help fight a growing
anti-communist insurgency before withdrawing this year.
   Afghanistan's first Communist leaders were Nur Mohammad Taraki
and Hafizullah Amin of the Khalq faction of the People's Democratic
Party of Afghanistan. Both eventually were assassinated.
   The Soviets replaced Amin in 1979 with rival Babrak Karmal of
the party's Parcham wing. Najib, of the same faction, became head
of secret police for the next five years.
   Najib was installed as party chief in 1986 after Karmal stepped
down for health reasons.
   When Karmal issued the list of secret police victims in February
1980, it was seen as an attempt to discredit Karmal's predecessors.
It is still available in Kabul bookshops.
   Lefrey charged the list was being resurrected to further
distance Najib from his party's Communist revolutionary roots.
   The Kabul government in recent years has attempted to shed its
Marxist taint in favor of Islam, Afghanistan's dominant religion,
in an effort to broaden its support.
   But the guerrillas have fought bitterly to topple it and
establish an all-Moslem government.
   Bethell told The Associated Press that said some Kabul lawmakers
``mentioned there had been a list of 11,000 in the early years of
the revolution'' but he did not know whether his was a carbon copy
of the earlier one.
   ``While Najib was head of Khad he did much worse than what was
on that list,'' Lefrey charged. ``Some think the number of people
who have been executed is 70,000 to 80,000 in the past 10 years.''
</TEXT>
