<DOCNO> AP891109-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SeafoodSafety     11-09 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seafood Safety,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocates: Seafood Should Be Inspected Like Beef, Poultry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The absence of federal seafood inspection puts
U.S. fishermen at a competitive disadvantage and leaves consumers
unsure about the quality of fish, witnesses told a congressional
hearing Thursday.
   House Democrats representing coastal districts are pushing the
Bush administration to back a plan for federally funded inspections
to provide consumers the same quality assurances available for
chicken and beef.
   Administration officials told the Subcommittee on Fisheries and
Wildlife Conservation and the Environment that they have reached no
decision on the issue.
   ``The administration has not come to the conclusion that it is
not needed right now,'' said James Brennan of the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration. But he added, ``The administration
has not come down on a position on what it wants to do.''
   Brennan's comment drew a sharp rebuke from the subcommittee
chairman, Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., who said, ``I don't think
we've had a matter of consequence before this committee on which
the administration has had a position.''
   The cost of a federally funded seafood inspection program could
range from $50 million to $80 million, according to Lester Crawford
of the Agriculture Department's Food Safety Inspection Service.
Currently the seafood industry pays about $6 million _ as much as
$100,000 per year for an individual company _ for seafood
inspections.
   Brennan said one reason for the administration's reluctance to
provide financing is that seafood inspection is a direct benefit to
the industry because it promotes consumer confidence.
   ``In essence we're talking about how to promote the U.S.
industry and whether the U.S. industry should pay for it,'' Brennan
said.
   Studds said that the beef and poultry industries benefit from
government-financed inspections while fishmermen must pay for their
own.
   Over eight years, the subcommittee said, consumption of
commercial seafood rose by 20 percent a year to a record high in
1987 of 15.4 pounds per capita.
</TEXT>
