<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     11-09 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Tightened to Curb Crime Before Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government on Thursday
stepped up security to curb a wave of crime that opposition leaders
say is a serious threat to next month's elections and the country's
transition to democratic rule.
   Police patrols were reinforced in this capital of 5 million
people, especially in areas where banks and shops are concentrated.
Police carrying submachine guns and wearing bulletproof vests were
seen in Santiago's center.
   Police said all vacations and days off were temporarily
suspended in the 29,000-member force.
   The government's reaction came after a series of often violent
robberies of banks, supermarkets, shops and private residences, and
several incidents of violence related to the current campaign for
the presidential and congressional elections scheduled for Dec. 14.
   Patricio Aylwin, the opposition presidential candidate, highly
favored by most polls to win, suggested radical pro-government
groups may be behind the crime wave.
   ``An atmosphere of violence and unrest only serves those who
know are going to lose'' the election, Aylwin said in southern
Chile, where he is campaigning.
   The election will mark the restoration of civilian rule in
Chile, which has been ruled by an authoritarian military regime
since the 1973 coup led by right-wing President Gen. Augusto
Pinochet.
   Police records show violent incidents have occurred almost daily
for five weeks. On Wednesday, two armed men wearing ski masks
entered the home of Enrique Silva, a leading opposition politician,
severely beat his wife and fled.
   Wilson Tapia, Silva's son-in-law, said the men first demanded
money and jewels but then fled with only a box containing family
documents and souvenirs. Tapia said ``the men did not look like
common criminals.''
   Earlier this month, similar incidents occurred at the homes of
two well-known television journalists.
   In the most serious political incident, Jecar Neghme, leader of
a radical leftist group, was assasinated Sept. 30. No arrests have
been reported.
   After the incident at Silva's residence opposition leaders said
the series of violent crimes may be part of an effort to interfere
in the election campaign.
   The coalition of 17 parties supporting Aylwin said in a
statement: ``These criminal actions constitute a suspicious pattern
of provocations and an apparently well-planned effort to scare and
alarm citizens.''
   Mario Astorga, Vice President of Silva's Radical Party, claimed
his party has information that members of the government's secret
police ``are operating in this situations.'' He did not elaborate.
   Former Finance Minister Hernan Buchi, the pro-government
presidential candidate, said the incident at Silva's home ``is more
than just a common crime. It can be interpreted as an attack on the
process of democratic restoration.''
   He said ``the government has the obligation'' of investigating
and arresting the attackers.
   The government said it will ``ensure the country's tranquility
and security and will maintain public order'' during the campaign
and until the inauguration of the new government next March 11.
   Col. Cristian Labbe, the government's Secretary General, accused
the opposition of trying to ``make political gains from a situation
that worries the entire country.''
   Pinochet was obliged to call the election after last year's
referendum in which voters rejected a military proposal to extend
his rule until 1997.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
