<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Aerosol-Smog     11-09 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerosol-Smog,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aerosol Deodorants Will Be Illegal After 1995 Unless Safe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aerosol deodorants will be banned in
California within six years, unless their makers can find
alternatives to harmful air pollutants emitted by the spray cans, a
state regulatory agency ruled.
   The decision Wednesday by the Air Resources Board was its first
step in adopting a plan to reduce pollution from a variety of
consumer aerosol products. The board ordered an 80 percent cut in
hydrocarbons found in spray cans by Jan. 1, 1995.
   ``This landmark action requires manufacturers to use more
environmentally acceptable substitutes if they choose to continue
selling aerosols and will likely set a precedent for other consumer
product actions that follow,'' board Chairwoman Jananne Sharpless
said in a statement.
   Hydrocarbons, one of many sources of smog and other pollution
that scientists say harm human lungs, are used as a propellant in
many spray products.
   Only a very few hydrocarbons are known to harm the Earth's
ozone. They became popular after 1978 when chlorofluorocarbons, or
CFCs, were banned in the United States because of their danger to
the ozone layer.
   Representatives of the aerosol industry attacked the decision,
saying it would force them to withdraw some products from the
California market.
   Other new regulations under consideration for household products
and for fuels and industrial processes include a proposed
regulation to control smoke from wood stoves in homes.
   Aerosol products, from hair spray to pesticides, will come under
board scrutiny in coming months, Sharpless said. Wednesday's
decision applied to deodorants.
   The agency is not attempting to ``pass a judgment on any
particular type of product'' or put manufacturers out of business,
she said.
   Sharpless called higher prices that could result from the
regulation the price consumers must pay for a safe environment.
   The board heard from a number of industry representatives who
said the deadlines were unrealistic and that some companies may
have to take their products out of the California market.
   The board, nonetheless, voted 6-2 to adopt the
deodorant-antiperspirant regulation. The dissenters, Dr. Eugene
Boston of Fullerton and Mayor Roberta Hughan of Gilroy, said they
were voting ``no'' because they wanted a tougher regulation.
   The 1995 ban is part of a complex regulation that would allow
exceptions for manufacturers to keep some polluting aerosol
products on the market until 1999.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
