<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Pay 1stLd-Writethru a0683 11-09 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Pay, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Sees Congressional Pay Raise Despite Budget Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last two grafs to CORRECT pay history; expands lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley said Thursday
that Congress will consider giving itself a pay raise even if it
fails to resolve the budget crisis that has the Pentagon
threatening tens of thousands of layoffs.
   But other lawmakers said passing the pay raise and ethics reform
package is already a politically dicey proposition and could fail
unless Congress first puts the government's fiscal affairs in
better order.
   Foley, D-Wash., has been meeting with leaders of both parties in
an effort to push through a pay raise this year as part of a
package that also would tighten congressional ethics regulations,
including clamping down on accepting fees for speeches to interest
groups.
   Foley and House Republican leaders have been working with the
White House to craft a package acceptable to the Senate and to
President Bush. Last week, Bush spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
indicated the president's willingness to look at such a proposal
but the president himself was silent.
   ``I think when the time comes... the president will be
forthcoming in his support,'' Foley said.
   Members of Congress are paid $89,500 a year. A plan to boost
salaries by 51 percent was killed earlier this year after a storm
of public protest.
   The House leadership has been briefing members this week on
their new plan, which includes a pay raise of about 8 percent to go
into effect January 1 and another 25 percent boost a year later.
The raise would apply to members of Congress, federal judges, and
top executive branch officials.
   Foley said he thought the package could be brought before the
full House as early as next week. He said it would move forward
even if Congress has failed to address government-wide spending
cuts ordered last month because lawmakers have failed to reduce the
federal deficit.
   ``That is a separate matter ... I don't think we are likely to
see any direct connection between the two,'' Foley said.
   Those cutbacks, required by the Gramm-Rudman law, cut many
domestic and military programs. Pentagon officials testified this
week that the 2.1 million active duty armed forces would have to be
reduced by about 229,000 in the next year.
   The Democratic-controlled Congress and the president are
currently in negotiations over a deficit-reduction bill which would
cancel those cutbacks. House Budget Committee Chairman Leon
Panetta, D-Wash., said he hoped to produce a bill by the end of
next week.
   If that effort fails, he said he thought passage of a pay
increase was unlikely.
   ``Whether people like it or not, the two issues are tied very
closely together,'' he said.
   What could become untied in the future is the salary of House
and Senate members.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine., and Republican
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said this week the Senate would accept,
perhaps without even a vote, a ``cost-of-living'' adjustment _
which is what the House leaders are calling the 8 percent raise
next January.
   Senators generally are wealthier than House members, and their
rules allow them to keep more speaking fees than their colleagues
across the Capitol.
   ``There's not a lot of support in the Senate for a pay raise,''
Mitchell said.
   If the Congress approved a pay raise for the House and not the
Senate, ``It would be odd,'' said Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who
said he supports raising Senate salaries and eliminating the
acceptance of honoraria.
   But it would not be unprecedented. From Dec. 21, 1982 through
July 1, 1983, House members were paid $69,800 and the Senate
$60,662.
</TEXT>
