<FIRST>r w AM-WorkPermits     11-09 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Work Permits,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Opposes Work Cards for Citizens, Aliens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration official testified
Thursday against a proposal that the government issue ``work
authorization cards'' on request both to citizens and to aliens
eligible to work in this country.
   Such cards would be used largely by immigrants, distinguishing
those who are in this country legally from those who are here
illicitly.
   ``This could lead to discrimination against those individuals
who do not have the card,'' said Paul W. Virtue, acting general
counsel for the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   He added that such a card might be viewed as a national identity
card, which Congress has forbidden.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., who sponsored the proposal for
a work authorization card, said that Social Security cards are used
much like identity cards.
   Morrison said the card he proposed would help prevent fraud and
discourage employers from discriminating against various groups.
   They spoke at a hearing of the subcommittee on Immigration,
which Morrison chairs. The subcommittee is part of the House
Judiciary Committee.
   Opposition to Morrison's idea also came from the General
Accounting Office, an investigative agency of Congress, and from
the American Civil Liberties Union.
   But there was favorable comment from the National Restaurant
Association.
  
</TEXT>
