<FIRST>u i AM-China-Kissinger     11-09 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Kissinger,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Thanks Yang for Cold Remedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Yang Shangkun gave a dinner for Henry
Kissinger on Thursday and the former secretary of state thanked him
for a cold remedy provided a year ago.
   Reporters allowed to cover the beginning of the meeting at a
government-run hotel overheard this exchange between Kissinger and
the 82-year-old former general:
   Kissinger: You look very well. I haven't seen you for a long
time _ one year. You gave me some medicine. ... It was very
effective.
   Yang: The best way to overcome a cold is to have a good sleep,
then no cold tomorrow.
   Li Jinhua, a Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, said Kissinger
renewed acquaintances earlier in the day with Premier Li Peng and
Communist Party chief Jiang Zemin.
   She said the former secretary of state and Jiang ``held friendly
and cordial talks on major issues of mutual interest.''
   ``Both were very glad to meet again in Beijing and recall their
friendship,'' Ms. Li said.
   Li Peng and Kissinger ``exchanged views extensively and in-depth
on issues of economic construction and other issues of mutual
interest,'' she said.
   Kissinger is making what is believed to be his 15th trip to
China since a secret visit in 1971 that set the stage for
normalization of relations between the two countries.
   He was scheduled to meet on Friday with senior leader Deng
Xiaoping and Li Tieying, the education minister.
