<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietGrain     11-09 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Grain,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvest Above Expectations, but Imports Still Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Thursday that
the Soviet Union's 1989 grain harvest turned out larger than
predicted but that Moscow still must import huge amounts of grain
in the year ahead.
   Currently, the department expects the Soviet harvest to total
208 million metric tons, an increase of three million tons from the
previous forecast.
   That would compare with 195.1 million tons in 1988 and would be
the fifth largest Soviet harvest on record, exceeded by 237.4
million tons in 1978, 223.8 million in 1976, 211.4 million in 1987,
and 210.1 million in 1986.
   Production of rye, barley, oats, corn, sorghum and millet _
so-called coarse grain _ was indicated at 105.5 million tons, up
2.5 million from the previous forecast in October. Wheat output was
unchanged at 89 million tons, but miscellaneous grain was increased
by 500,000 tons to 13.5 million.
   Total grain imports by the Soviet Union in the 1989-90 trade
year, which began July 1, were estimated at 37 million tons, up
three million from earlier. That would still be short of the 39
million tons imported in 1987-88 and the record 55.5 million in
1984-85.
   No specific breakdown showing U.S. shares of the Soviet trade
was included, but the report noted that Moscow was recently cleared
to buy 16 million tons of U.S. grain in 1989-90 under a long-term
agreement.
   However, the agreement year began on Oct. 1, so the comparisons
are not exact. In 1988-89, the Soviets bought a record of 21.7
million tons of U.S. wheat and corn, and so far this year have
purchased 8.1 million tons for 1989-90 delivery.
</TEXT>
