<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-USSIowa 1stLd-Writethru a0629 11-09 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-USS Iowa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Oakar Questions Navy Decision on USS Iowa Skipper</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with Senate Armed Services Committee hearing
scheduled next Thursday, witness list</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congresswoman Thursday questioned the Navy's
decision to make the skipper of the USS Iowa eligible for another
major command in light of inquiries into the battleship blast that
killed 47 sailors.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, said she was asking Navy Secretary
Lawrence Garrett III to explain the ``alleged selection'' of Capt.
Fred P. Moosally for sequential major command.
   The Navy investigation concluded that gunner's mate Clayton
Hartwig of Ohio ``most likely'' caused the April 19 explosion by
inserting some type of detonator between bags of gunpowder in one
of the ship's 16-inch guns.
   Members of Congress, Hartwig's family and shipmates have
criticized the report. Oakar has asked the General Accounting
Office, the investigative arm of Congress, to review the Navy's
findings.
   The Navy screening board that took the action on Moosally
includes Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who headed the service's
investigation into the explosion, Oakar said.
   ``I realize that consideration and possible selection of Capt.
Moosally does not commit the Navy to consider him for sequential
major command, but I question the propriety of such action while
there are several congressional and Navy investigations ongoing,''
Oakar said.
   Moosally, Oakar said, received a non-punitive ``letter of
admonition'' Oct. 3 after an administrative hearing on the Iowa
explosion.
   A sequential major command for a Navy officer would be a move
from commanding a cruiser or battleship to another similar command,
Navy officials said.
   ``The selection or non-selection of an individual is predicated
on his or her past performance and an individual's entire career
and his or her performance during that entire career is
considered,'' said Cmdr. Craig Quigley at the Pentagon.
   ``If someone is selected, that means they are just eligible,''
Quigley said.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of a House Armed
Services subcommittee that's reviewing the matter, cited an FBI
report that said its laboratory inquiry was inconclusive about what
caused the explosion.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee will question Milligan,
Moosally and Robert J. Powers, who heads the criminal division of
the Naval Investigative Service, at a hearing Nov. 16.
</TEXT>
