<FIRST>r w AM-Barbados-Ambassador     11-09 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbados-Ambassador,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Delays Ambassador Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator delayed action Thursday on President
Bush's choice to be ambassador to Barbados, saying the nominee's
only qualification was that she made large contributions to the
Republican Party.
   ``I'm out to put an end to this ... ambassadorial spoils
system,'' Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., told the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee about the nomination of Joy Silverman.
   ``There are no qualifications for this lady,'' Sarbanes said.
``There's nothing there. There's no `there' there.''
   Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-N.Y., defended the nomination, saying
Bush made it because of his friendship with Mrs. Silverman not
because she was a large GOP contributor.
   Sarbanes, exercising his rights under the rules of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, blocked committee action for at least
a week. But some Republicans said they feared the Senate might be
prevented from acting at all because the current session of
Congress is nearing an end.
   Sarbanes said Mrs. Silverman, and her husband, Jeffrey, gave
about $300,000 to the national Republican Party in 1987 and 1988.
That figure, he said, didn't include other large contributions to
GOP candidates in New York state and New York City.
   Jeffrey Silverman's company, Ply Gem Industries Inc. of New York
City, made other large contributions to Republican causes, many of
which have not been identified, Sarbanes said.
   The Silvermans also arranged a $100,000 corporate loan in
December 1988 to President Bush's inaugural committee about the
same time Mrs. Silverman was making clear her interest in an
ambassadorship, Sarbanes said.
   The interest-free loan, which had been solicited with about 200
others for ``seed money'' to plan and arrange inaugural events, was
repaid a month later, Sarbanes said.
   The Silvermans are members of Team 100, people who have
contributed $100,000 or more to the Republican National Committee.
   Sarbanes said the many prominent figures who wrote letters
urging that Mrs. Silverman be named an ambassador cited no other
qualifications than her abilities as a GOP fund-raiser.
   In her submission to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
Mrs. Silverman said she was qualified for the post because she had
``assisted my husband by planning and hosting corporate functions.''
   Sarbanes has opposed several of Bush's nominees on grounds they
had no apparent qualifications except their large political
contributions.
   He said there are 41 women in the senior service of the U.S.
Foreign Service, all highly qualified and experienced. None has
been named by Bush as an ambassador.
</TEXT>
