<DOCNO> AP891109-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1810EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     11-09 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibians Crawl, Ford Rivers to Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ONGWEDIVA, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One woman crawled to the polls. Some
people waded across rivers. Others camped overnight at polling
stations as Namibians displayed a fierce determination to vote in
their first open elections.
   Namibians have peacefully endured hours of searing heat, wind
and dust in milelong lines to vote for an assembly that will write
a constitution paving the way for independence from South Africa.
   ``Perhaps I can, hopefully, in the end of this exercise, say
that this has been the most democratic elections in the world,''
U.N. special representative Martti Ahtisaari said Thursday after
touring polling booths in northern Namibia.
   The United Nations is supervising the independence process in
the territory, which South Africa has ruled for 74 years. No date
for independence has been set, but independence is expected to be
early next year.
   By Thursday, the third day of 5-day elections, more than 60
percent of the 701,483 registered voters had cast ballots,
according to Ahtisaari and territorial officials.
   Ahtisaari flew to the northern Ovambo district, Namibia's most
populous area, and was told that 75 percent of those registered in
the region already had voted.
   ``I think it indicates how dedicated the Namibians are, how
anxious they have been to use their democratic right in this
election,'' he remarked.
   Namibia's South African administrator, Louis Pienaar, predicted
Wednesday the voter turnout would be nearly 100 percent by the time
polls closed Saturday.
   Lines were much shorter Thursday, but the queues snaking along
sandy village and township roads during the previous two days
showed the variety of peoples who populate the territory.
   Diminutive Bushmen, clay-covered Himba women with animal-skin
aprons, tall Herero women in Victorian-style dresses, and city
dwellers in T-shirts declaring ``My vote is my secret'' _ all stood
in line, quietly, patiently and with good humor.
   No reports of serious political violence and few instances of
intimidation emerged. Election code violations have occurred, such
as anonymous smear pamphlets aimed at discrediting the South-West
Africa People's Organization, the election favorite.
   SWAPO President Sam Nujoma said before voting began that the
organization would accept any outcome certified by the United
Nations.
   The key election issue is whether SWAPO will win two-thirds of
the vote necessary to write a constitution without consulting the
other nine parties.
   Polling stations in the northern region have no electricity or
phones. Some were set up by teams flown in by helicopter. Water
trucks and candles were brought in.
   Near Oshakati, a lame woman who had come without friends crawled
toward the polling booth Wednesday. In another Ovambo village a
crippled man pushed himself along with his hands.
   A U.N. official in the northeastern town of Rundu said voters
crossed the Okavango River in small canoes or waded across it.
   People who live in neighboring countries can vote if they or
their parents were born in Namibia or if they resided in the
territory for four years.
   U.N. Regional Director Linda Cohen said the Kavango people, most
of whom haven't voted in a century of colonial rule, began arriving
at the Rundu polling station more than eight hours before it opened.
   ``They were just excited. They wanted to be the first,'' she
said. ``They've been waiting a long time for this to happen.''
</TEXT>
