<SECOND>AM-Superpower Summit,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>New U.S. Ambassador Says Libyans Pose No Special Security Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new U.S. ambassador to Malta said
Thursday she does not believe that visiting Libyans in Malta pose
any special security risk for next month's superpower summit.
   President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev are
scheduled to hold shipboard meetings off Malta on Dec. 2-3.
   Ambassador Sally Novetzke, who presented her credentials
Thursday to President Vincent Tabone, also said she considers it
unlikely any meeting would be arranged between Bush and Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi during the summit.
   The Socialist Party leader and former prime minister, Karmenu
Mifsud Bonnici, on Wednesday called on the government to try to
arrange a Bush-Gadhafi meeting in an effort ``to reduce tensions
between the two countries.''
   The Bush administration has said previously it was not prepared
to hold talks with Libya. It said last month that Libya is still
providing funds, weapons, haven and training facilities to
terrorists.
   Bonnici was the prime minister in April 1986, when Malta gave
Libya advance warning of the U.S. air raids on the Libyan cities of
Benghazi and Tripoli.
   However, Libya apparently did not act on the information.
Then-President Reagan said the bombing raids were intended to
punish Libya for its alleged support of international terrorism.
   The Socialists were voted out in 1986 after 16 years in power
and the conservative government of Prime Minister Eddie Fenech
Adami has moved closer to the United States and Western Europe.
   Mrs. Novetzke said the fact that Libyans are allowed to freely
visit Malta does not pose any special security risk for the summit.
``It is not a worry,'' she said.
</TEXT>
