<HEAD>Demonstrators in Anti-Bases Rally At U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA4</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 protesters burned
effigies of President Corazon Aquino and Uncle Sam on Thursday and
carried banners reading ``Yankee Go Home'' in demanding that the
country's six U.S. bases be closed.
   The protest in front of the U.S. Embassy took place before Mrs.
Aquino met President Bush in Washington for two hours of talks that
included the future of the military bases, whose lease expires in
1991.
   U.S. and Filipino negotiators are expected to begin talks in
Manila next month on extending the bases. Mrs. Aquino refuses to
say whether she wants a new agreement.
   Sen. Wigberto Tanada, a member of the pro-Aquino coalition, told
the rally that even if Mrs. Aquino supported a new agreement, the
Senate would disapprove it.
   The constitution requires approval of any bases agreement by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate. Tanada told the crowd 10
senators were committed to dismantling the bases in 1991 and he
expected up to five more to support closure.
   ``When Cory and Bush hold hands, that will be the climax of
Cory's betrayal of the Filipino people,'' said one leaflet by the
New Patriotic Alliance, the May First Movement and the League of
Filipino Students.
