<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-09 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL CITY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's every kid's worst nightmare: a
spinach cook-off.
   The culinary countdown is part of the Crystal City Spinach
Festival, an annual event that draws thousands to this South Texas
town of about 8,500. They're welcomed by _ who else? _ Popeye.
   An 8-foot concrete statue of the spinach-chomping cartoon sailor
sits in front of City Hall, symbolizing Crystal City's love affair
with the dark green leafy stuff.
   ``We're expecting 50,000,'' said Bella Delgado, a spokeswoman
for the Crystal City Spinach Festival Association. ``They come from
all over the world. I don't know why, they just come.''
   This year's gala starts Friday and lasts through Sunday.
   Spinach fanatics from as far away as London have called to
inquire about the festival. Official guests include former San
Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros, U.S. Rep. Albert Bustamante of San
Antonio and state Rep. Ernestine Glossbrenner of Alice.
   The Spinach Festival also features sports contests, live music,
a carnival, parade, chili cook-off, Miss Spinach pageant and the
ever popular spinach cook-off.
   To cap the celebration, Festival-goers will see a real-life
Popeye leap from a plane with a group of skydivers during the
festival.
   Chefs put forward their best recipes to make such taste treats
as spinach casserole, spinach dip, spinach salad and spinach quiche.
   What about the kids in this spinach-loving town? Well, they come
around, according to Ms. Delgado, who didn't like spinach herself
until age 16.
   ``I didn't like spinach at first, but now I do,'' she said. ``I
had to try it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Trooper Robby Anger's Lamaze class
in natural childbirth techniques emphasizes relaxation. But try
telling that to a cow.
   Anger and fellow Trooper Mark O'Donnell got a call from a
motorist Thursday telling them a Holstein cow was giving birth on
the shoulder of Route 36 in Dansville, about 45 miles south of
Rochester.
   ``The mother was very protective when we got there _ we didn't
know it was two of them,'' O'Donnell said. ``Then we could see two
legs and the head coming out.''
   Troopers are routinely trained to help humans give birth, but
neither Anger nor O'Donnell had ever helped anything give birth,
they said.
   ``Robby's wife is pregnant _ he's going to Lamaze classes, so he
stayed with the mother to help and I ran up to the nearest farm to
wake somebody up,'' O'Donnell said. ``We figured it was good
practice for him.''
   The mother, it turned out, didn't need much coaching and
wouldn't let the troopers near her. After she cleaned up her newly
born calf, O'Donnell set up a roadblock so oncoming cars wouldn't
hit it.
   Both mother and newborn are reportedly doing fine, O'Donnell
said.
</TEXT>
