<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Housing     11-09 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Housing,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill Providing Funds for Veterans, Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday signed a bill
providing $67 billion for veterans, housing, environment, space and
other programs for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
   Bush said in a statement that the measure included a $500
million increase, to $11.4 billion, in Veterans Administration
medical care.
   ``Those men and women who have served in the military can expect
to receive the benefits they deserve,'' Bush said, noting that the
nation is about to celebrate Veterans Day.
   The bill provides $12.4 billion for NASA, $1.7 billion more than
last year's level. Of the total, $1.8 billion would go to
development of the planned space station, $250 million less than
the Bush administration sought.
   It makes available $5.6 billion for the Environmental Protection
Agency, a $400 million boost over 1989. The Superfund hazardous
waste cleanup program would get $1.5 billion and anti-pollution
efforts $817 million.
   Veterans' medical care would receive $11.4 billion, $551 million
more than last year. Housing programs would be bolstered by $2.3
billion over 1989 levels, to $15.1 billion.
   The legislation also increases, to $124,874, the size of home
mortgages available from the Federal Housing Administration in many
communities with high housing prices.
</TEXT>
