<HEAD>More Attacks Reported Against Parliament Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police reported more bombing attempts
Thursday against Parliament members who elected Rene Mouawad as
Lebanon's new president, and Mouawad pursued talks on forming a
Cabinet of national reconciliation.
   Sources among Western diplomats said Thursday the diplomats will
shun Gen. Michel Aoun, head of the Christian Cabinet for the past
13 months, who has refused to recognize the election of the
president election last weekend.
   ``There has been a decision to boycott Aoun,'' said one
diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   French Ambassador Rene Ala was the last diplomat to visit Aoun
on Sunday. Aoun dismissed as unconstitutional Parliament's election
in north Lebanon that day and refused to leave the presidential
palace in suburban Baabda to allow Mouawad, a Maronite Christian,
to settle in there.
   Police reported Thursday that a 66-pound bomb was defused
minutes before it was set to explode late Wednesday outside the
apartment of Christian deputy Michel Sassine in east Beirut's
Ashrafiyeh neighborhood.
   A police spokesman said a small bomb did explode Tuesday under
the car of Christian deputy Nasri Maalouf in east Beirut's Hazmiyeh
district and another went off overnight under the car of Druse
deputy Toufik Assaf in west Beirut.
   The attacks caused damage but no casualties, said the spokesman,
who cannot be identified under standing regulations.
   At least six bombs have targeted deputies in Beirut since Nov.
3. Five of them exploded. No one claimed responsibility and each
side blamed the other.
   Mouawad's election was under terms of a peace plan that would
cede more political power to the Moslem majority and end Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war. Aoun complained that the plan lacked a
timetable for total withdrawal of the 40,000 Syrian troops here. He
fought the Syrian forces for six months until an Arab
League-sponsored cease-fire in September.
   The Syrians are in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   Mouawad, 64, set up headquarters at the prime minister's office
in Syrian-policed west Beirut, becoming the first Christian
president to operate from the city's Moslem sector in 31 years.
   Mouawad met with Parliament speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite
Moslem, and then with Salim Hoss who headed the predominantly
Moslem Cabinet before the presidential election.
   Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, supports Mouawad and submitted his
Cabinet's resignation Monday to facilitate formation of a new
government.
   Husseni later told reporters that ``consultations are
continuing. The objective is the formation of a national
reconciliation government which, most probably, will be an expanded
one.''
   Mouawad also met with Moslem and Christian deputies and with
former ministers.
   Syrian soldiers ringed the area to protect the new president,
causing a traffic jam.
   Mouawad's meetings came a day after a car bomb explosion near
his intended residence killed four people and wounded 19.
</TEXT>
