<FIRST>u w AM-HUDReforms     11-09 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Reforms,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Approves Kemp's HUD Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary Jack Kemp's proposals for reforming
the scandal-ridden Department of Housing and Urban Development won
passage in a House subcommittee Thursday with bipartisan support.
   The housing subcommittee of the House Banking Committee approved
a bill including most of the elements of Kemp's reform package, and
both Democrats and Republicans said the full committee may send the
measure to the House floor next week.
   ``The HUD reform package approved today will change
significantly the way the department operates,'' said Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y. ``The measure will eliminate much of the
possibility of fraud and abuse at the department.''
   Schumer, who sat with another subcommittee that investigated the
billion-dollar scandals involving mismanagement, influence-peddling
and fraud at HUD, said the reform package would bring ``openness
and disclosure'' to the department's grant-selection process.
   Among the Kemp proposals included in the approved package were a
requirement that consultants on HUD projects be registered, subject
to criminal penalties; establishment of a department chief
financial officer and comptroller for the Federal Housing
Administration; limits on FHA mortgages for second residences and a
requirement that HUD waivers of regulations be disclosed.
   The panel added to Kemp's initiatives a requirement that HUD
provide documentation in support of all funding decisions, and a
requirement that HUD consider the value of low-income tax credits
received by developers on projects for which they may also benefit
from other HUD subsidies.
</TEXT>
