<FIRST>r w AM-Navy-Computers     11-09 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Computers,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Concedes Rules Broken</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy conceded Thursday that its employees
violated regulations in accepting free training from IBM Corp.
   A House subcommittee, which has been investigating mismanagement
of the Navy's automated data processing service, said at least 128
Navy officials were improperly trained by IBM in San Jose, Calif.,
from 1985 to 1987.
   The disclosure came just one day after the General Accounting
Office, the investigative arm of Congress, and the Defense
Department testified that the Navy showed partiality toward IBM in
awarding millions of dollars of computer contracts.
   ``It's as if all the laws and regulations are being evaded, and
that we have very serious problems in terms of having open and fair
competition in government procurement,'' Rep. John Conyers, Jr.,
D-Mich., chairman of the House Government Affairs subcommittee on
legislation and national security, said Thursday.
   ``It is my opinion that acceptance of the IBM vendor training
was not in accordance with the controlling regulations,'' Roger T.
McNamara, assistant general counsel on ethics at the Navy, told the
House subcommittee.
   ``Consequently, government travel funds should not have been
authorized in the first instance for such a purpose. However, they
were,'' he said.
   Specifically, he said IBM's selection of employees to attend the
training program violated Defense Department and Navy rules on
accepting free vendor training.
   The training represented an impermissible gratuity, McNamara
said.
   Alvin F. Easter, program manager for IBM's Data Processing
Management Institute, defended its program, saying none of the
company's ``executive education offerings ... were devised for the
Navy _ or any other particular customer or set of customers.''
   Easter said federal employees, including the Navy, made up ``but
a small fraction of the attendees at these San Jose Executive
Education classes during the entire period being considered by the
committee.''
   The House subcommittee, GAO and Defense Department inquiries
were prompted by a November 1988 letter from six IBM competitors in
which they said they had been frozen out of much of the Navy's
multibillion-dollar computer market.
   The companies complained to then-Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci that Navy officials had tailored the bid specifications so
that only IBM could win although many of the companies offer
``clones'' or duplicates of IBM systems at lower prices.
   The five-page letter was signed by executives of the Amdahl
Corp.; Memorex Telex Corp.; PacifiCorp Capital Inc.; VION Corp.;
NCR Compten; and Storage Technology Corp.
</TEXT>
