<FIRST>r a AM-VaVoteCount     11-09 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Vote Count,0279</SECOND>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat L. Douglas Wilder's margin over
Republican Marshall Coleman in the governor's race widened slightly
Thursday as more counties certified results and errors in
unofficial tallies were corrected.
   Changes in vote totals from six jurisdictions boosted Wilder's
total by just under 300 votes, while cutting slightly less than 800
from Coleman's total. Late Thursday, the unofficial statewide total
stood at 896,553 for Wilder to 889,971 for Coleman _ a margin of
6,582 votes for the Democrat.
   Many Virginia jurisdictions continued retabulating the vote
Thursday in preparation for certifying the returns to the state
government.
   Availability of official tabulations made the biggest difference
in Newport News, where Wilder picked up 274 votes and Coleman lost
119. That official total boosted Wilder's statewide margin by 393
votes.
   Certified vote totals in Henry County and in Chesapeake and
Norfolk changed each candidates' tallies by a small number of votes.
   The biggest change in unofficial tallies was in Fairfax County.
   The registar's office on Thursday said the county's unofficial
totals were Wilder 127,184 and Coleman 99,126. These figures were
the same as AP reported late Tuesday after the election.
   On Wednesday, the AP had obtained totals from the registrar's
office giving Wilder 127,197 and Coleman 99,835 _ which would have
raised Coleman's statewide total. The registrar on Thursday said
the Tuesday night figures were the correct, unofficial totals.
   Official Fairfax totals will not be available until Friday.
   Correcting a data entry error by the AP in Prince William
County's totals boosted Wilder's tally by 34 votes.
   Official certification of the statewide vote is scheduled Nov.
27.
