<FIRST>r a AM-ArrowDeath     11-09 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arrow Death,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son Charged With Killing Mother With Arrow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIE AICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state legislator's 19-year-old son was
charged Thursday with shooting a hunting arrow into his mother's
heart, killing her, during a predawn dispute at the family
farmhouse.
   A criminal complaint filed in Dodge County Circuit Court charged
Chad E. Goetsch with first-degree intentional homicide in the death
early Wednesday of his mother, Carolyn Goetsch, 51.
   Goetsch told authorities he shot his mother accidentally while
playing with a hunting bow at the farmhouse, according to the
complaint.
   But Goetsch's father, state Rep. Robert R. Goetsch, said in the
complaint that his son shot his wife, then pointed an arrow at him.
   ``My son was going to kill me,'' the lawmaker said in the
complaint. He said he grabbed the arrowhead and broke it off,
cutting his hand.
   Robert Goetsch said he and his son fought, passing through a
hall and several rooms. At one point, the legislator's 14-year-old
daughter, Shana, grabbed a knife to protect herself, authorities
said.
   Shana Goetsch called authorities, who arrested Chad Goetsch at
the home outside Juneau, a town of about 2,000 people about 50
miles southwest of Milwaukee.
   Mrs. Goetsch was pronounced dead at the scene. Robert Goetsch
was treated at a hospital for cuts on his hands and face, and
released. No charges were filed in connection with his injuries.
   If convicted of homicide, Chad Goetsch faces a mandatory
sentence of life in prison.
   Circuit Judge Daniel W. Klossner set bail at $200,000 cash, and
ordered the young man to undergo psychiatric evaluation at Mendota
Mental Health Institute in Madison. A public defender was appointed
to represent him.
   Robert Goetsch did not attend Thursday's hearing.
   Chad Goetsch is a freshman at Marquette University in Milwaukee
and does not live at home. He is Mrs. Goetsch's biological son, and
was adopted by Robert Goetsch when the couple married 15 years ago,
relatives have said.
   Shana told authorities that she had heard her brother threaten
her parents' lives in the past, the complaint said.
   During a domestic dispute at the Goetsch home in November 1987,
authorities said they found a note in Chad Goetsch's room that
said, ``Nothing would please me more than your death ...,'' the
complaint said. The letter was signed with Chad's initials.
   In a fight in September 1988, Chad Goetsch punched his mother in
the eye and choked his father, the complaint said.
</TEXT>
