<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CoalStrike     11-09 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston, UMW In First Joint Session with Supermediator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Pittston Co. and United
Mine Workers met jointly for the first time Thursday with the
government ``supermediator'' named to resolve the bitter and often
violent 7-month-old strike.
   No significant progress was reported in a session said to be
largely dedicated to setting the groundrules for intensive
negotiations set to begin Monday.
   ``I'm absolutely convinced that both sides want a contract,''
mediator W.J. Usery said after the session. ``We need the jobs. We
need people back to work and we need paychecks.''
   Usery, a former labor secretary and veteran mediator, spent 75
minutes in a joint meeting with the two sides and then had several,
shorter talks with company and union representatives in separate
rooms. Both sides agreed to negotiate throughout next week and also
to refuse to discuss the substance of those talks with the press,
Usery said.
   The walkout began in April and has kept 1,700 miners in
Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky of the job. Their picketing
has been marred by sporadic violence and the union has been heavily
fined for defying court orders restricting its demonstrations.
   The biggest issue in the dispute is over Pittston's payments of
health and retirement benefits, a fight whose outcome could have
far-reaching effects in the coal industry.
   The session was the first at which UMW President Richard Trumka
and Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas sat face-to-face with their
respective negotiating teams as well as the first joint meeting
with Usery, who was named as mediator two weeks ago by Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
   Trumka and Douglas both had praise for Usery after the meeting
but no substantive progress to report.
   ``We weren't dealing with substance,'' Trumka said. ``We're just
going over ground rules.''
   Douglas said he was willing to do ``whatever I can do to help
with the process.''
   Douglas participated in the entire joint session but left a
short time later, leaving behind the rest of the Pittston team.
``I've got to get back,'' he said when leaving, presumably
referring to Pittston's headquarters in Greenwich, Conn.
   Usery said he did not want Trumka and Douglas at the talks next
week unless a settlement appeared within reach.
   As for Usery, Douglas said he was ``very impressed'' with the
mediator and Trumka added: ``If anyone can get this job done I
think Bill Usery can.''
</TEXT>
