<DOCNO> AP891109-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Guyana-Venezuela     11-09 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guyana-Venezuela,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guyana, Venezuela Agree to Appoint Mediator Over Land Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela and Guyana have moved closer
to solving a 157-year-old territorial dispute following a meeting
between presidents of the neighboring South American nations, state
radio said Thursday.
   Guyana's Desmond Hoyte and Venezuela's Carlos Andres Perez
agreed Wednesday in Caracas to appoint a mediator to settle the
dispute that involves 60 percent of Guyana's land, including all of
its mineral-rich western region.
   Since 1832, 11 years after gaining independence from Spain,
Venezuela has laid claims to the territory.
   Venezuela said the British, who first made claims on the land
that became Guyana in the late 16th century, had taken territory
that had belonged to the Spanish Empire for decades. The Dutch, who
had a competing claim in the region, ceded the territory to Britain
in 1814.
   Tense relations attributed to the land claim did not subside
with Guyana's independence from Britain in 1966, and only began to
improve when Hoyte came to power in 1985.
   Hoyte and Perez chose Alister McIntyre, vice chancellor of the
University of the West Indies, as mediator.
   Before returning home later this week, Hoyte was expected to ask
Venezuela to resume shipments of oil on credit to Guyana. Venezuela
suspended shipments earlier this year, citing Guyana's unpaid $25
million bill.
</TEXT>
