<SECOND>AM-Margarine Heiress,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Margarine Heiress, Colombian Found Guilty Of Distributing Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury on Thursday convicted a
margarine heiress and a Colombian co-defendant of helping her
unemployed boyfriend run a cocaine ring out of her mansion.
   Sandra Filbert Amos, the 35-year-old granddaughter of the
founder of Mrs. Filbert's Margarine, and Guillermo Moran, a
32-year-old Colombian living in New York City, face a maximum
sentence of life in prison.
   U.S. Attorney Breckenridge Willcox said prosecutors would
probably recommend at least 10 years in prison without parole for
each of the defendants. U.S. District Judge Joseph Howard set
sentencing for Feb. 14.
   Amos and Moran were each found guilty of two counts of
distribution of cocaine and one count of conspiracy to distribute
more than five kilograms of cocaine.
   Prosecutors said Amos helped Jeremia Dennis Case, her unemployed
boyfriend, set up the drug ring at her Easton mansion on Maryland's
Eastern Shore because she wanted to overcome his feeling that the
disparity in their incomes hurt their relationship.
   Case has pleaded guilty to drug charges, and is awaiting
sentencing.
   Defense attorney Russell White had argued that Amos was guilty
only of possession. He said Case distributed cocaine, while Amos
was an addict, spending as much as $2,000 a week to support her
habit.
   Amos' $750,000 five-acre estate, including the mansion, has been
seized by the government because of the drug case.
   Willcox said, ``There's sort of a bigger message here. Even
relatively uninvolved participants in a major conspiracy, people
who don't actually lug the cocaine around, even if they are knowing
participants, they are going to be convicted and serve as much time
as the major participants.''
</TEXT>
