<FIRST>u i AM-CheckpointCharlie     11-09 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Checkpoint Charlie,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Disappointed at Checkpoint Charlie, Finally Free to Pass</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were wild scenes at Checkpoint Charlie, the
most famous crossing in the infamous Berlin Wall, when hundreds of
East Germans arrived Thursday night and tried to get through.
   Minutes after West German television said it had heard East
Germans were allowed to cross at Checkpoint Charlie, about 300 East
Berliners arrived carrying only their identity papers.
   Watched by cheering West Berliners, waving from 50 yards away,
the East Germans tried to persuade their border police to let them
through.
   ``I just want to go over and have a good time,'' one man said.
``We've got to get back to work tomorrow.''
   ``Let us have a beer over there,'' a woman said. ``We'll come
back.''
   ``We're coming right away!'' the East Germans shouted to West
Berliners on the other side.
   Suddenly, the border guards relented and hundreds of people ran
through toward the customs hall, waved on by East German officials.
   At the last barrier, the crowd encountered locked doors. Guards
urged everyone to be patient and distributed cards to be filled out.
   ``Just so we know who went through,'' one guard explained.
   ``This is a historic day!'' a man yelled. ``We're going to be
able to tell our children about this!''
   Then came disappointment. Border guards said no one could go
through without a visa stamp from East Berlin police, which they
could get only when police stations re-opened Friday morning.
   ``This is kindergarten,'' one youth grumbled.
   Eventually, the crowd was persuaded to turn back, but
34-year-old Angelika Wachs slipped through the door when it was
opened to let an Associated Press correspondent through.
   ``Ja-a-a-a,'' she whispered gleefully, then came tense seconds
as the East German guard checked her newly issued passport, which
contained a visa allowing her to visit West Germany beginning next
week.
   When she got past the controls and saw the screaming, cheering
West Berliners gathered to welcome any arrivals from the East, she
cried: ``This is unbelievable! I can't believe it!''
   She raced off to find a ride to a friend's house in the West
Berlin district of Charlottenburg.
   Later, hundreds more East Germans arrived at Checkpoint Charlie
and, finally, they too were let through. The flood of new arrivals
continued into the night, a historic night.
</TEXT>
