<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RadioactiveLeak     11-09 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radioactive Leak,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plant Officials Say Radiation Dosage Small</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMISBURG, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operators of a government-owned nuclear
production plant said Thursday that area residents were exposed to
virtually no tritium as a result of an accidental release of the
radioactive gas.
   Richard Neff, manager of environment, safety and health at the
Mound Nuclear Production Plant, said off-site air samples showed a
slight increase over normal levels of tritium, which is radioactive
hydrogen.
   But the maximum dose to each of the 2,400 residents under the
radioactive cloud from Wednesday's release was 0.00012 millirems,
he said. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's standard of
safe dosage is 25 millirems a year.
   ``You're getting down to a range where it is essentially
nothing,'' said Neff, adding that such levels are difficult to
measure. ``The chance of a person getting cancer from this is
roughly equivalent to smoking 14 cigarettes.''
   Neff said that of the 52 workers evacuated from the building,
six had shown low levels of radiation in their systems. But he said
further testing revealed that those levels may have been the result
of the workers' regular handling of tritium.
   ``We don't have any concentrations greater than what we would
expect from normal operations,'' he said. ``We don't see any
workers who we feel have any significant exposure from this event.''
   Jim Morley, Dayton-area manager for the U.S. Department of
Energy, said DOE will investigate the incident.
   The radioactive gas was released into the air and fell over a
three-mile area northwest of the plant, extending over a section of
downtown Miamisburg and the Great Miami River.
   The plant enriches tritium gas, which is used in combination
with plutonium to act as a trigger for nuclear weapons. A total of
3.7 grams of tritium was released through an exhaust vent, about 10
times what the plant normally releases in a year.
   The release occurred when a quartz window in a bell jar
containing tritium shattered during a laser-drilling operation.
   About 2,200 workers are employed at the Mound Plant, which is
operated for the Energy Department by EG&amp;G Mound Applied
Technologies.
</TEXT>
