<FIRST>r a AM-FarmSearch     11-09 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Search,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Case Squad That Found Four Bodies Disbands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sheriff Thursday disbanded a squad
of about 20 officers from nine counties brought together for a
murder investigation that turned up four bodies buried in barns.
   Livingston County Sheriff Leland O'Dell said the investigation
would continue with help from the Missouri State Highway Patrol,
but that other counties could not afford to continue providing
help. The North Central Missouri Major Case Squad, activated Oct.
13, worked 3,237 hours and checked 367 leads, he said.
   Officers began digging on the northwest Missouri farm of Ray
Copeland after he and his wife, Faye, were arrested Oct. 9 in an
alleged cattle swindle. They remained jailed on $25,000 bond each,
charged with conspiracy to steal.
   The Copelands have not been named as suspects in the deaths of
four transients whose bodies were found in shallow graves on two
other farms on Oct. 16 and 25.
   However, authorities say Copeland had done odd jobs on those
farms and the four victims had connections to a Springfield mission
where Copeland sometimes appeared to hire help. Investigators
compiled a list of 20 people who had worked for Copeland since
1986, and eight are unaccounted for.
   The digging began after a drifter, Jack McCormick, called an
anti-crime hotline in Nebraska to say he had found a human skull
and legbone on Copeland's farm, Patrol Sgt. Larry Stobbs said.
</TEXT>
