<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-IndianActivist     11-09 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Activist,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Indian Activist Ordered Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Indian activist Robert
Satiacum was ordered deported to the United States on Thursday,
hours after he was convicted of fondling a 10-year-old girl in an
unrelated case.
   The U.S. government has been trying to extradite the former
chairman of the Puyallup Indian Tribe in Washington state for
several years on embezzlement and racketeering convictions.
   ``I am bound in law to issue you with a deportation order,''
said immigration adjudicator Garry Braunwarth. ``I have no
alternative. The law permits no discretion.''
   Satiacum, 60, who contended he was persecuted in the United
States, lost his bid for refugee status in Canada Nov. 2, allowing
the deportation proceedings to reopen.
   The deportation hearing did not deal with Satiacum's conviction
for sexual touching. Satiacum is to be sentenced on that charge
Nov. 17. He faces a maximum sentence of 10 years.
   Lawyers for the Canadian government and Satiacum argued Thursday
over whether he should be deported before he served his sentence on
the sex charge.
   Satiacum's lawyer, Mark Hilford, said the deportation hearing
should be adjourned pending a decision from the Supreme Court of
Canada on Satiacum's claim for refugee status.
   ``It's improper for Immigration Canada to be seen as attempting
an end-run around the Supreme Court of Canada,'' he said.
   Satiacum, who fled to Canada in 1982, faces a lengthy jail
sentence in the United States. His problems began with his battle
over selling tax-free cigarettes on Indian land and escalated from
there.
   He was originally granted political asylum in Canada in 1987 but
the decision was overturned this year.
   Satiacum, who has diabetes and a bad heart, spent three years in
jail while he fought efforts to extradite him.
   Thursday morning, County court Judge Cathy Ryan convicted him of
touching a person under 14 for sexual purposes. ``This verdict is
worse than the verdict of murder,'' a weary-looking Satiacum said.
``It takes away my whole future.''
   Satiacum continued to maintain his innocence, saying he did not
touch the girl in April 1988 while he was staying at a house in
suburban Richmond owned by her grandmother. He said he may appeal
the verdict.
   The girl testified she awoke to find Satiacum with his hand
beneath her underwear. Satiacum testified he had tripped over the
girl, who was asleep on the floor, and fell partly on her but did
not molest her.
   ``I reject Mr. Satiacum's evidence as untruthful,'' the judge
said.
</TEXT>
