<FIRST>u i AM-EGermany-FirstTime     11-09 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-First Time,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berliners Take First Look at West Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torsten Ryl simply flashed his identity card early
Friday, and for the first time in his life the East German waiter
entered West Berlin.
   ``At the stroke of midnight, they (East German border officials)
told us `The procedure has been shortened, and all you need is a
stamp,''' he said.
   With that, Ryl walked into the West at the Checkpoint Charlie
crossing through the Berlin Wall, where guards had forcibly kept
East Germans out for 28 years.
   ``I've never been here before,'' said Ryl, who like hundreds of
others early Friday took advantage of their Communist government's
decision to open the country's borders.
   ``It's not my intention to stay here, but we have to have the
possibility to come over here and go back again. I have my
apartment and my car over there,'' Ryl said.
   A middle-aged West German reached over and gave him 20 marks
($11) and said with a grin: ``Why don't you go get yourself a beer
first?''
   Several thousand people greeted Ryl and the other East
Berliners; West Berliners held impromptu dances atop the wall and
hoisted people up from the other side of the divided city to join
them.
   Thomas Moll, 21, said he was allowed to cross into West Berlin
in less than five minutes.
   ``I just can't believe it,'' he said. ``A lot of people thought
it was just another trick.''
   Moll said he also intended to return home after having a look
around West Berlin.
   It seemed as if each East Berliner who crossed the demarcation
line was greeted with cheers _ many by hugs and kisses _ by the
crowd at Checkpoint Charlie.
   Traffic jams built up on western side at the checkpoint, and
people streamed out of the Kochstrasse subway stop on the West
Berlin side to join the party.
   There were similar scenes as other border checkpoints.
   ``It's just unbelievable,'' sobbed a middle-aged woman, who said
she just wanted to take a walk in West Berlin.
   Thousands celebrated on the Kurfuerstendamm, a boulevard in West
Berlin's upscale shopping district.
   East German Trabant cars were welcomed by cheers and honking
horns as they slowly wended their way down the boulevard, now the
scene of the wildest celebrations since the Berlin Wall was born in
the Cold War.
</TEXT>
