<FIRST>u w AM-Anti-WarProsecutor     11-09 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-War Prosecutor,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guy Goodwin, Opponent of Radicals, Lost Job After Sex Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a Justice Department unit that
prosecuted anti-war protestors during the Nixon administration was
forced to retire following a conviction for sexual batttery, it was
disclosed Thursday.
   Guy L. Goodwin, who traveled the country in the early 1970s
obtaining controversial indictments against anti-war protestors and
political radicals, retired last year following his conviction in
Wichita, Kan.
   Goodwin's case was noted in a report released Thursday by the
Justice Department's Office of Professional Responsibility. The
report did not identify Goodwin by name, but the case had received
publicity in Wichita.
   Department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed that the report referred to Goodwin.
   Goodwin was arrested in an adult bookstore on Feb. 9, 1988 after
making a sexual advance to a male undercover police officer,
according to accounts in the Wichita Eagle and a summary of the
incident in the Justice Department report.
   Goodwin pleaded no contest to a sexual battery charge and was
fined $100 and placed on probation. Sexual battery is touching in a
sexual context.
   Goodwin joined the Justice Department in the late 1960s and
gained noteriety for heading a Justice Department unit started by
the Nixon administration to investigate ``revolutionary
terrorists.''
   Grand jury investigations that Goodwin conducted around the
country returned scores of indictments against anti-war activists
but resulted in only a few convictions.
   Most of the charges were either dismissed or defendants were
acquitted. Defense attorneys frequently alleged prosecutorial
misconduct, including the use of agents provacateurs.
   One of the more noted cases was the unsuccessful prosecution of
Dr. Benjamin Spock, the pediatrician, child-care writer and
anti-war activists, in Boston.
   In another case, eight members of the Vietnam Veterans Against
the War were accused of plotting to disrupt the 1972 Republican
National Convention in Miami.
   All eight defendants were acquitted and later filed a suit
charging that Goodwin violated their constitutional rights by lying
to a judge during the grand jury investigation that preceded their
indictment.
</TEXT>
