<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial     11-09 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drunken Driving Raised In Jury Selection in Bus Crash Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospective jurors were questioned about
drunken driving Thursday in the murder trial of a man accused of
killing 27 people, mostly children, when he slammed into a church
bus with his pickup truck.
   Carroll County Circuit Judge Charles Satterwhite dismissed two
people during jury selection in the trial of Larry Mahoney, 36,
after they said they had lost relatives to accidents involving
drunken drivers.
   Three other prospective jurors said they had relatives who had
been in legal trouble for driving under the influence. They were
not immediately released from the jury pool.
   ``Obviously, that's going to be a very great topic for
individual questioning,'' said defense attorney William Summers.
Before the trial, Summers said he would look for jurors who had an
understanding of the widespread incidence of drunken driving.
   The 1988 accident was considered the deadliest in U.S. history
to be blamed on drunken driving.
   Prospective jurors were also asked about previous jury service
in the second day of jury selection in this county seat about 40
miles northeast of Louisville. Other questions included whether
they were related to anyone involved in the trial and issues
expected to be raised during the trial.
   Some jurors were dismissed for such routine reasons as a family
sickness or full-time student status.
   Attorneys plan to interview prospective jurors privately next
week.
   Mahoney is accused of driving the wrong way on Interstate 71 on
May 14, 1988 when his pickup truck slammed into a bus from the
Radcliff Assembly of God church. Twenty-seven people, all but three
of them children, died in the fiery crash.
   Mahoney was found to have a blood-alcohol content of .24, nearly
2{ times the limit of .10 for being considered legally intoxicated.
   Mahoney is charged with 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of wanton
endangerment, 12 counts of assault and one of driving under the
influence.
   If convicted of all charges, he faces a maximum sentence of 27
life prison terms plus 450 years.
   Jury selection was expected to last at least through next week.
</TEXT>
