<FIRST>u w AM-Justice-Official 1stLd-Writethru   11-09 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Official, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0809,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resigned After Investigation; Reinstated; Didn't Go Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf to CLARIFY that Pilon accepted reinstatement at
the Justice Department but then resigned; picks up 9th graf, bgng: ``Something
is ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department official resigned in 1988
following an investigation of suspicions that he disclosed
classified information to a foreign government, said a report
released Thursday.
   The annual report of the department's Office of Professional
Responsibility said a counterintelligence investigation did not
produce sufficient evidence to prosecute the official but
determined he should be dismissed.
   The report did not identify the official, but Roger Pilon,
former head of the Justice Department's Office of Asylum Policy and
Review, confirmed he was the subject of parallel investigations by
the FBI and the Office of Professional Responsiblity in 1988.
   Justice Department and FBI officials refused to comment on the
case. But a source who spoke on condition of anonymity confirmed
that Pilon had been the subject of an FBI counterintelligence
investigation.
   Pilon insists that he is innocent of the allegation that he or
his wife, Juliana, passed a secret State Department document about
communist influence in South Africa to the South African government.
   And Pilon produced a 1988 letter from a senior Justice
Department official stating that he was being reinstated after the
investigations.
   ``No implication adverse to you should be taken from the
investigations,'' said the letter by Dee V. Benson, then the
principal associate deputy attorney general.
   Pilon said he accepted reinstatement at the department, which
restored his security clearance, but he then left to join the Cato
Institute, a libertarian think tank where he is now a senior fellow.
   ``Something is going on and it stinks if people like us can be
dragged through the mud,'' said Pilon. ``It's been a nightmare, a
Kafkaesque nightmare.''
   Pilon said FBI agents showed him the State Department documents
while his wife was undergoing a FBI background check for
appointment as an assistant secretary of the interior.
   The agents ``plopped this document on my desk'' and said ```That
document is now in the hands of South Africa. You gave it to your
wife, your wife gave it to the South Africans.'''
   Pilon said he and his wife, then an analyst at the Heritage
Foundation, both passed government polygraph tests, commonly called
lie detector tests. But the investigation dragged on and his wife
was never nominated for the job at the Interior Department.
   The Jan. 8, 1987, document in question was a secret assessment
of the influence of communism in South Africa produced by the State
Department. Pilon had worked at State as policy director of the
Bureau of Human Rights before joining the Justice Department in
March, 1987.
   Pilon said he suspects the FBI had monitored a conversation
between his wife, who studied United Nations affairs, and an
official of the South African mission in New York.
   The phone calls with Chris Camp, a public affairs attache at the
South African mission, took place in January or February of 1987,
Pilon said.
   ``She had been trying to get documents from him about communist
activity at the United Nations. He wanted material she had been
working on.''
   ``Undoubtedly there was a conversation (about) an exchange of
documents,'' Pilon said, who insisted his wife never passed along
he document FBI agents had shown him.
   Pilon said the FBI is apparently still investigating what
happened to the document. Two of the same FBI agents had recently
approached a friend, Pilon said, and asked about the document.
   ``I can only speculate as to what's going on here. I really
don't know,'' Pilon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
