<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Refugees     11-09 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Refugees,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Grants Asylum to Two After Signing Refugee Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has granted asylum to two
Soviet bloc citizens, the first refugees to benefit from its
decision to join the U.N. Convention on the rights of refugees, a
newspaper said Thursday.
   The trade union daily Nepszava identified them as a Soviet from
the Ukraine and a Bulgarian. Their names were not available.
   It quoted Laszlo Albrecht, deputy head of the Refugee Affairs
Department, as saying 44 applications for political asylum were
filed, with one case rejected and 41 still under review.
   Albrecht said the Soviet citizen was jailed and then fired from
his job after taking part in demonstrations, and later fled to
Hungary, according to the paper. It quoted him as saying the
Bulgarian suffered discrimination after defending the rights of the
Turkish minority in his country.
   On March 14, Hungary became the first Soviet bloc country to
join the U.N. Convention on refugees' rights. It came into force
June 12. On Oct. 15, a government decree bringing the country's
legislation in line with the convention went into effect. The two
people are the first to have formally been granted asylum in
Hungary under these terms.
   Hungary accepted the convention for European refugees only. It
commits authorities not to return anyone to a country where his
``life or freedom would be threatened on account of his race,
religion, nationality ... or political opinion.''
</TEXT>
