<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Governors     11-09 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors: Education Goals on Fast Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors meeting with Bush administration
officials said Thursday that work on national education goals is on
a ``very, very fast track'' and they are now ready to work with
Congress.
   The meeting between leaders of the National Governors
Association and White House officials was a follow-up to the
education summit between President Bush and the nation's governors
in September.
   Congress and educators had been excluded from the two-day
discussions in Charlottesville, Va. that concluded nationwide goals
are needed to improve learning.
   ``The involvement of the Congress is essential in my opinion,
and in the opinion of the White House and others, as we seek to
form a true coalition between the Congress, the states and the
executive branch of the White House in trying to build a consensus
to improve education in the country,'' said South Carolina Gov.
Carroll Campbell after the White House meeting.
   Not only will Congress be courted, but the governors decided to
seek the advice of experts and recommendations from educators and
business executives communities at a Dec. 7 meeting.
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad, NGA chairman, said Congress will be
asked to begin immediately to work on legislation that would bring
more flexibility to what is now considered rigid regulations
attached to many federal programs.
   Loosening restrictions on federal funds was one target chosen at
the Charlottesville meeting.
   Other summit goals were to improve early childhood programs,
reorganize school systems to make educators more accountable, keep
drugs out of schools, bolster on-the-job education, improve
literacy and reduce dropouts.
   Branstad said Thursday's meeting with Chief of Staff John
Sununu; Roger Porter, the president's domestic policy adviser;
Richard Darman, director of the Office of Management and Budget;
and Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos was ``very constructive'' and
``we've agreed that we're going to continue to work to develop the
national goals for education.''
   After the Dec. 7 Task Force on Education meeting, the governors
will hold state hearings and discussions in their respective states
in December and January, said NGA Vice Chairman Booth Gardner of
Washington state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
