<FIRST>u w NYAPW:ForManila     11-09 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>NY APW: For Manila</SECOND>
<HEAD>AM-Bush-Aquino Toasts,660</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the toasts President
Bush and Philippines President Corazon Aquino exchanged at Thursday
night's state dinner:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PRESIDENT BUSH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Part of the enduring friendship between our nations has been
on our shared sacrifices as we fought together side by side _ a
poignant reminder in these turbulent days of the cost of freedom.
...
   ``We want to help the Philippines strengthen its democracy and
continue its economic recovery, and we've offered our belief that a
new long-term security agreement will enhance our mutual security.
... A new agreement will preserve bipartisan support for this
continued economic and military aid.''
   ``Part of America's love of the Philippines is based on pure
unabashed sentiment and optimism. Americans have cheered the people
power ... revolution, which galvanized the world, inspiring
freedom-loving people everywhere. And you, Mrs. President, proved
that ballots are stronger than bullets, and that while democracy
can be delayed, ultimately it cannot be denied.
   ``And your accomplishments since 1986 are monumental: a new
constitution in 1987; free elections for thousands of local and
national leaders, the restoration of press freedom and other civil
liberties, and in just a few short years the Philippines has gone
from a deep recession to steady economic growth. And we urge you to
continue with the free market reforms needed to spur Philippine
economic development.
   ``Political and economic freedom are the destiny of the
Philippine people, and the destiny of the American people must be
and is to stand with you.''
   ``You have said that being a grandparent makes you happier than
being president. Well, Cory, if you'll excuse the informality, that
just's one more thing that you and I agree on,'' he said, raising a
glass and toasting to U.S.-Philippine friendship and ``to a better
world for our grandchildren and for children everywhere.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PRESIDENT AQUINO</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``I have returned to the United States in a world much changed
by startling events. In Central Europe the men of iron vision are
loosening peacefully their long grip on power.''
   Recalling her own country's revolution, she said, ``The memory
of that stirring event is engraved in the heart of all Filipinos
who lived through it and deeply impressed in the memory of the
world.''
   ``The Philippines is a small country and cannot claim to affect
directly events beyond its borders. Certainly not across half the
world in Europe. Yet it is not too much to say that the images of
heroism spawned by our people power revolution gave dominated
peoples throughout the world a glimpse of certain possibilities
that they are now exploring _ the possibility, for example, that
armor and infantry do not exhaust the varieties of power; that
perhaps people by peaceful numbers and unshakeable resolve may
sometimes tilt the balance in their favor _ as they saw it happen
in my country and as it has happened in other parts of the world
since then.
   ``For the first time in a long time something different has
happened in the world, and perhaps the Philippines had something to
do with it. If so, then we have simply returned the favor for the
support we received from friends of liberty throughout the world.''
   ``Anything new is fragile and I share the apprehension of
President Bush that on this bright new age of tolerance and
freedom, the darkness may yet fall abruptly. It has happened in one
country. ... We must remain prepared for that dark contingency, yet
we must do everything prudent possible and prudent to encourage
those who are working for change.
   ``In this desire for constructive change and movement toward
democracy, we are one with the United States. We look to the United
States as the natural leader in this great movement. She has ever
been in the forefront of the modern struggle for both peace and
freedom.''
   Referring to Bush, she said, ``As a man who lived through war,
he knows the price of peace; as I who lived through tyranny know
the irreplaceable value of freedom.''
   ``This sense of new possibilities must inform the future
relations of the United States and the Philippines, and guide the
discussions we shall have. It is time for something new to happen
in the world, and we are all so privileged to be a part of it.''
</TEXT>
