<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-09 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warm Weather in the Northwest and Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably high temperatures warmed the Northwest and Florida
on Thursday, breaking or tying records up to 109 years old in eight
cities. Scattered rain fell in the East and the Midwest.
   Snow showers fell from northern lower Michigan and upper
Michigan to western Wisconsin and southeast Minnesota. Rain
continued along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Scattered rain fell from western New York state to northern
Illinois and southern Wisconsin.
   The mercury climbed to 90 degrees in Hollywood, Fla., snapping
by 3 degrees the record for the date set in 1983.
   Records were also set at the Miami airport (89 degrees, 88 in
1958); Pendleton, Ore. (72, 70 in 1971); and Lewiston, Idaho (66,
63 in 1976). High-temperature marks were tied in Key West, Fla.,
(86, 1880); Portland, Ore. (65, 1987); Billings, Mont. (65, 1981);
and Helena, Mont. (62, 1971).
   The high temperature for the nation was 91 degrees at the North
Dade County Airport near Miami.
   In contrast, a cold front moving across the Atlantic Coast
states brought lower temperatures west of the front. A frost
warning for Thursday was in effect for the mountains of western
South Carolina.
   High-wind warnings remained in effect for the eastern slopes of
the mountains of northwest Wyoming and in Wyoming for the upper
Yellowstone Valley and the Front Range of the Rockies.
</TEXT>
