<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia 1stLd-Writethru a0738 11-09 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Labs Raided by Police, U.S. Agents, 25 Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, CHANGING arrest figure, UPDATING with quotes,
other. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of U.S. and Bolivian agents
raided 11 cocaine labs in eastern Bolivia and arrested 25 people as
drug trafficking suspects, police said Thursday.
   Six airplanes and eight helicopters on Wednesday ferried the
agents to the cattle ranching town of San Ramon, 250 miles
northeast of La Paz, where they arrested 17 people and raided and
destroyed 11 clandestine laboratories for producing cocaine
hydrochloride, police said.
   It was the biggest single sweep since a 3-month operation in
1986.
   Other raiders invaded dozens of homes and shops in the country's
second most populous city, Santa Cruz, 355 miles east of La Paz,
and arrested eight people, including two Colombian chemists, police
said.
   About 350 members of Bolivia's U.S.-trained anti-narcotics
force, called the Leopards, and 30 U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agents took part in the raids, police said.
   They appeared to signal an intensification of Bolivia's
anti-drug efforts, in line with President Bush's recent call for an
all-out international effort against narcotics trafficking.
   ``The purpose of these raids is to dismantle Bolivia's principal
cocaine- producing operations,'' said Don Ferrone, U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration station chief for Bolivia, after
returning from the raid.
   ``It is a new strategy and we are going right at the biggest
organizations and they will have serious problems in the future.''
   Two of those arrested in San Ramon were Argentines carrying
automatic weapons and grenades, the DEA said.
   Dozens of other people were initially caught up in the sweeps
but were cleared of suspicion and quickly released.
</TEXT>
