<DOCNO> AP891109-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HealthCare     11-09 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Care,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Warned Against Piecemeal Health-Care Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoping to move beyond Medicare's doomed
catastrophic illness program, a House committee on Thursday
examined a series of proposals to rework the nation's health care
system and avoid piecemeal reform.
   Douglas Fraser, chairman of the private Committee for a National
Health Insurance, told the House Select Committee on Aging that the
nation's health-care delivery system is ``an absolute shambles''
that leaves many people unprotected and saddles others with huge
costs.
   ``We have to make fundamental changes,'' said Fraser, former
president of the United Auto Workers union. ``Patchwork will not do
it.''
   He said there is growing support for a national health insurance
program, even among major employers who no longer can keep up with
rising health-care costs.
   Committee Chairman Edward Roybal, D-Calif., who himself has
proposed a health-care reform package, said the hearing was
designed to find solutions to ``the nation's cost, quality and
access problems and for building an American health system.'' Up to
37 million Americans are uninsured and many more are underinsured,
particularly against the staggering costs of long-term care, he
said.
   Roybal cited the year-old Medicare catastrophic coverage program
as an example of a piecemeal attempt to improve the health-care
system. Congress is on the verge of scrapping all or part of the
program after being inundated with complaints that its cost were
too high and its benefits unneeded by some senior citizens.
   The blue-ribbon U.S. Bipartisan Commission on Comprehensive
Health Care, established as part of the catastrophic legislation,
also is looking for answers to the problems of the uninsured and
the costs of long-term care.
   Deborah Steelman, chair of the Advisory Council on Social
Security, which also has been asked to examine the nation's
health-care system, told the Aging Committee that determining who
will pay for new health-care benefits is always the ``sticky
wicket'' but that the government could do much more with what it
already is spending.
   Fraser's group is pushing a plan that would retain the Medicare
program for the elderly and cover everyone else through a
state-administered program financed perhaps through payroll taxes,
private insurance premiums, alcohol and tobacco taxes and state
sources.
   Another plan was advanced by Paul Rogers, a former congressman
who co-chairs the private National Leadership Commission on Health
Care. The commission's plan would retain Medicare and private
insurance programs and add a state-administered universal access
plan for the uninsured, financed by fees paid by employers and
people with income above 150 percent of poverty.
   ``Limited access, soaring costs and uncertain quality interact
with the malpractice crisis to form a tightly woven web,'' Rogers
said. ``We need to take the best features of this intricate design
and weave them into a renewed system of health care.''
   Graham Scott, former Ontario deputy minister of health, told the
committee that Canada's national health insurance program is
immensely popular at home, but success there ``does not mean that
it is necessarily the answer for the United States'' because of
cultural differences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
