<HEAD>Shooting Victim's Newborn Baby Dies Two Weeks After Fatal Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with statement by mayor; picks
up 4th graf, `The baby ...' ADDS 3 grafs at end to ADD background, more
comment from mayor; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The infant boy born to a pregnant shooting victim
died Thursday, two weeks after his mother was shot to death and his
father wounded when they were held up outside a childbirth class.
   Christopher Stuart died at 4:34 p.m. at Brigham and Woman's
Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Cathleen O'Donnell. She
declined to release the cause of death.
   The Suffolk County coroner and officials at the district
attorney's office were not immediately available for comment.
   ``Everybody in the city of Boston was really praying beyond hope
that Christopher would make it,'' Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn
said Thursday night.
   The baby had struggled for life in the hospital's neo-natal
intensive care unit since his delivery by emergency Caesarian
section hours after his mother was shot Oct. 23.
   Carol Stuart, 30, a lawyer who was seven months pregnant, was
shot in the head by a gunman who held up the couple in their car
after they left the hospital near the Roxbury section of Boston.
   Charles Stuart, 29, who managed to contact rescuers with his
cellular car telephone, was shot in the abdomen and listed in
stable condition Thursday at Boston City Hospital, a spokesman said.
   At the father's request, family members declined Thursday night
to comment on the infant's death.
   ``It's a very difficult time for all of us and we're just trying
to follow Chuck's wishes,'' said Mrs. Stuart's brother, Carl
DiMaiti.
   The attack on the Stuarts, who traveled from their suburban home
to the city for its medical facilities, launched a city-wide search
for the assailant, who was still at large Thursday night.
   ``There aren't words to describe the sadness and tragedy,''
O'Donnell said. ``This horror struck in Boston on a city street and
that's difficult for a hospital that values life so much.''
   Residents in the Mission Hill neighborhood where the attack took
place expressed little hope this week that the gunman would be
caught, but Flynn said Thursday that police were pursuing strong
leads.
   Flynn said he didn't know if prosecutors would attempt to bring
double-murder charges if a suspect was arrested, ``but the
senseless, tragic act resulted in the deaths of two innocent
people, as far as I'm concerned.''
   ``It hits home when you lose a little baby to the senseless
violence that's taking place in our communities,'' the mayor said.
``We have to recommit ourselves in the memory of all people who
have been innocent victims of violence to make the streets safe for
everyone.''
</TEXT>
