<FIRST>r i AM-China-US     11-09 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Condemns U.S. Congress Attempt at Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China castigated the U.S. Congress on Thursday
for pressing ahead with plans for sanctions against Beijing, saying
sanctions would ``cast a new shadow'' over Chinese-American ties.
   Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li Jinhua also singled out
Washington as being ``too deeply involved'' in the pro-democracy
movement here last spring that was suppressed by Chinese troops.
   If sanctions against China are adopted, ``it will cast a new
shadow over Chinese-U.S. relations and ... will hurt the feelings
of the Chinese people,'' she told a weekly news conference.
   Negotiators from the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives
agreed on Tuesday to stiffen proposed sanctions against China to
protest the June crackdown.
   The measure asks two years of trade sanctions, including
suspension of trade assistance; a halt to certain insurance for
firms doing business in China, and a freeze on exports of
satellites, semimilitary items such as helicopters, and certain
nuclear material and components.
   The bill condemns the ``unprovoked, brutal and indiscriminate
assault'' on the protesters, which it said left at least 700 dead.
   China has said about 300 people died.
   ``At present, Chinese-U.S. relations are in a period of great
difficulties,'' Ms. Li said. ``China should not be held responsible
for the difficulties. The reason for these difficulties is that the
U.S. has gotten itself too deeply involved in the turmoil and
rebellion that happened not too long ago in Beijing.''
   China insists the protests were whipped up by
``counterrevolutionaries'' seeking to overthrow the communist
regime, and says foreign forces supported the uprising.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping also told visiting former President
Richard Nixon last week that the United States was ``too deeply
involved'' in the demonstrations, and China was ``the real victim''
of the events at the time.
   The U.S. government rejects the charges. A State Department
spokesman said this month that the protests ``were clearly the
result of domestic developments in China.''
</TEXT>
