<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-NorwayWhales     11-09 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Norway Whales,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Threat on Norwegian Whaling Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. action against Norway because of its
persistence in hunting whales has been indefinitely postponed, a
spokesman for Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said Thursday.
   Reed Boatright, Mosbacher's spokesman, said a decision had been
due next Monday on whether Norway was violating U.S. law by
interfering with the ban of the International Whaling Conference on
commercial whaling. He said there would now be negotiations with
Norway's new government, headed by Conservative Prime Minister Jan
P. Syse.
   The Norwegian Labor government ousted last month allowed the
taking of 17 whales this year, which it said were for scientific
research. U.S. conservationists, who campaign against all whaling,
say that Norwegian whalers used to take about 2,000 a year and that
17 are not enough for any scientific or commercial purpose.
   Syse's trade minister, Kaci Kullmann Five, had a meeting with
Mosbacher on Thursday. Afterwards, she said Norway would take five
whales next year.
   ``There will not be any certification on Nov. 13,'' Mrs. Five
said in an interview. ``No date has been set.'' She said she
expected ``positive developments'' in future talks.
   Boatright would not say if the United States agreed with Mrs.
Five on further whaling. He said that after negotiations with
Norway, Mosbacher will make a recommendation to President Bush. If
Bush certifies that Norway is interfering with the international
ban, he may restrict or even halt Norwegian shipments of fish to
the United States.
   Roger Payne, senior scientist at the World Wildlife Fund,
predicted a strong reaction from conservationists in the United
States who campaign vigorously to end all whaling.
   ``The conservation community will be jumping all over the
administration if it agrees to that,'' he said, referring to the
Norwegian insistence on continued whaling.
   ``The Norwegians are the only ones doing any whaling except the
Japanese. This would prevent the Japanese from being isolated.''
   Conservationists say the Japanese take about 300 whales a year,
also for what they say are scientific purposes.
</TEXT>
