<DOCNO> AP891109-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-RecessAppointments 3rdLd-Writethru a0756 11-09 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Recess Appointments, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0756,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House May Bypass Senate With `Recess Appointments'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 16th graf: ``Untermeyer's work,'' with earlier report
on the subject</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, frustrated by Senate
delays on its nominations, may give some of its 119 languishing
nominees ``recess appointments'' not requiring Senate action, White
House officials said Thursday.
   Such a parlimentary end run around the Senate's
advice-and-consent powers would surely anger Democatic leaders and
worsen already-strained relations between President Bush and
Congress.
   White House personnel director Chase Untermeyer said he was
preparing recommendations for Bush on the procedures for making a
possible batch of recess appointments during Congress' upcoming
year-end break.
   ``I've done it on my own without the direction of the president
or the chief of staff (John Sununu),'' said Untermeyer. However, he
added, ``I've not been told to stop.''
   Untermeyer said there were 119 presidential appointments pending
as of late Thursday.
   Another White House official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said, ``We're not anxious to do this. This is only a
last resort. But it is something we may be compelled to do,'' said
a White House official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Under the Constitution, the president can temporarily sidestep
the Senate's confirmation powers by appointing a person to fill a
vacancy while the Senate is in recess.
   The provision was put into the Constitution to enable the
government to continue to function when the Senate took long
recesses _ sometimes, in the early days of the Republic, for months
at a time.
   Someone granted such a ``recess appointment'' may serve, under
the Constitution, until the end of the next session of Congress.
   Were Bush to appoint someone during the upcoming yearend recess,
that individual could keep the job at least until the end of 1990
without the Senate having a say.
   Nearly all presidents have made recess appointments from time to
time. And it is a favored tactic for giving political supporters
short-term jobs like ambassadorships near the end of a presidential
term.
   However, the device has never been used in a wholesale fashion
before.
   ``The president really hasn't wanted to resort to this. But
neither did he realize that some many of his nominees wouldn't be
acted on this late on,'' said a White House official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Such a move has high political risks and would escalate the
battle between Bush and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine.
   Up until now, Bush himself has not advocated such a drastic
step, White House sources said. But senior advisers might urge him
to take such a course in an effort to break the Senate logjam, the
sources said.
   Untermeyer's work on the question first was reported in Thursday
editions of The Washington Times.
   Among the pending nominations are Richard G. Austin as head of
the General Services Administration, Barbara Everitt Bryant as
director of the Census Bureau, Brian W. Clymer as urban mass
transportation administrator, Michael Paul Gavin as assistant
secretary of commerce and a host of ambassadorial and judicial
appointments.
   Some of the delayed nominations have been controversial.
   For instance, Bush's choice of James Cason for a top Agriculture
Department post has drawn opposition from environmentalists and
many senators for what they allege to be a pro-development bias.
   And some ambassadorial appointments have been blocked by Senate
Democrats who claim they have few qualifications other than large
contributions to Republican campaigns.
   In fact, on Thursday, Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., vowing to end
an ``ambassadorial spoils system,'' sought to kill Bush's
nomination of Joy Silverman as ambassador to Barbados. `There are
no qualifications for this lady. There's nothing there,'' Sarbannes
told the Senate.
   The nomination of Victor Stello Jr. to be assistant secretary of
energy for defense programs has been stalled since July over
criticism of his record at the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. And
the nomination of Vaugh R. Walker to be a federal judge in Northern
California has been snarled in neoptism charge. He is Bush's cousin.
   At a news conference on Tuesday, Bush accused the Democratic-led
Congress of ``blocking everything I do'' and has often vented his
frustration at the slow pace of Senate consideration of his
nominees.
   And Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater earlier accused the Senate
of holding up dozens of presidential appointments ``for artificial
reasons.''
   At the same time, however, Mitchell has accused Bush of
foot-dragging on other key government positions.
   The Maine Democrat told the Senate recently that Bush had failed
to ``make nominations for nearly half'' of the key executive branch
jobs and that Bush's criticism was ``unfounded and unfair.''
   Many of Bush's ambassadorial nominations have been delayed in
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee _ where Democratic leaders
have accused the president of seeking to fill many of the posts
with political supporters rather than experienced diplomats.
   If Bush does choose to make recess appointments, the Senate
loses its power to deny the individual the post for more than a
year. But there are other ways that Congress can make its will felt.
   ``If the recess appointee wanted to get paid, it might be a
problem,'' said an official in the Senate parlimentarian's office,
who spoke on the condition of anoymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
