<DOCNO> AP891109-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Polly Adv10   11-09 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Polly, Adv 10,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Nov. 10 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NBC's `Polly' Flawed But Enjoyable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is ratings ``sweeps'' time, and you face
considerable Nielsen-boosting sex, violence, and bad manners on TV.
But there are occasional respites, and a nice one for the family
lies ahead on NBC Sunday night.
   It's ``Polly,'' an updated adaptation, with music and a black
cast, of ``Pollyanna,'' the 1960 Disney movie that was so goshdarn
positive it made the Up With People singers seem the Grumble
Chorale.
   This two-hour TV version, which dips into ``The Cosby Show''
cast for its button-cute star, Keshia Knight Pulliam as Polly, and
Phylicia Rashad as her stern spinster aunt, suffers from a similar
case of sugary.
   Still, it's oddly refreshing to see such unabashed innocence and
good will on prime-time TV, if only as an antidote to all the
``fact-based'' TV movies that air later and are mostly routine
salutes to grim.
   This ``Polly,'' written by William Blinn and directed and
choreographed by Debbie Allen, former colleagues in TV's ``Fame,''
is a gentle tale that through its young star slips in a plea for
racial harmony.
   Set in 1955, in times of racial segregation, it takes place in
the mythical, tidy, all-black Alabama town of Harrington, a hamlet
run and virtually owned by Polly's lovely, no-nonsense aunt.
   The aunt played by Rashad _ who in real life is Allen's sister _
believes that life is a very serious matter. Woe betide anyone,
even the town preacher (Larry Riley), heard making a joyful noise.
   All this starts changing when young Polly, left an orphan by a
car crash that killed her parents, arrives from Detroit to live
with her aunt, and quickly becomes best friends with a local orphan
boy (Brandon Adams).
   Young Polly is a small ray of sunshine whose faith in humanity,
regardless of race, is unshakeable. She brings out the good in
everyone.
   But of course that proves a turning point when she befriends a
rich, frowsy old white woman (Celeste Holm) who, as the Caucasian
counterpart of Polly's aunt, runs and virtually owns a nearby
all-white town.
   Such predictability can be overcome with a good script. Problem
is, Blinn, normally a fine writer, has sort of a tame teleplay here.
   Instead of showing the world through the child's shiny brown
eyes, the script is littered with distracting subplots, including
the love of a young music professor (Dorian Harewood) for Polly's
aunt.
   Worse, a supposedly mean old man (Brock Peters) the kids
encounter has a kindly twinkle in his eyes. A mean old man isn't
supposed to have such a twinkle, only a soul of garlic.
   A little more grittiness, less pasteurization, and more sharply
drawn characters would have greatly helped this show. But it's
enjoyable, anyway, for two reasons.
   One is the fine cast, most of whose members have stage
backgrounds. You only wish the script had offered them more.
   The other is the music, particularly Harold Wheeler's tasty
orchestrations of the gentle ballads or rollicking gospel songs.
With two first-rate dance numbers as part of the show, the tunes
help propel ``Polly.''
   They also make you wish this were a full-fledged musical, not a
story with music. It's a little frustrating. As in ``Tap,'' which
had the potential to be a great dance movie, most musical numbers
in ``Polly'' end too quickly and seem unwisely abbreviated.
   Oh, well. ``Polly'' is a good family show, and cheers to NBC for
commissioning it.
   A warning: shoo your tykes away when it ends. For all will
return to normal sweeps-month routine then, and NBC will air its
grim ``Manhunt: Search for the Night Stalker.''
   It is a TV movie based on the true story of Richard Ramirez, the
satanic ``Night Stalker'' of Los Angeles who butchered or raped
more than a dozen people during a deadly spree in 1985.
   Ramirez, convicted of 13 murders, was sentenced to death on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television...
   THE GREAT AUDIENCE QUESTION _ For those who want to know if
ABC's ``PrimeTime Live'' is going to dispense with its studio
audience, the answer from ABC News President Roone Arledge is
probably yes _ but not every week.
   He says the studio audience was made part of the program's
format ``because we were going to do a lot of Town Meeting-type
segments,'' but that hasn't often happened. Now, he says, ABC
executivies are pondering whether to have a studio audience only on
those weeks they feel the program needs it. ``We're in the process
of deciding that right now,'' he says.
   THE REAL AND THE RE-CREATED AT CBS NEWS: Thursday's scheduled
``48 Hours'' program on teen sex included excerpts of a girl
telling a Wisconsin hearing that she had an abortion without
parental consent. Tomorrow, ``Saturday Night With Connie Chung''
re-creates what a Massachusett teen-ager went through _ including
counseling and legal advice _ when seeking an abortion without her
parents' consent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Nov. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
