<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv10   11-09 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 10,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Fri, Nov 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Weaker Corporate Profits Were No Surprise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You have to wonder about the stock market as an
economic forecaster if what they're saying is true: that the recent
market slump has its origins in corporate profit weakness.
   Why? Because the slowing in the growth rate of profits has been
going on for a long time, and with so pronounced a trend that no
informed investor could have been surprised. The red flags were
flying high.
   Even ordinary workaday consumers, those without any particular
knowledge or even interest in corporate profits, must have known,
because it was their stubborness that forced sellers to compete
with lower prices.
   In 1988, based on the Standard &amp; Poor's composite index,
corporate profits showed a 36 percent increase. In this year's
first quarter the rate was down to 22 percent, year over year. In
the second quarter it was under 10 percent.
   Aerospace, apparel, automotive, electrical, metal and oil and
gas companies have been strained. Record profits for the automotive
companies are a matter of history now. In electronics, Wang and
Control Data suffered sharp reversals.
   Theoretically, the stock market sees ahead at least six months,
but in this instance the professionals allegedly were surprised by
events that began at least six months ago and which are likely to
continue for months more.
   The economy is sluggish. Consumers are watching dollar and
credit balances. Reports show they are not losing their buying
confidence, but instead are sharpening their perspective on prices.
They are forcing price cuts.
   The signs are all about. Anheuser-Busch says it is ready to
match competitor discounts. Instead of almost constant sales, Sears
is promoting ``everyday low pricing.'' McDonald's and other
fast-food outlets are finding that customers sometimes prefer to
buy frozen foods and microwave them at home.
   Everyone is aware by now that the car companies are in a fix,
and are willing to talk deals. Knowing this, customers are driving
more hard bargains than new cars. And in some parts of the computer
market it's the same way.
   Such behavior is an extreme contrast to the inflationary
situation that existed through much of the 1970s, when customers
competed to buy and thereby forced up prices _ which in turn caused
other buyers to stampede before prices went even higher. In that
case, the consumer lost on every deal.
   In today's marketplace, competition is among sellers rather than
customers, and customers are winning on almost every deal.
   After one of the longest economic expansions ever, millions of
Americans have bought all the luxuries they need. Anything
additional is optional. If they see a bargain they might buy, but
they are ready to do without too.
   Meanwhile, many companies are involved in a marketplace brawl
that has little to do directly with consumers _ except to put them
in an even better bargaining position.
   Such companies are fighting to retain market position, the
better to greet the eventual upturn. They are reluctant to cut
production sharply; instead, they maintain high production and sell
at low or no profit.
   Holding market position can be extremely costly, of course, but
a lot of companies today are like breakfast cereal companies,
forced to hold onto their shelf position because if they don't they
might never get it back.
   Such a position is a rare one for the consumer because it has
the added benefit of forcing lower both inflation and interest
rates. And in the long run the harsh competition might be good for
producers too.
   In the meantime, however, it isn't very good for corporate
profits, and everyone seemed to have sensed it except the so-called
professional stock traders, who should have been watching that
signal most closely of all.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, Nov. 10.</NOTE>
</DOC>
