<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Baker Adv13   11-09 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Baker, Adv 13,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Nov. 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rappers, Rockers, Crooners and Funksters Flock to Baker</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY302 of Nov. 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the home of producer Arthur Baker, near
Woodstock, N.Y., are crates containing more than 10,000 records. In
midtown Manhattan, the location of Baker's Shakedown Studio, nearly
as many musicians have passed through.
   Bruce Springsteen, Bob Dylan, Miles Davis and Paul McCartney are
but a few of the artists with whom Baker has worked, remixing songs
or producing albums.
   Rappers, rockers, crooners and funksters have all gotten a boost
from Baker's studio expertise and pounding drum sound that's best
described by the Hall and Oates album he produced, ``Big Bam Boom.''
   Disappearing behind the control board doesn't appeal to Baker.
Emotional, hard-headed and opinionated, he believes in the producer
as collaborator, even star.
   ``The producers who turned me on were (Kenny) Gamble and (Leon)
Huff, Thom Bell and all those Philadelphia guys,'' Baker said in a
recent interview at Shakedown.
   ``Norman Whitfield of Motown was a big influence. All those
producers made producer-oriented music. The producers would write
the songs, arrange them and do the whole thing. That's what I
aspire to be.''
   Baker has no catch phrase like Phil Spector's ``Wall of Sound''
or Motown's ``Sound of Young America.'' If anything, the producer
sees walls as something to be broken down, not constructed. That's
why he calls his new record ``Merge.''
   ``My album is representative of the music I like,'' Baker said.
``If you come out to my house and see my records, you know my
influences. This album is the merging of lots of different music.
   ``What I focused on was writing really good songs and making an
album that I found listenable and enjoyable. The next album I'd
like to combine some different elements and make new music.''
   Shirley Lewis, Tiny Valentine and John Warren are featured
singers. Al Green's soaring vocals carry the album's first single,
``The Message Is Love,'' but the song took months to record.
   ``We first did a reading and then he sang it through and it was
really good,'' Baker said. ``He said, `OK, Al Green ain't going to
sing it much better than that ...' But he didn't get the melody, he
rewrote it.
   ``He goes back and sings the medody but it's horrible. I ask
him, `Do you think we can get the other Al Green?' He sang it again
and it was great. Then I had to do some more over-dubbing. We ended
up doing two takes in Boston and four in Memphis.''
   Conflicts in the studio don't faze Baker, who has seen them from
all angles, settling creative differences and causing some, too.
Cocaine was a problem, he admits, and nearly ruined his career
after a run of hit records in the mid-1980s. He's counting on
``Merge'' to bring him back.
   ``The only way I cn do anything is to go in and write songs. I
had a bad reputation. People were saying I was difficult. But I
helped create things like multiple edits and songs without bass
lines. I think I can be innovative again.''
   Baker, a Boston native, made his breakthrough in 1981 with
Africa Bambaata's ``Planet Rock,'' an early rap record. He was soon
one of the industry's hottest producers and remixers, asked to edit
extended versions of songs from Springsteen's ``Born in the USA''
album. Dylan, McCartney and Hall and Oates also wanted his services.
   In 1985, he helped produce the ``Sun City'' record, assembling a
remarkable collection of musicians _ including Springsteen, Davis,
U2's Bono and Ruben Blades _ to perform material attacking South
Africa's apartheid system.
   In a studio crammed with stars, no one was revered more than the
reclusive Davis, who glided past an awestruck Bonnie Raitt and
contributed a horn part to a jazz track that appeared on the album.
   ``We asked Miles if it was OK to have a guy in the studio with a
video camera,'' Baker recalled. ``He starts playing and while he's
playing, he goes, `You can't come in here, you're the wrong color.'
I thought he was talking to the video guy, who's white.
   ``Then he says, `This ain't your country,' and we realized what
he was doing. We stopped and said that was great and asked if he
would mind doing something like that again.''
   But Baker also has unhappy memories of drunken sessions with
Dylan, feuds with Hall and Oates, and drawn out legal battles with
New Edition that he said contributed to his drug problems.
   Now, he's hoping to produce work that equals his best material
and will stick around as long as the blues records that fill his
home.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Nov. 13</NOTE>
