<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv12   11-09 1007</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 12,1034</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Issues and Tactics of '89 Elections Could Spill Over Into 1990 Races</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans already were having an off
off-year, and they knew there was worse coming.
   So they had an alibi ready when Democrats swept the season's big
three elections in New Jersey, Virginia and New York City. The
outcomes ran to form, although the margins for a black governor in
Virginia and mayor-elect in the New York were narrower than the
pollsters anticipated.
   The Republican refrain was a tested and familiar one _ that
these losses were local, not portents of the national elections of
1990.
   But the hangover remedy didn't work this time.
   Republican National Chairman Lee Atwater acknowledged as much,
even as he tried to play down the losses.
   These scattered elections had too much in common, in issues,
themes and tactics that could echo into next year's national
campaign for Congress and 36 governorships.
   Earlier in the year, Democrats had won five out of seven special
elections to the House; their majority will be 259 to 176 heading
into national mid-term elections in which the White House party
historically has lost seats in Congress.
   The 1990 elections also will shape the state governments that
will control the process of reapportioning congressional seats
after the census, another worrisome prospect for the GOP. It takes
a governor or control in at least one branch of the state
legislature to put a party in a bargaining position on
reapportionment. Republicans will control none of the above in the
two state governments shaped by Tuesday's balloting. Democratic
Govs.-elect James J. Florio of New Jersey and L. Douglas Wilder of
Virginia _ who still faces a recount _ will be working with solidly
Democratic legislatures.
   ``Take a look at what happened to underpin reapportionment for
1992,'' said Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
   Atwater said it would be a mistake to read national patterns
into local elections, but there were some:
   _The abortion issue boomeranged on Republicans, who once had
seen it work against Democratic candidates. President Bush, Atwater
and Republican congressional leaders discussed it at a Wednesday
political post mortem. Bush said in advance that he was not budging
in his own anti-abortion stance, enforced with two vetoes this fall.
   Atwater was quoted as saying that if abortion becomes the main
issue in the 1990 campaign, Republicans will lose.
   The Republican losers in Virginia, New Jersey and New York City
all were abortion foes, although each had tempered that opposition.
Wilder's campaign advertisements stressed the issue, saying he
would veto any attempt to take away a woman's right to choose. In
the closest of counts, that almost certainly gained him votes
crucial to his victory margin.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, the House Republican whip, said
extreme positions for or against abortion can only hurt candidates,
but that there is a common sense position in the middle.
   The Republican problem is that when their 1989 candidates tried
to move there, Democrats hammered successfully at their old,
absolutist positions, while anti-abortion groups denounced them for
trying to change.
   Democratic National Chairman Ronald H. Brown said Bush had dug
himself and his party into a hole on the issue.
   But the Democrats aren't home free, either. The official party
position is in favor of unrestricted abortion rights, but Brown
said that should not be a litmus test for their candidates. ``We
don't want to run Democrats away from the party because they won't
favor the platform line on this issue,'' he said.
   _Campaigns were tough, negative and sometimes personal, with
candidates and their advertisements concentrating on tearing down
the opposition. It is a proven tactic; President Bush used it in
1988.
   While Democratic leaders criticized that style of campaigning
and claimed the 1989 outcome would end it, Democratic winners used
it as aggressively as Republicans.
   ``Maybe I can have a role in seeing that it gets a little more
positive,'' Bush said Tuesday. How? ``Well, say I think it ought to
be a little more positive.''
   The argument now and probably next year is about who throws the
first stone, with each side blaming the other for negativism as
both sides go at it. While Brown said the voters are fed up with
negative politics he also said Democrats ``don't believe in
unilateral disarmament.''
   _Wilder became the first black elected governor, and David
Dinkins the first black mayor of New York, although by unexpectedly
narrow margins. Both ran as centrists; neither was vulnerable to
the tax-and-spend, soft-on-crime labels Republicans attached to the
Democratic ticket in 1988. Black Democrats were elected to succeed
white mayors in Cleveland, Seattle and New Haven, Conn. Even the
losing Republicans applauded the trend there and elsewhere;
Gingrich said the black victories were fundamentally good for
America.
   Atwater could point only to a handful of down-the-ballot
victories as evidence of success for black Republican candidates.
   And Eddie N. Williams, president of the Joint Center for
Political Studies, said Republicans still tend to send black
candidates on ``suicide missions,'' running them against heavily
favored Democratic officeholders. He said the Dinkins and Wilder
victories will help the Democrats attract black candidates and
solidify black support.
   There will be at least one major bid for another black
breakthrough next year.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young is preparing to run for governor of
Georgia in 1990. He'll seek the Democratic nomination on what is
likely to be a crowded ballot.
   If he won, two of 50 governors would be black. There are no
black senators, 24 House members.
   And Williams sees no prospect that those numbers will change
significantly next year. ``I don't know where there would be any
major advances in 1990.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 12</NOTE>
