<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 13,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Nov. 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Volume `Comfort Level' Seems To Affect Driving Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That rap or heavy metal music blaring from
teen-agers' car stereos may not be the distraction some people
think.
   People tend to react faster when music is at a personal
``comfort level,'' said Wichita State University psychologist
Marilyn Turner, who has tested about 100 people in a driving
simulator. Subjects were told to brake when a red bulb lit, with
music playing at different levels up to 80 decibels.
   An airplane landing nearby generates 120 or more decibels, rock
concerts generally produce 90 or more, and ear damage can occur at
95 decibels.
   ``In general, we found that people reacted fastest when there
wasn't any music at all,'' Ms. Turner said. ``And we expected as
the music got louder they would get slower in their reaction time.
What happened is that as they got to their preference level, they
actually got a little bit faster.''
   Gender difference also shows up in the tests, she said. Men have
the fastest reaction time when there isn't any music, and women
react fastest when the volume was right for them. Men tend to want
the volume higher than women.
   Turner plans to expand the study to see what effect volume has
on reaction time when people are trying to remember directions,
listening to music they prefer and listening to music they don't
like.
   When someone turns down the music to look for a street address
or in heavy traffic, she said, ``Really, all a person is doing is
saying, `Hey. All of a sudden my driving task isn't automatic any
more.'''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientist's `Pet' Microorganisms Eat Hazardous Waste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAQUEMINE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Portier calls them pets, but others
think his microorganisms may be an answer to hazardous waste
problems.
   ``The bugs feed upon phenol and other organic materials found in
nearly all carbon-based substances. ...These bugs eat and digest
bad materials and produce environmentally neutral byproducts,''
said Portier.
   The Louisiana State University researcher and three engineering
firms have cleaned up a hazardous waste pond and 30,000 cubic feet
of contaminated soil at Georgia Gulf's Plaquemine plant. ``The
water is impeccably clean, but the water was the least of the
problems. The big problem was the sludge and chemicals underneath
the water. That soil is now as safe as garden soil,'' he said.
   ``This is ... the first time we were able to use this natural
process to resolve a large-scale hazardous waste disposal
problem,'' said Vince Tretter, environmental manager at the plant.
   Portier's developments in adapting microorganisms to eat toxic
materials also is planned for a Superfund cleanup at the Old Inger
hazardous waste site near Darrow. It will be the first such use in
a Superfund site.
   ``Only about 60 percent of the sites can be approached from a
microbiology point of view, but the economics are quite attractive
when it can work. It cost about one-third to one-half the cost of
incineration,'' Portier said.
   The microorganisms could be used to clean up oil spills, too, he
said.
   ``Our imagination is the only limit to the future application of
this technology,'' said Peter Perez of Environmental Remediation
Inc., one of the firms involved in the cleanup. He believes
microorganisms will eventually be used to clean up a large
percentage of the nation's Superfund sites.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 13</NOTE>
