<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-CellStudy Adv13   11-09 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Cell Study, Adv 13,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Nov. 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chameleon Scheduled for Space Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note Wednesday time element</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests on the skin of a chameleon
heading for space on Wednesday could help scientists understand
more about cell structure and offer clues to down-to-earth human
problems like osteoporosis.
   ``In space, cells apparently make their normal products but
sometimes these products can't get out,'' said Roy Hammerstedt. He
hopes to learn if cells that secrete hormones malfunction in low
gravity because their structure is changed.
   The experiment will treat chameleon cells with hormones that
change skin color from green to brown or brown to green. If the
cells' structure changes in microgravity, one-thousandth normal,
the hormone won't trigger the change.
   ``Chameleon skin color change is hormonally dependant and
requires its own type of internal cell structure,'' said
Hammerstedt, a biochemist with Penn State University's NASA-funded
Center for Cell Research.
   ``We picked a skin model because it has many of the same
features as some of the more fragile cells we're interested in.''
   Researchers also believe a hormone imbalance causes
osteoporosis, muscle atrophy and other ailments, he said.
Astronauts have experienced bone and muscle problems that mimic
arthritis, osteoporosis and other diseases.
   Wesley Himer, a Penn State biochemist and director of the cell
research center, has found in experiments on U.S. and Soviet space
missions that growth hormone secretions in rats are reduced by half
in space. Experiments in space are useful because microgravity
speeds some cell processes, Hammerstedt said.
   His is one of 12 experiments to be launched Wednesday aboard a
Consort 2 rocket from White Sands, N.M. The seven- to eight-minute
journey will carry the 12-foot-long, 1,004-pound experiment module
to an altitude of 200 miles.
   Other experiments were submitted by Battelle Advanced Materials
Center in Columbus, Ohio; Kansas State University and the
University of Colorado-Boulder; Thiokol Corp.; Instrumentation
Technology Associates; the University of Alabama in Huntsville;
McDonnell Douglas Space Systems Co.; and Phillips Petroleum Co.
   Consort 2 is the second launch from White Sands devoted to
experiments. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has
funds for another this fiscal year. Consort 1 flew March 29 with
six materials science experiments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 13</NOTE>
