<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-09 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0900</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has given final passage to
legislation to raise the hourly minimum wage to $4.25 by April
1991, the first increase in the floor wage since 1981. President
Bush is expected to sign the bill next week.
   The 89-8 Senate vote Wednesday came eight days after Bush and
congressional Democrats agreed on the plan to boost the minimum
wage by 45 cents next April 1 and another 45 cents a year later.
   The measure, passed overwhelmingly by the House last week, also
creates a new, subminimum wage that could be paid to teen-agers for
their first three months in the work force and up to three months
more for those in certified training or education programs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury has begun replenishing its
coffers after last-minute congressional action raising the debt
limit averted the government's first-ever default.
   The Treasury on Wednesday sold $16 billion in three- and
six-month bills in its weekly auction that was postponed on Monday
because the government's borrowing authority had dropped to $2.8
trillion, a level its debt already surpassed.
   The drop also forced postponement of $40 billion in quarterly
refunding auctions and Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady said
the government would default if Congress had failed to act by
midnight Tuesday, which it didn't.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the Machinists union and
Condor Partners have met amid reports the UAL Corp. board of
directors has given its chairman permission to explore the
possibility of a buyout or recapitalization of United Airlines'
parent.
   The meeting in Washington, D.C., was held Wednesday to hear what
Condor is planning for UAL, a union spokesman said.
   He said the union was not seeking to reach any immediate
agreements with Condor, which was formed by Coniston Partners, a
New York investment group that announced last week it had
accumulated a 9.7 percent stake in Chicago-based UAL.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Sentencing Commission has unveiled
draft guidelines for punishing corporate wrongdoers that would
dramatically increase fines for companies convicted of federal
crimes.
   The draft guidelines, published Wednesday in the Federal
Register, contain elaborate formulas for calculating the fines that
companies would be required to pay for a variety of federal crimes.
   In recent years large frauds committed by big corporations have
increased the average fine paid by companies from $48,000 between
1984 and 1987 to $195,000 last year, according to a studies
performed by the commission.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARROLL, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. net farm income will decline steadily
through 1996 from its current record heights, researchers say.
   The projections made Wednesday include forecasts of falling
government subsidies, declining soybean prices and generally stable
prices for cattle, hogs and corn.
   The Food and Agricultural Policy Research Institute predicted a
27 percent drop in net farm income by 1996, but said that still
would leave the income figure higher than in any year before 1986.
</TEXT>
