<FIRST>r f PM-IBM-Micron     11-09 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM-Micron,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM to Give Micron License to Make Latest Memory Chips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. is giving
Micron Technology Inc. a license to make the latest generation of
computer memory chips, a boon to Micron and to buyers who want
American-made chips.
   In its announcement Wednesday, IBM said it is continuing to
discuss a similar licensing arrangement with U.S. Memories Inc.,
the consortium launched in June to rebuild the American share of
the world memory chip market.
   IBM was the world's first company to announce volume production
of the 4 million-bit dynamic random access memory chip, known as
the 4-megabit DRAM.
   The deal helps Micron, a Boise, Idaho-based company that might
not have been able to come up with the design and process
technology for the new generation of chips by itself.
   It also benefits computer users by ensuring that there will be
another American supplier of the chips. IBM is the world's largest
maker of chips but uses its entire production internally. It also
buys chips from outside suppliers, including Micron.
   ``This agreement shows IBM's dedication to preserving American
supplies of vital semiconductor components,'' Joe Parkinson,
Micron's chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
   The only U.S. companies besides Micron that sell DRAMs on the
open market are Texas Instruments Inc., which has a
research-sharing agreement in DRAMs with Japan's Hitachi Ltd., and
Motorola Inc., which is closely allied in DRAMs with Japan's
Toshiba Corp.
</TEXT>
