<FIRST>r f PM-Fax-PostOffices Bjt   11-09 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fax-Post Offices, Bjt,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Installers of Post Office Fax Machines Helped Pioneer Fax Use</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Edd'' in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that is introducing facsimile machines
to the nation's post offices was born out of frustration.
   It was 1985 and Edd Helms was in Atlanta trying to rework a bid
proposal due the next morning from his Miami-based electrical
contracting firm.
   Late at night, Helms asked the hotel desk for its fax number so
he could receive documents from his main office.
   ``They said, `What's a fax?''' said Helms. ``I was stunned. I
thought they were kidding.''
   Helms' company lost the bid, but the incident sparked the idea
for Hotelecopy Inc., which has installed fax machines in more than
1,700 hotels nationwide.
   On Monday, Hotelecopy moved into a new arena as the U.S. Postal
Service's first customer fax machine opened in New York City under
a one-year program that will bring the devices to about 8,000 post
offices nationwide.
   ``The fax machine is what the personal computer or automatic
bank tellers once was,'' said the Hotelecopy president. ``It will
become so integrated into American life that we will wonder how we
got along without it. The post office has recognized that.''
   Hotelecopy, which has contracted with MCI Communications Corp.
for telephone connections to the machines, will install the credit
card-operated fax machines in 54 post offices in the Northeast. It
also plans to submit bids later this month to provide service for
the remaining regions of the country.
   Customers will be charged $12.75 for three minutes of
transmission, which is equivalent to about seven pages.
   Hotelecopy will pay the Postal Service $150 a month rent for
each location and an undisclosed percentage of revenue.
   Hotelecopy, which made its first public stock offering in
September, had revenue of about $5 million last year.
   Even before Hotelecopy was founded, Helms, 43, said he was
extolling the virtues of the fax.
   By the early 1980s, Helms said he decided to place purchase
orders for his contracting company exclusively by fax. He then gave
his suppliers three options: buy a fax, lease one from Helms or
lose his business.
   Today, the Hotelecopy fax network moves about 50,000 pages a
day. Helms recently expanded the service to include translation
services and secretarial work.
   ``A businessperson faxes down a document to us in Miami and we
send back the translation,'' said Helms.
   Hoteleticket Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary, has also placed
airline ticket machines in about 50 hotels, from luxury resorts to
chain establishments. The units can print a ticket and boarding
pass within 10 minutes of order, said Helms.
   ``There is a whole new definition of what fast is and what good
service is,'' said Helms. ``People today want things immediately
and they don't what to go out of their way to get it. Time is too
precious.''
   Helms estimates fax machines are used in about 25 percent of
U.S. businesses but fewer than 1 percent of homes.
   ``Think of the butcher, the baker, the candlestick maker. You
think they have a fax? But soon they may not be able to do without
access to one,'' said Helms. ``That's the void the post office will
fill. The fax-less will no longer have to do without.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AdAwards Bjt   11-09 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ad Awards, Bjt,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Club Picks Federal Express ``Fast-Talker'' Ad As Best of '80s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Express Co. commercial that featured
an incredibly fast-talking businessman was the best advertisement
of the 1980s, according to a survey of the board of the ad trade
group The One Club.
   The Orwellian ``1984'' commercial for Apple Computer Inc. and a
series of Rolling Stone magazine print ads noting the differences
between some perceptions about its readers and reality also were
ranked among the best ads of the decade, the group said Wednesday.
   Ads for Levi Strauss' jeans, Nike shoes, the wine coolers
Bartles &amp; Jaymes and California Cooler and Miller Lite beer also
made the list.
   The One Club, an association of advertising copywriters and art
directors, developed its ranking based on responses to surveys in
which each of its 13 directors was asked to rank personal favorites
from the past decade.
   None of the directors' ad agencies placed an ad on the decade's
best list.
   Of the 12 best ads, 10 involved television commercials, one was
a print campaign and one used billboards.
   Mike Hughes, vice chairman and creative director of The Martin
Agency of Richmond, Va., said the directors generally were trying
to identify ads that broke from convention and spawned imitators of
their own.
   But he said 1985 commercials for Levi's 501 jeans, which showed
young people in urban settings cast in a blue-shaded hue, had a
style copied widely. ``A lot of commercials became blue,'' he said.
   Hughes said the top-rated ``Fast Talker'' ad from Federal
Express in 1982 brought activity to a halt in many households each
time the commercial aired.
   A separate Federal Express campaign from 1980 that showed top
executives anxious to get a package delivered picking up the phone
and saying ``Hello-o-o Federal'' broke the ad taboo of ``Never make
the customer look silly,'' Hughes said.
   Apple's ``1984'' ad showed a dreary scene of prisoners filing in
for a televised address by a dogmatic leader. The gloom was
shattered when a woman tossed a club that broke the screen. The ad
ran only once _ during the telecast of the 1984 Superbowl football
game _ but Hughes said no other ad has had more impact on one
airing.
   Authorship of a memorable ad in the 1980s did not necessarily
mean an ad agency kept the assignment. Ally &amp; Gargano, which made
the two winning Federal Express ads, is no longer the Federal
Express agency, and Apple has dropped Chiat-Day, which made
``1984,'' as its agency.
   But Chiat-Day offices, now known as Chiat-Day-Mojo, were
responsible for five of the 12 best ads, according to the One Club
survey.
   Here is the list of best ads of the decade, the year and the
agency responsible for them, according to The One Club:
   1. Federal Express, ``Fast-Talker,'' 1982, Ally &amp; Gargano, New
York.
   2. Apple Computer, ``1984,'' 1984, Chiat-Day, Los Angeles
   3. Rolling Stone magazine, ``Perception-Reality Campaign,''
1986, Fallon McElligott, Minneapolis.
   4. Nynex, ``Dumbwaiters, Rock Drills, Furniture Stripping,''
1988, Chiat-Day, New York.
   5. Bartles &amp; Jaymes, introductory TV campaign, 1986, Hal Riney &amp;
Partners, San Francisco.
   6. Levi Strauss, ``Gang, Blues Singer, Street Singer,'' 1985,
Foote Cone Belding, San Francisco.
   7. Federal Express, ``Hello-o-o Federal,'' 1980, Ally &amp; Gargano,
New York.
   8. Nike, billboard campaign, 1984, Chiat-Day, Los Angeles.
   9. (tie) Nike, ``I Love L.A.,'' 1985, Chiat-Day, Los Angeles;
California Cooler, introductory TV campaign, 1987, Chiat-Day, San
Francisco; and Miller Lite, ``Butkus, Uecker, Powell,'' 1984,
Backer &amp; Spielvogel, New York.
   10. Wendy's, ``Where's the Beef,'' 1984,
Dancer-Fitzgerald-Sample, New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
