<DOCNO> AP891109-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WhittleProjects     11-09 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whittle Projects,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Considers High-Tech TV Network for Doctors' Waiting Rooms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The media concern Whittle Communications thinks
it's not enough to have taken over the magazine racks in doctors
offices with its series of magazines. Now it wants to get patients
to watch its TV programs as they wait for their appointment.
   Whittle said Wednesday it is developing a closed-circuit,
advertiser-supported television network for installation in 100,000
medical waiting rooms nationwide.
   The company disclosed it was developing the new TV project on
the same day it launched the first in a series of non-fiction books
that contain advertising and are being given for free to 150,000
civic and business leaders.
   Whittle executives hope to decide by year's end whether to
proceed with a large-scale test of the new TV project, which they
said could be the company's largest to date and one of the biggest
in broadcasting, with a potential audience of 30 million a week.
   The Knoxville, Tenn.-based company, which is 50 percent owned by
Time Warner Inc., is already in 60,000 doctor's offices with either
its Special Reports magazines or sponsored posters.
   The TV project has the potential to generate more annual revenue
than the $90 million expected from Whittle's other television
project, the Channel One daily news show for teens that Whittle
plans to launch in March in 1,000 middle and high schools, Whittle
executives said.
   Alan Greenberg, vice chairman of Whittle and the executive in
charge of the new TV project, said the system would deliver
programming live by satellite to doctors' waiting rooms. The rooms
would be equipped with advanced viewing systems _ possibly
high-definition TV sets, multi-screen sets or wide-screen TV.
   ``We want to offer something as different from existing TV
technology as color was from black-and-white,'' he said.
   He said it has not been determined what kind of programming
would be carried on the system, but said that possibilities under
study include a health-related program or an entertainment program.
   Whittle would produce the program, which may last an hour or so,
and the show would be repeated continuously during the day, he
said. A new show could be produced every week or two, he said.
   The project could involve more than $250 million in technology
alone, well above the $150 million being spent on Channel One.
   Greenberg said the TV project is a logical extension of
Whittle's involvement with publications targeted to people in
medical waiting rooms.
   Special Reports, a series of six quarterly publications, are
read by about 60 percent of the people visiting the 17,000 doctors'
waiting rooms where the magazines are available, he said.
   The audience is predominantly women with children, an appealing
target for many advertisers that is often hard to reach in large
numbers with other media.
   He said Whittle has received ``very positive vibes'' from the
medical community about its plans for a TV network.
   If the TV project is launched, Greenberg said, advertisers would
probably be given the chance to buy packages that would include ads
in the magazines and on the TV network with the guarantee that
competing brands would not appear.
   He said it had not yet been determined how much advertising time
would be sold on each program, but said it would probably be less
than the 16 minutes of network and local advertising carried each
hour on broadcast television.
   Whittle plans to decide in late December whether to undertake a
large-scale test of the system, Greenberg said. The test could
begin in mid-1990, he said, and if that proves successful, the
project could be launched nationally the following summer.
   The main stumbling blocks, he said, are assurances that the
programming can be delivered on time and the cost of technology.
   The first book in what Whittle is calling The Larger Agenda
series is ``The Trouble with Money'' by William Greider, who wrote
``The Secrets of the Temple,'' which explored the Federal Reserve
System.
   The books in the series are slimmer than most regular books so
that harried opinion-makers will read them, said Whittle editor
William S. Rukeyser.
   Greider's book runs 96 pages with 18 pages of advertising, all
of it from Federal Express Co., the air courier based in Memphis,
Tenn.
   Federal Express also is shipping the books for free to 150,000
government and business leaders over the next few days.
   In addition, the book will be available without advertising for
$11.95 in 150 selected Waldenbooks stores later this month.
   Rukeyser said Whittle hopes to publish one new book in the
series every two months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-InterestRates     11-09 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Interest Rates,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Lowers Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve, after weeks of complaints
from the Bush administration about high interest rates, has nudged
a key interest rate lower in a move analysts predicted would
trigger widespread declines in a variety of consumer and business
borrowing rates.
   Economists were looking for commerical banks to cut by one-half
percentage point their prime lending rate, which is used as a base
to calculate more than one-third of their business and consumer
loans.
   One bank, Southwest Bank of St. Louis, said Wednesday that it
was cutting its prime lending rate from 10.5 percent to 10 percent.
While the move was not immediately followed by the country's
largest banks, analysts predicted that it would be, perhaps later
this week.
   Many economists predicted that the easier Fed monetary policy
would accelerate a move to lower mortgage rates.
   Wall Street was buoyed by the Fed's actions with stock prices up
sharply on investor optimism that the central bank was moving to
keep the economy from slipping into a recession. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks closed with a gain of 26.23 points
at 2,623.36.
   As usual, the Fed made no announcement of its decision to move
toward an easier monetary policy.
   However, analysts said there was little doubt that such a
decision had been made, given the fact that a bellwether interest
rate, the federal funds rate, traded again Wednesday at 8.5
percent, down from 8.75 percent when the week began.
   The federal funds rate is the interest that banks charge each
other to make overnight loans. Because it is directly influenced by
the Fed's decisions on the amount of cash to make available to the
banking system, it considered the best gauge of Fed policy
intentions.
   ``It is clear that the Fed has eased,'' said Allen Sinai, chief
economist of the Boston Co. ``The central bank is acting to prevent
the economy from heading into a serious downturn.''
   Federal Reserve officials refused comment on a report in
Wednesday's Washington Post that the decision to ease was made
during a telephone conference call Monday among members of the
Federal Open Market Committee, composed of Fed board members in
Washington and presidents of five of the 12 regional Federal
Reserve banks.
   The FOMC, which gathers in Washington eight times a year to map
monetary strategy, will meet Tuesday and some economists expressed
surprise that the Fed took action this week instead of waiting for
the regularly scheduled meeting.
   The quarter-point drop in the federal funds rate this week is
the fifth small decline that has occurred since late May when the
central bank began to reverse a year-long effort to drive interest
rates higher as a way to fight inflationary pressures.
   President Bush and others in the administration have been
complaining that the central bank has been moving too slowly to
lower interest rates. White House Budget Director Richard Darman
warned in August that if the economy does slip into a recession, it
will be the fault of the Fed's tight-money policies.
   Some economists, however, said Wednesday that the Fed was wrong
to buckle to political pressure, warning that the action could make
inflationary pressures worse in 1990.
   ``I am very disappointed in the Fed and very pessimisitc about
the chances of keeping inflation down,'' said Cynthia Latta, an
economist with DRI-McGraw Hill. ``They may be thinking that they
can loosen, rescue the economy and then tighten again, but
experience has shown that doesn't usually work.''
   Other economists were not as pessimistic, saying that if the Fed
had waited to ease until it got inflation down further, it would
have run an even greater risk of dumping the economy into a
downturn.
   ``Central banks in the past have made big errors in fighting
inflation for too long and then watching as the economy tumbles
into a widespread, broad recession,'' Sinai said. ``That just
intensified the downturn and forced the central bank to pump up the
economy with easy money, creating a bust-boom situation.''
   Various analysts said they believed that a hallmark of the Fed
under Chairman Alan Greenspan has been a gradual approach to either
tightening or loosening monetary policy and for that reason they
said that the 0.25 percent drop in the federal funds rate would not
be followed quickly by further decreases.
   But even the modest reduction will be enough to prompt
reductions in the prime rate and other business and consumer
borrowing rates, economists predicted.
   Mortgage rates have already dropped into single digits with
fixed-rate mortgages averaging 9.82 percent last week, according to
a survey by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Some economists forecast that rates could drop by another
one-half percentage point by the end of the year in response to the
Fed's easier credit moves.
</TEXT>
