<DOCNO> AP891109-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL Bjt   11-09 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, Bjt,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Management Resumes Effort to Sell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under the growing threat of an outside takeover,
United Airlines pilots are again talking with management and
possible investors about an employee buyout of the company.
   Directors of United's parent company, UAL Corp., have given
Chairman Stephen Wolf the go-ahead to explore a deal, Hank
Krakowski, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, said
Wednesday.
   The pilots in October spearheaded an attempted employee buyout
of the airline company, but the bid failed for lack of financing.
   Krakowski said the pilots have met with management, and the
union is ``continuing to explore any and all options in its effort
to gain employee control of the airline.''
   ``All I can say is the pilots are seeking employee ownership
with the current management team,'' Krakowski said. He did not,
however, exclude an effort with other parties.
   Investor Saul Steinberg, who was a passive investor in UAL and
recently sold a sizable stake, met with pilot representatives
Tuesday and indicated he might participate in a bid ``under the
right circumstances,'' the Chicago Tribune quoted an anonymous
source as saying.
   Steinberg last week sought government clearance to acquire more
than a 15 percent stake in the company.
   Gus Oliver of Coniston Partners said he is aware that UAL
directors have given Wolf the go-ahead to explore buyout
possibilities, but it doesn't change his goals.
   He said: ``... There has been no change in our plans'' to gain
control of UAL. We've been talking to all interested parties and
will continue to do so.''
   Coniston, a New York investment group, met Wednesday with
representatives of United's Machinist union.
   The meeting in Washington was to hear what the group was
planning for UAL, said spokesman Jim Conley of the Machinists,
United's largest union representing 25,000 of its 70,000 workers.
   He said the union was not seeking to reach any immediate
agreements with the group, which last week announced that it had
bought up 9.7 percent of UAL's stock.
   Oliver refused to elaborate on the substance of the meeting.
   The Machinists have opposed the employee ownership plan promoted
by the pilots and contributed to its collapse in October.
   Coniston wants to reduce UAL's board of directors from 16
members to five, three of whom would be Coniston principals.
   UAL spokeswoman Sara Dornacker declined to comment on the latest
developments.
   Directors of UAL issued a statement last month indicating the
board would not consider any offer under $300 a share _ the
per-share price that failed in October.
   UAL stock gained $5.25 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange
trading Wednesday to $185 a share.
</TEXT>
