<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Turner-OzMania     11-09 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turner-Oz Mania,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turner, Others Turning Yellow Brick Road Into Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turner Entertainment Co., which owns the movie
``The Wizard of Oz,'' is off to see the banker to turn the Yellow
Brick Road into gold.
   The 50th anniversary of the release of the movie has ignited a
marketing mania of movie memorabilia. Turner Entertainment, which
also owns ``Gone With the Wind,'' stands to make millions from Oz
license rights alone.
   Turner has re-released the original movie to theaters across the
country and is selling a special Oz anniversary videocassette. The
tape includes 17 minutes of previously unseen footage of Buddy
Ebsen, the original Tin Man. The role went to Jack Haley after
Ebsen suffered an allergic reaction to the Tin Man's makeup.
   The video, introduced in early October, already has sold more
than 2 million copies at $24.95 each.
   Turner has produced a catalog to help fans skip through the
merchandising department of the Emerald City in the privacy of
their homes. It includes a special ``Wizard of Oz'' jean jacket for
$250, as well as a similar ``Gone With the Wind'' jacket.
   ``It's amazing the amount of interest people have about the Oz
collection,'' said Shelley Charles, general manager of the CNN
Turner Store. ``It just keeps going.''
   So far 49 companies have received licenses to market products,
ranging from Franklin Mint heirloom dolls, which retail from $135
to $245, to lunchboxes and playing cards. Several hundred people
are on waiting lists for official Oz silk-sreened color prints from
artist Melanie Taylor Kent which sell for $2,500 each.
   The Western Costume Co. in Hollywood is producing 500 pairs of
ruby slippers, replicas from the original mold of those Judy
Garland wore as Dorothy, for $5,000 a pair.
   ``We're getting 20 calls a day and we've only made three pair so
far,'' said company President Paul Abramowitz. ``This (the Oz
movie) is one of the great dreams of America. People want a piece
of it.''
   A reproduction pair of ruby slippers is on display at the CNN
Turner Store, not for sale. But a ruby slipper rhinestone pin can
be purchased for $150.
   Turner Entertainment is not the only entity profiting from Oz
mania. Auction houses selling props from the film also have
profited.
   One of the supposedly original seven pairs of ruby slippers sold
for $165,000 last year. The pointed Wicked Witch's hat Margaret
Hamilton wore sold for $33,000. Dorothy's twister-proof gingham
dress went for a non-bargain basement $22,000. And the Cowardly
Lion's can of ``witch remover'' brought in $20,000 for a New York
City collection house in June.
   There's even new interest in Oz author L. Frank Baum. ``The
Dreamer of Oz,'' an NBC-TV movie scheduled to air at Easter, is due
to start production next month with John Ritter as Baum.
   Baum was 44 when ``The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' was published in
1900 and made him wealthy. He died in 1919 and his creation is
still a moneymaker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0272 </DOCNO>
