<FIRST>r f PM-Georgia-Pacific-ICC     11-09 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia-Pacific-ICC,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Gets ICC Clearance to Include Railroads in Takeover
Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. has received government
clearance to include four railroads controlled by Great Northern
Nekoosa Corp. in its bid to acquire the paper products company.
   The Interstate Commerce Commission approved the clearance, which
is required when the holder of a railroad seeks to acquire another,
said Georgia-Pacific spokeswoman Gail Smith.
   ``This is part of the process,'' Ms. Smith said Wednesday.
``Both Georgia-Pacific and Great Northern control railroads, and
this is a clearance necessary for approval to acquire Great
Northern's railroads.''
   Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific now controls four ``short line''
railroads, used primarily to transport products and raw materials
to and from company facilities in California, Arkansas, Louisiana
and Mississippi.
   Great Northern, based in Norwalk, Conn., also controls four rail
lines _ two in Georgia, one in Mississippi and one in Wisconsin.
   Georgia-Pacific last month announced a $3.13 billion offer to
acquire Great Northern. The Atlanta company has offered $58 a share
for each of Great Northern's approximately 54 million shares of
outstanding stock.
   Great Northern is expected to respond to the offer next week.
The tender offer expires at midnight EST Nov. 29.
   Stephen Hill, Great Northern's director of investor relations,
declined to comment on the ICC decision and on his company's
continued consideration of the Georgia-Pacific offer.
   ``We have to issue a formal response next week, and we will,''
Hill said.
   Since the announcement of Georgia-Pacific's takeover bid, Great
Northern's officers have been named in two separate federal
lawsuits challenging anti-takeover measures taken by the directors.
The lawsuits were filed in Portland, Maine, where Great Northern is
incorporated.
</TEXT>
