<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SouthAfrica-Privatize     11-09 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Africa-Privatize,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Gets Record Check After Privatizing Steel Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government received a
check worth $1.1 billion Thursday for the sale of the state-owned
steel company to the private sector.
   Finance Minister Barend du Plessis said the money would be used
to reduce debt, thereby helping the government save about $200
million a year in interest payments.
   The check, believed the be the largest ever written in South
Africa, represented proceeds from the sale of 1.85 billion shares
in Iscor, the country's largest steel and iron producer. Shares
were sold at 2 rand each _ or roughly 76 cents _ to 300,000
purchasers.
   However, a controlling interest in the company was offered to a
range of major financial institutions and not made available to the
general public.
   About 54,000 Iscor employees, many of them blue-collar workers,
received 100 shares free.
   Iscor will continue to be run by its current management. The
board of directors will be determined by the major institutional
shareholders.
   The Iscor shares were listed on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange
for the first time on Wednesday, the largest listing in the
exchange's 101-year history.
   The result was a day of hectic trading that saw Iscor stock rise
from an opening price of 2.25 rand to 2.27 rand at the close. The
exchange said 32 million Iscor shares changed hands, by far the
most highly traded new listing ever on the exchange.
   Du Plessis said the privatization would enable the government to
spend less on interest payments and gain revenue by taxing Iscor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
