<DOCNO> AP891109-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WangCuts     11-09 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wang Cuts,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wang Announces `Reordering' of Business, Layoff of 2,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc., the struggling computer
maker that cut about 5,000 workers this year and posted financial
losses, today announced it would lay off 2,000 more workers as part
of a ``fundamental reordering.''
   ``Immediate and deliberate action does not call for another
reorganization,'' Richard Miller, president of the Lowell-based
company, said. ``Rather it demands a revolution _ a radical and
fundamental reordering of the way in which every individual at Wang
follows through on their respective responsibility to our
customers,'' he said in a news release..
   The company's new approach, according to Miller, will eliminate
bureaucracy to put Wang in closer touch with the needs of its
customers.
   ``We must become increasingly more efficient in the way we
work,'' Miller said.
   The result will be the elimination of approximately 2,000 jobs
throughout the company by Jan. 1. A severance package for these
employees will result in a onetime charge of $30 million against
earnings in the company's second quarter, which ends Dec. 31.
   Wang last month reported a first-quarter loss of $62.1 million,
and Miller said at the time he expected losses to continue through
the second quarter. But he predicted the company would return to
profitability by the fourth quarter next June.
   Wang Laboratories earlier this year had cut about 5,000
employees, lowering its workforce to approximately 25,000.
   The high-tech industry has suffered other setbacks. Data General
Corp. announced last month it would eliminate 2,200 jobs, and
Digital Equipment Corp. recently offered voluntary severance to 700
workers.
   ``To survive and prosper in the maturing market of the next
decade, Wang Laboratories must acknowledge that our customers are
our lifeline,'' Miller said.
   Miller said Wang would change the way it operates in various
phases of its business, including product development, technical
service support and the process of taking orders for products and
shipping them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
