<FIRST>r f BC-PhilipMorris-Rothmans     11-09 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Philip Morris-Rothmans,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Agrees to Sell Shares in Rothmans International</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. Inc. on Thursday announced it
has agreed to sell its stake in Rothmans International PLC to the
subsidiary of a Swiss-based holding company for the equivalent of
$860 million.
   Philip Morris, a major consumer products company, said it
expects to realize a pre-tax gain of more than $450 million on the
sale.
   Under the transaction, Compagnie Financiere Richemont AG will
pay Philip Morris 610 million pounds in 10.25 percent
sterling-denominated notes maturing in 1994.
   Philip Morris purchased a 29.9 percent equity interest in
Rothmans, a London-based tobacco company, and related trademark
rights in 1981 for $350 million. Philip Morris said it will retain
the trademark rights in the United States.
   ``Our investment in Rothmans has increased in value and has
generated cash returns, but it has also been more passive than we
anticipated in 1981 and we now consider it preferable to divest
it,'' said Hamish Maxwell, chairman of Philip Morris.
   Philip Morris' three main operating segments are tobacco,
packaged foods and beverages. Its products include Marlboro and
Benson &amp; Hedges cigarettes, Maxwell House coffee, Kraft-brand foods
and Miller beers. The company has its headquarters in New York.
</TEXT>
