<HEAD>Intellicall Denies Allegations By AT&amp;T Over Billing Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intellicall Inc. on Thursday denied it is
programming its pay telephones to illegally obtain billing
information owned by American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
   An AT&amp;T lawsuit suit filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
Dallas asks for unspecified actual and punitive damages from
Intellicall and for an order requiring Intellicall to stop using
the information.
   ``We are examining the lawsuit to evaluate our options and
formulate the company's response,'' Intellicall President Stephen
Polley said. ``We vigorously deny the allegations and expect that
we will prevail.''
   AT&amp;T said the issue involves how Intellicall pay phones
determine the validity of calling card numbers for billing purposes.
   The lawsuit says Intellicall pay phones are able to access
AT&amp;T's card validation system, which contains information that AT&amp;T
considers competitive.
