<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-GlassVenture     11-09 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Glass Venture,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford-Japanese Glass Co. Form Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will enter into a joint
venture with a Japanese glass company to make windows for vehicles
made at the U.S. assembly plants of a number of Japanese automakers.
   Central Glass Co. and Ford said Wednesday that Ford's glass
division plants would supply the joint venture company with flat
glass. The glass will be made into windshields and side and rear
windows for the Japanese automakers at a site yet to be determined.
   Manufacturing should begin in the latter half of 1991.
   Japanese companies making cars and trucks in the United States
include U.S. subsidiaries of Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd., Honda
Motor Co. Ltd., Isuzu Motors Ltd., Mazda Motor Corp., Mitsubishi
Motors Corp., Nissan Motor Co. Ltd., and Toyota Motor Corp.
   Central Glass will own 51 percent of the new company and Ford
will own the rest.
