<HEAD>Prices Steady as Market Awaits Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened steady to
slightly lower this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Trading in corn and soybeans is expected to be subdued as
investors await the release this afternoon of the U.S. Agriculture
Department's crop report.
   The report may show larger than previously expected corn and
soybean crops. A lack of export business may also put a damper on
prices, said analyst Joel Karlin of Research Department Inc. in
Chicago.
   Wheat prices are expected to get some support from the National
Weather Service's six- to 10-day forecast, which calls for dry
weather in winter wheat crop areas.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to a \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.04 a bushel; corn was a
{ cent lower to a \ cent higher wtih December at $2.37\ a bushel;
oats were a { cent lower to } cent higher with December at $1.41} a
bushel; soybeans were } cent to 3\ cent higher with November at
$5.64{ a bushel.
   Livestock future prices were mixed and pork prices were lower in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
