<FIRST>r f PM-TaintedFeed 1stLd-Writethru f0069 11-09 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tainted Feed, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0069,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restrictions on Nearly 1,000 Farms Because of Contaminated Cattle
Feed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with EEC investigation; picks
up 13th graf pvs, `National Farmers ...' This also moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain today banned milk sales by more than 900
farms because of lead-tainted feed that killed 18 cattle, and the
government blamed the contamination on a criminal conspiracy.
   Hundreds of Dutch farms also were affected after dozens of
cattle died of lead poisoning.
   In Brussels, European Economic Community Agriculture
Commissioner Ray MacSharry ordered an immediate investigation into
the alleged conspiracy that is believed to stretch across several
EEC nations.
   MacSharry will contact ``all the relevant authorities in
Britain, Belgium, the Netherlands and West Germany,'' said an EEC
Commission official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   British Agriculture Minister John Gummer said a shipment of rice
bran used as cattle feed started in Rangoon, Burma, and was
contaminated with lead from other cargo aboard the ship on its
journey to the Belgian port of Antwerp.
   Authorities in Antwerp diverted the feed to Holland for
destruction, he said. But instead it passed through several hands
and was turned into maize pellets that ended up being sold by a
feed importing company in Britain and the Netherlands.
   ``There has been a major criminal conspiracy,'' said Gummer said.
   ``It has meant that there are 300 farms in Holland which are
under restriction and I have no doubt that by the time we have
completed the material here during the day, we may have as many as
1,000 farms or just over that in Britain,'' he said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. radio interview.
   The Agriculture Ministry said milk from the 940 affected British
farms, mostly in southwest England, is being collected separately
for testing and thousands of gallons have been withheld from public
sale.
   The ministry said milk from 200 farms had been tested and 89
were found to have milk above the trigger level for concern about
lead contamination but below the safety level of 200 parts of lead
per billion.
   Officials said most of the farms which had received the feed had
now been traced.
   On Wednesday, Gummer urged the European Commission to open a
full-scale inquiry into the alleged conspiracy.
   National Farmers' Union deputy president David Naish said
farmers had suffered heavy losses.
   ``There are going to be some very substantial civil claims _
initially against the suppliers of the feed and then going back
further down the chain,'' he said.
   In The Hague, Dutch Agriculture Ministry spokesman Mat Thissen
said that the Dutch authorities had thoroughly investigated the
origin of the tainted rice bran after more several dozen cattle
died of lead poisoning in the northern Netherlands last month.
   ``The (feed) component was traced to a firm in Dronten (in the
central Netherlands), then to back Antwerp and also Hamburg,''
Thissen told The Associated Press, adding that he hoped the inquest
would be completed by next week.
   He disputed part of Gummer's account, saying there was no
evidence yet indicating that the cattle feed had been shipped to
the Netherlands to be destroyed.
   Thissen said the Dronten firm had exported part of the tainted
rice bran to Britain, but he did not know the quantity involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0287 </DOCNO>
