<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Oil     11-09 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Royal Dutch-Shell's Third-Quarter Profit Falls 16 Percent; BP's Drops
34 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies and British
Petroleum Co. PLC, two of the world's largest oil companies, posted
sharply lower third-quarter profits Thursday, hurt by sagging
results in two main businesses.
   Royal Dutch-Shell, the world's second largest oil company behind
Exxon Corp., said its net income for the three months ended Sept.
30, fell 16 percent to 652 million pounds, or $1.04 billion,
compared with 778 million pounds, or $1.2 billion, in the same
period a year ago. The company does not report consolidated
per-share earnings.
   Revenue rose 12.5 percent to 16.2 billion pounds from 14.4
billion pounds in the comparable 1988 period.
   London-based British Petroleum, which owns Cleveland-based
Standard Oil Co., said its net profit for the three months fell 34
percent to 211 million pounds compared with 318 million pounds a
year ago.
   Revenue for the fourth-largest oil concern totaled 7.6 billion
pounds, up 14 percent from 6.65 billion pounds in the same 1988
period.
   Both companies' chemicals businesses suffered due to lower
demand and prices for chemical products, while refining and
marketing results fell as refined product margins and sales volumes
declined.
   The companies' financial statements are based on British
accounting methods and cannot be directly compared with those of
most American companies. Inventories are valued on the basis of
first in first out (FIFO), instead of the typical American system
of last in first out (LIFO).
   On the American basis, Royal Dutch-Shell's third-quarter net
income fell 20 percent to 667 million pounds, from 837 million
pounds a year ago.
   Royal Dutch-Shell, based in The Hague, the Netherlands, said a
38 percent drop in chemicals earnings offset substantial gains in
oil exploration and production.
   Refining and marketing results also slipped lower while
corporate charges jumped 64 percent to 115 million pounds from 70
million pounds a year ago, the result of currency losses totaling
101 million pounds, more than triple year-earlier losses.
   For the first nine months of the year, Royal Dutch-Shell's net
income advanced 31 percent to 2.93 billion pounds from 2.23 billion
pounds. On the American basis, it rose 12 percent to 2.68 billion
pounds from 2.4 billion pounds. Revenue gained 12 percent to 46.5
billion pounds from 41.6 billion pounds.
   British Petroleum's third-quarter profit on an American
accounting basis fell 34 percent to 264 million pounds from 402
million pounds. Per share earnings came to 4.2 pence a share, or 7
cents, compared with 5.2 pence, or 8 cents in the comparable period
last year.
   British Petroleum said higher crude oil prices only partially
offset lower production and higher production costs and taxes.
Chemicals earnings declined, reflecting weaker product demand, and
refining and marketing results fell 29 percent as U.S. margins
slipped.
   For the nine months, net profit amounted to 1.3 billion pounds
compared with 938 million pounds in the year-earlier period.
Revenue gained 10 percent to 21.6 billion pounds from 19.6 billion
pounds.
   On an American basis, earnings totaled 1.02 billion pounds
compared with 1.13 billion pounds. Earnings per share amounted to
23.5 pence compared with 15.5 pence.
</TEXT>
