<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Disney     11-09 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Disney,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 56 Percent Profit Gain in 4th Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Walt Disney Co. said Thursday its
fourth-quarter earnings rose by 56 percent, reflecting strong
attendance at its theme parks and booming results from its home
video unit which had big sales on its release of the movie
``Bambi.''
   Disney said its profit rose 35 percent for the year with big
contributions from all of its main businesses, which include filmed
entertainment, consumer products and theme parks and resorts.
   In filmed entertainment, for instance, the company had higher
than expected profits from movies like ``Honey, I Shrunk the
Kids,'' and ``Dead Poets Society.''
   For the quarter ending Sept. 30, Disney earned $212.7 million,
or $1.54 per share, compared to $136.4 million, or 99 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose by 33 percent to $1.3 billion from
$1 billion.
   For the fiscal year, net income was $703.3 million, or $5.10 per
share, compared to $522 million, or $3.80 per share, last year.
   Full-year revenue climbed 34 percent to $4.6 billion from $3.4
billion.
   Operating income climbed 62 percent to $373 million for the
quarter and 39 percent for the fiscal year to $1.2 billion.
   Disney chairman Michael Eisner and president Frank Wells noted
in a statement that more people attended Disney theme parks than
ever, and spent more on average. The new Disney-MGM Studios
attraction in Florida was a major contributor to the sector's
earnings, they said.
   Eisner was brought in to run Disney at the end of the fiscal
year 1984, in which the company earned $98 million on revenues of
$1.7 billion. Since then, annual revenues have increased at an
average rate of 35 percent, profits are up sevenfold, and the stock
is worth about eight times as much per share after adjusting for
stock splits.
</TEXT>
