<DOCNO> AP891109-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WangCuts Bjt   11-09 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wang Cuts, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wang Announces `Reordering' of Business, Layoff of 2,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Wang Laboratories Inc., declaring
computers no longer represent a boom industry, announced Thursday
his company would undergo a ``fundamental reordering'' and cut
2,000 more workers from its payroll.
   The cutback was the latest sign of a high-tech industry slowdown
that has contributed to a softening of the region's economy.
   ``Some fundamental things are happening that will drive all
(computer) companies to do things differently or they will fail,''
Wang president Richard Miller said.
   Miller was named president of Wang in August, succeeding
Frederick Wang, who had been ousted from the job by An Wang, his
father, company founder and chairman.
   Prior to Thursday's announcement, the company already had cut
about 5,000 jobs this year and announced plans to sell $200 million
in assets. Furthermore, Wang reported a first quarter loss of $62.1
million in the first quarter that ended Sept. 30, and Miller
predicted more losses for the second quarter.
   Miller said under the company's new approach, Wang will cut its
bureaucracy to get in closer touch with the needs of its customers.
   ``We are eliminating the layers between the field and
laboratory,'' he said. ``We will eliminate entire functions _
functions that I view as stifling.''
   For example, he said, the company's product development programs
often duplicate efforts, with no single group taking
responsibility. As a result, products often have been introduced
late.
   But Miller said departments will be combined, leading to a
streamlined approach.
   The reorganization of the company will mean the loss of about
2,000 by Jan. 1, lowering the Wang workforce to just over 22,000,
he said.
   About 1,000 of the layoffs will occur in Massachusetts, mostly
at the company's headquarters in Lowell, with the rest being
scattered around the world.
   A severance package for these employees will result in a onetime
charge of $30 million in the company's second quarter, which ends
Dec. 31.
   Miller said the restructuring announced Thursday would cut
annual costs by about $115 million, but he stressed that the
company was not simply calculating how much needed to be cut in
order to be profitable.
   The Massachusetts high-tech industry has suffered other
setbacks. Data General Corp. announced last month it would
eliminate 2,200 jobs, and Digital Equipment Corp. recently offered
voluntary severance to 700 workers.
   ``I think restructuring is becoming a common word in this
industry,'' Miller said.
   Miller said much of Wang's bureaucracy grew while the high-tech
industry was booming. But now the industry has reached a
``maturing'' stage with slower growth, he said.
   The bureaucracy ``just built up because of the luxury of very
big margins in a high growth industry,'' he said.
   But while Miller pointed to the fluctuations in the computer
industry for many of his company's problems, analysts said some of
the trouble _ particularly poor customer service _ has been unique
to Wang.
   ``They have had this problem with service and support for a long
time,'' said Steven Wendler, an analyst with Gartner Group Inc. in
Stamford, Conn. ``Rick Miller is a breath of fresh air.''
   Also, Wendler said, after the company completes the cost-cutting
measures, ``the hemorrhaging, financially, will stop.''
   ``A lot of Wang customers have the shakes right now,'' he said.
   George Elling, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner and
Smith Inc. in New York, said during the 1970s and early 1980s, Wang
did not pay attention to customer service because it became
confident as a leader in word processing equipment.
   ``They had something everyone wanted,'' he said. ``People were
willing to put up with poorer service.''
   ``Wang was too slow to recognize they needed to change,'' he
said.
   Part of the change, Miller said, will include more focus on
software and other computer applications.
   ``Most customers are not crying for new technology,'' he said.
``They are crying for new applications of technology.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891109-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Electricity     11-09 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Electricity,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Withdraws Nuclear Plants From Electricity Privatization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it would withdraw
nuclear plants from the planned privatization of the nation's
electricity industry.
   Energy Secretary John Wakeham, speaking in the House of Commons,
said the move was necessary to ensure the public sale of the
industry is held before the next national elections, which must be
called by mid-1992.
   Wakeham said high costs associated with nuclear energy also were
a key factor in the decision to keep the plants under government
control.
   The electricity privatization, which had been expected to raise
up to $43 billion, would be the largest yet under Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's successful program.
   Since the privatization program began, the government has sold
billions of dollars worth of state-owned companies _ including
Jaguar PLC and British Airways PLC _ to promote capitalism.
   But the electricity sale and the planned sell-off of Britain's
water industry are highly controversial. Opponents say such vital
utilities, particularly nuclear plants, should stay in state hands
for security reasons.
   Britain's 18 existing nuclear plants will be placed under the
control of a government-owned company after the government
privatizes their current parent, the Central Electricity Generating
Board, Wakeham said.
   The overall plan involves breaking up the Central Electricity
Generating Board into privately held generating companies called
National Power and Power Gen and into a single distribution company
called National Grid Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
