<SECOND>AM-Lockheed-IBM,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM to Buy Lockheed's Cadam Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. will sell its Cadam Inc. software
subsidiary to International Business Machines Corp., the companies
said Thursday.
   IBM is already a major distributor for Cadam, of Burbank,
Calif., which makes software for computer-aided design and
manufacturing. The companies declined to disclose the purchase
price.
   Aharon Olansky, an analyst for Wedbush Morgan Securities Inc. in
New York, estimated the unit might have fetched roughly $100
million.
   Frank H. Puhl, Cadam's president, will remain with the company,
which will be an IBM subsidiary.
   IBM said the purchase of Cadam from the aerospace company would
``significantly assist IBM in its goal to be the premier solution
provider in the industry.''
