<DOCNO> AP891109-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FlightAttendants     11-09 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight Attendants,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union's Goals: Increased Pay, Job Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As takeovers and expansion attempts make cash
flow even more important to airline executives, leaders of the
Association of Flight Attendants tried Thursday to come up with a
strategy to secure higher pay and job security for their members.
   Susan Bianchi-Sand, president of the 27,000-member union, said
its board of directors is focusing on short-range planning because
of what is happening in the airline industry.
   Recent events include UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines,
pursuing a buyout or recapitalization of the nation's
second-largest carrier; Eastern Airlines struggling to make a
comeback in the face of an eight-month-old strike; and a number of
airlines, including United, battling to increase service to Europe
and Asia.
   ``We will be going to the table with newer and stronger
proposals for job security,'' said Ms. Bianchi-Sand, whose union
represents flight attendants on 18 airlines, including United. ``We
will want guarantees that the contract stays intact if a company is
bought.''
   Flight attendants' pay has fallen at carriers that have been
hard pressed by competition, she noted.
   In recent years, attendants have accepted pay cuts of as much as
20 percent to help carriers such as Republic Airlines, Western
Airlines and Braniff Inc. to survive. Republic and Western have
since been merged into larger carriers, while Braniff recently
filed for bankruptcy reorganization for the second time in seven
years.
   Also forcing down salaries has been two-tier wage scales, with
new flight attendants accepting starting salaries far below those
given their senior colleagues.
   Jack Hunter, an airline analyst for Howe Barnes Investments Inc.
in Chicago, noted that salary for B-scale attendants is $950 a
month, and that most contracts call for flight attendants to remain
at the lower scale for five years.
   ``The attendants will be trying to cut the B scale from five
years to three years'' in future negotiations, Hunter said.
   But that will be a difficult task because of airline expansion
plans and takeover activity, he said.
   Last year, most major airlines had strong profits, with
Dallas-based American Airlines showing a $476 million profit and
Chicago-based United $372 million.
   ``The airlines are trying to cut their costs,'' Hunter said.
``And they think that the only way they can keep expanding is
buying new airplanes. And the only way they can do that is a strong
cash flow.''
   Ms. Bianchi-Sand said her Washington, D.C.-based union also will
emphasize the issue of flight attendant health in future
negotiations with the carriers.
   ``There are issues of reproductive concerns because of
radioactive cargo, and cabin air quality apart from the smoking
issue,'' she said.
   Fumes are generated by cabin materials, Ms. Bianchi-Sand said,
and flight attendants are plagued by back problems caused by
pushing food carts that weigh more than 200 pounds.
   Perhaps one of the most difficult tasks for the union is
reaching a contract with United for its 14,000 flight attendants.
   Following the failure of a $6.75 billion takeover effort by
United's top management, its pilots union and British Airways PLC,
the attendants demanded a resumption of the federal mediation that
was suspended in August due to the buyout efforts.
   United's flight attendants joined the buyout bid in its latter
stages, a move Ms. Bianchi-Sand described as primarily a protective
strategy.
   ``We felt it was better to be part of the process instead of
letting someone else determine the fate of the airline,'' she said.
   Resuming contract talks could lead to a walkout if the
negotiations are as unsuccessful as they have been for the past two
years, union officials say.
   ``They had enormous demands for concessions that did not fit
reality,'' said Ms. Bianchi-Sand. ``They were seeking work rule and
benefit concessions that were not acceptable to membership.''
   Hunter says he believes flight attendants' negotiators will find
their work more difficult as airlines continue to cut costs to
maximize profits.
   ``In the future, you will see a situation of 10-year contracts
for flight attendants,'' he said.
   ``Attendants will be allowed to work 10 years only, there will
no longer be attendants working for years beyond that. The unions
will fight that hard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
