<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Thursday against most major
currencies except the Japanese yen and Canadian dollar.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid for gold at 4 p.m. EST of $386.30 a troy ounce, down from
$387.50 late Wednesday.
   Dealers said the dollar had little reaction to a
larger-than-expected 0.4 percent rise in U.S. wholesale prices in
October. Analysts had expected an increase in the Producer Price
Index of 0.2 percent.
   ``You saw most of the market react rather subdued to the PPI
report,'' said David Ethridge, vice president of foreign exchange
at Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. ``It wasn't a shock.''
   Currency traders said the dollar remained strong despite the
market's perception that the Federal Reserve is relaxing its credit
policy, which likely would encourage lower interest rates. Falling
interest rates usually depress the dollar's value.
   The key factor was selling between other currencies that pushed
down the dollar vs. the Japanese yen, said Keith Raphael, an
assistant vice president at Bank Brussels Lambert in New York.
   He said the yen rose against the West German mark and also
gained ground against the dollar in the morning. The selloff ran
out of steam when the dollar hit 142.25 yen and traders bought
dollars in an afternoon rally, traders said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 142.70 Japanese yen, down 0.27
yen from Wednesday's close. Later in London, the dollar rose to
142.85 yen. In New York, the dollar closed at 143.13, down from
143.18 late Wednesday.
   Raphael said the dollar rose against the British pound because
the Bank of England expressed concern that pressure to increase
wages could lead to a recession.
   In London, the British pound edged up to $1.5863 from $1.5860
late Wednesday. Later in New York, the pound fetched $1.5823, less
than $1.5885 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8523 West German marks, up from
1.8445; 1.6250 Swiss francs, up from 1.6168; 6.2810 French francs,
up from 6.2515; 1,354.25 Italian lire, up from 1,347.25; and 1.1670
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1698.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Wednesday, included: 1.8475 West German marks, up from 1.8450;
1.6212 Swiss francs, up from 1.6170; 6.2545 French francs, up from
6.2510; 2.0815 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0805; 1,351.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,349.50; and 1.1675 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1695.
   Gold bullion rose in London to a late bid of $386.25 a troy
ounce from $384.75 late Wednesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $387.30
from $384 late Wednesday.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold fell to $387.10 from
$388.80 the day before.
   Earlier, gold fell $1.08 an ounce in Hong Kong to $386.72.
   Silver bullion rose in late London trading to a four-month high
of $5.33 a troy ounce from $5.25 late Wednesday.
   On New York's Comex, silver contracts for current delivery
closed at $5.28 a troy ounce, down from $5.295.
</TEXT>
