<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-09 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Prices Continue to Surge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper prices continued their surge Thursday on New York's
Commodity Exchange amid investors' concerns over labor conditions
in Chile.
   On other markets, grain was mostly lower and soybeans higher;
energy and sugar futures were higher; gold was off while silver
gained and livestock and pork futures were mixed.
   Copper settled .70 cent to 1.35 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in November at $1.1640 a pound.
   Miners at Chile's four largest mines have voted to strike if the
government adopts a law that would reorganize state-owned Chile
Copper Corp. The proposal would give members of the military
government power over mine operations after the government leaves
office and reduce the power of unions.
   Helping to boost prices was the perception the metal had been
oversold in recent weeks because of settlement of labor disputes in
Canada and Mexico, said analyst Don Tierney of Stanley Bell &amp; Co.
in New York.
   Expectations that Monday's report on stocks in London Metal
Exchange-approved warehouses will show a decline also helped
prices, as did prospects that interest rates are going down, which
would increase demand, Tierney said.
   Grain futures were mostly lower and soybeans were higher in
quiet trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Trading in corn and soybeans was subdued as investors awaited
the release of the U.S. Department of Agriculture's latest crop
report.
   The report, released after the close of trading, estimated the
1989 corn harvest at 7.59 billion bushels, up 54 percent from last
year's drought-shriveled crop. The estimate was up 2 percent from
prospects a month ago when the department estimated this year's
production at 7.45 billion bushels.
   Soybean production, a source of high-protein meal and vegetable
oil, was estimated at 1.94 billion bushels, up 25 percent from last
year's harvest of 1.54 billion bushels and 1 percent above the
October estimate of 1.93 billion bushels.
   Wheat prices were forced lower due to a lack of export business,
although some support was received from the National Weather
Service's six- to 10-day forecast, which calls for dry weather in
winter wheat crop areas.
   Wheat was a { cent to 1{ cent lower with December at $4.03\ a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to } cent higher with December at
$2.36{ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1\ cent higher with December
at $1.42{ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 4} cents higher with
November at $5.67} a bushel.
   Precious metals futures were mixed in active trading on the
Comex as investors in gold decided to take profits and invest in
silver.
   Over the past three days, gold increased in value by $10, and a
correction was overdue, said Tierney.
   He noted that silver has had minor changes in value, trading up
or down in a minor range until Thursday when traders bailed out of
gold and bought silver in the expectation its price would go up.
   Gold settled $1.80 lower with December at $389 a troy ounce;
silver was 1.3 cents to 1.7 cents higher with December at $5.308 a
troy ounce.
   Sugar prices rose on New York's Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange
on technical factors and continued concern that Brazil will not
meet its export obligations.
   Prices also were boosted by reports the United States may
increase its import quotas, which would be a boost to the world
market, said analyst Kim Badenhop of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
Inc. in New York.
   Sugar was .16 cent to .21 cent higher with January at 15.01
cents a pound.
   Energy futures climbed on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 5 cents to 20 cents higher
with December at $19.92 a barrel; heating oil was .20 cent to .50
cent higher with December at 58.92 a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.35 cent to .71 cent higher with December at 52.22 a gallon.
   Livestock prices were up and pork futures were lower on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle was .13 cent to .35 cent higher with December at
74.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .40 cent higher
with November at 83.17 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .30
cent lower with December at 47.52 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to 1.30 cent lower with February at 63.17
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
