<FIRST>r f AM-Braniff     11-09 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Braniff,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Executives Review Possible Sale, Other Options</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc. may reactivate some of the
beleagured carrier's grounded fleet while continuing to seek a
buyer, a company official said Thursday.
   A skeletal group of executives are considering expanding the
Orlando-based carrier's charter services, leasing some of its
aircraft or establishing some kind of maintenance operation, said
Tom Volz, senior vice president for marketing.
   ``We're formulating a realistic business plan,'' said Volz.
   Braniff dismissed most of its remaining 1,800 employees after
shutting down its 46 daily flight schedule shortly after midnight
Monday.
   After filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection Sept. 28, the
carrier drastically cut back flights and laid off nearly 2,900
workers.
   Volz said 200 to 300 employees were still working Thursday,
including some 50 administrative people in Orlando and more than
150 in an accounting department in Dallas, the carrier's former
headquarters.
   Braniff Chairman William G. McGee and Chief Financial Officer W.
Howard Mackinnon have been trying to negotiate a possible $100
million sale to investors led by securities expert John Latshaw of
Kansas City. Company officials Thursday declined to give the
progress of the talks.
   ``There seems to be continued interest,'' said Volz.
   He said he had ``no knowledge at this time of any other action''
on a possible buyout or other short-term operations plan.
   Braniff, which was losing about $1.5 million a week before
filing for bankruptcy, already operates charters out of the
Bahamas, Salt Lake City and Dallas.
   Company officials are also trying to determine its work force
needs, Volz said.
   ``We hope to have some answers by early next week on those
questions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
