<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TWA     11-09 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-TWA,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>TWA Posts Loss for Third Fiscal Quarter, Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. said Thursday it lost
$29.9 million in its third fiscal quarter, citing higher interest
expenses associated with the privatization of the carrier last year
and higher operating costs.
   TWA, which is owned by takeover specialist Carl Icahn and based
in this New York suburb, said its loss for the three months ended
Sept. 30 contrasted with a profit of $88 million for the quarter a
year earlier.
   The results a year ago included a one-time gain of an
unspecified amount from litigation between TWA and the estate of
the late Howard Hughes, a previous owner. The latest figures fail
to reflect about $98 million in unrealized gains in TWA's
investment portfolio, the airline said.
   Revenue in the quarter was virually unchanged at $1.27 billion.
   The nation's sixth-largest carrier said its operating profit
tumbled to $60.7 million in the latest quarter from $141 million a
year earlier.
   It said its operating expenses climbed to $1.21 billion from
$1.13 billion because of the expiration of concessions previously
granted by the Machinists union, general salary increases, fuel
price increases and increased costs due to improvements in
trans-Atlantic service.
   For the first nine months of the fiscal year, TWA said it lost
$117.3 million in contrast to a profit of $132.7 million a year
earlier.
   Nine-month revenue rose 4 percent to $3.48 billion from $3.33
billion a year earlier.
   Though TWA is privately owned, it reports its earnings because
it has publicly traded bonds.
</TEXT>
