<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     11-09 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Scraps Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. on Thursday
scrapped its latest plan to emerge from bankruptcy protection after
Wells Fargo Bank withdrew its commitment to provide $400 million in
financing.
   The small-appliance maker said at a hearing in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court it would revert to a previously filed backup plan that would
repay virtually all creditors in new stock.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph L. Cosetti pledged to force lawyers
to work through the weekend to get an amended form of the stock
plan ready for a vote by creditors even if no alternative source of
bank financing can be found quickly.
   Meanwhile, The Pittsburgh Press reported Thursday that a group
that reportedly included shaving king Victor Kiam has offered to
buy Allegheny for $683.8 million.
   Kiam would become the new chief executive under the proposal
made by Japonica Partners, a New York investment firm, sources
familiar with the deal told The Press.
   Japonica made an offer for Allegheny in July and put more
substance behind the bid Wednesday in a letter to Allegheny's
board. The July offer gave no indication of how the bid would be
financed or how the reorganized company would be operated.
   At Thursday's hearing, lawyers for Allegheny and its major
creditors said they did not put much credence in the Japonica
proposal. Bruce McCullough, a lawyer for Allegheny, said the
company's board is ``not going to waste a lot of time on it.''
   Cosetti called Japonica's offer ``almost impertinent'' and said
it would not hold up consideration of management's newest plan.
   The skepticism stems from doubts about whether Japonica could
raise the money it says it is willing to pay for Allegheny.
   Japonica made its offer in conjunction with Steinhardt Partners,
a New York money management firm. Japonica said it was confident of
lining up financing from several banks, none of which was
identified.
   Japonica contended its bid is more sensibly financed than
Allegheny management's plan. All but $53 million of the $683.8
million price would be paid in cash. Unlike Allegheny's latest
plan, Japonica's would not use high-yield, high-risk debt
securities known as junk bonds.
   On a different front, Kiam, Remington Products' president and
pitchman, has recently worked on a possible bid for Allegheny in
conjunction with the equity committee in the company's bankruptcy
case. That effort is not related to Japonica's offer, according to
Gary Blu, the lead lawyer for the equity committee.
   Kiam was out of town Thursday and not immediately available for
comment, his secretary said.
   Wells Fargo previously expressed concern that the management
plan contained too little equity, but it had given no indication it
would withdraw its financing.
   Allegheny has been operating under Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy
protection since February 1988.
   Last month it filed two alternate plans to emerge from
bankruptcy. The company has filed several plans in its efforts to
reorganize but has met consistent opposition from creditors and
shareholders. Its debts currently total about $500 million.
</TEXT>
