<HEAD>Control Data To Sell Ticketron to Carlyle Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. said Thursday it
agreed to sell its Ticketron Sports &amp; Entertainment division to the
Carlyle Group, a private merchant banking firm based in Washington,
D.C.
   Terms were not disclosed.
   Control Data said it will retain its Automated Wagering Services
operation, which supplies on-line wagering systems to state
lotteries and off-track betting jurisdictions. The operation was
formerly part of Ticketron.
   Ticketron is the nation's oldest computerized ticketing service
company. Last year, Ticketron sold over 19 million tickets
generating about $450 million in gross ticket receipts and $41.4
million in revenue, while breaking even for Control Data.
   ``Carlyle's strengths will build on Ticketron's solid market
presence and reputation for customer service and make it an even
stronger competitor,'' said Lawrence Perlman, president and chief
operating officer of Control Data. ``The sale allows Control Data
to focus more resources on the growth of its Automated Wagering
Services operation and other businesses.''
   Carlyle is owned by the Richard King Mellon family and by the
Carlyle managing directors, which include Frank Carlucci, former
U.S. defense secretary.
   Earlier this year, Carlyle led an investor partnership that
bought Coldwell Banker Commercial Group from Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co.
   The Ticketron sale is expected to be completed in 30 days.
