<FILEID>AP-NR-11-09-89 0011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Volcker     11-09 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Volcker,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Federal Reserve Chairman Volcker Says No Recession Ahead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Volcker, former chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board, said he doesn't foresee a recession in the
near future, but warned that Americans should re-examine their
habits of overspending and dependence on foreign capital.
   Volcker, who oversaw the nation's monetary policy under the
Carter and Reagan administrations, pointed to the recent Japanese
acquisitions of Columbia Pictures and Firestone Tire as warning
signals.
   ``Japan has been lending us a lot of money and buying a lot of
our companies,'' Volcker said. ``It has financed a large part of
our deficit. It has also permitted our consumption to proceed.''
   Volcker, now chairman of the James T. Wolfensohn investment
banking firm, was in Birmingham to speak at Birmingham-Southern
College.
   Volcker said the nation's economy will likely continue its
current seven-year expansion, the longest peacetime growth period.
He noted that the unemployment rate has hit a 15-year low, prices
are stable and inflation is remaining steady at about 4 percent.
   ``The chances are good, in fact, that we will avoid a recession
in the next year, and if we play our cards right, we may have an
expansion for years to come,'' Volcker said.
   Despite his optimistic forecast, the former policy-maker warned
that the economy's built-in risks _ the federal and trade deficits,
reliance on foreign capital and a low savings rate _ continue to
threaten growth.
   Volcker said the stock market crash of Oct. 19, 1987, was a sign
of problems in the economic system but that investors did not heed
the warning and continue to shrug off the twin deficits.
   With a higher savings rate, Americans could finance more of the
economy themselves, he said.
   ``There are more risks than usual in our economy,'' he said.
``They are pretty well known.''
</TEXT>
