<FIRST>u f AM-StarTribune-Guild 1stLd-Writethru f0344 11-09 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Tribune-Guild, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0344,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guild Members Approve Pact With Star Tribune</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with union approving pact, vote
total, quotes. Picks up penultimate graf, `Union members...'. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Star Tribune newsroom employees approved a
six-year contract Wednesday night, hours after their second strike
deadline in as many days, but union leaders could find little
positive to say about the deal.
   Guild Chairwoman Margaret Zack said the vote was 233-70.
   A lack of support from other unions at plant helped spur the
reluctant membership to accept the contract after several hours of
discussion, union leaders said.
   ``It's a bad deal. It's a rotten deal,'' said Jay Weiner, vice
chairman of the negotiating committee. But Guild members feared
they would be replaced in a prolonged strike, he said.
   ``We could have struck, but without the other unions it would
have been extremely difficult,'' said strike coordinator Steve
Brandt, who characterized the contract as ``punitive.''
   ``It simply doesn't meet the needs of people trying to keep
their standard of living intact,'' he said.
   Star Tribune spokeswoman Bette Fenton said the newspaper was
``back to work as usual.''
   ``We had hoped from the very beginning that we were able to
reach a fair and equitable settlement and we're pleased that we've
done that,'' she said.
   Brandt said the contract covers six years and includes bonuses
in each of the first three years, and pay raises of 3.2 percent in
the fourth year, 3.1 percent in the fifth year and 3.0 percent in
the sixth year.
   For top scale reporters, photographers, copy editors and
district circulation managers, the bonuses would be $2,000 in the
first year, $1,750 in the second and $1,500 in the third, Brandt
said.
   The pay raises for top-scale employees would amount to about $26
a week in each of the last three years, he said. Weiner said the
package averages out to a 1.6 percent annual increase in pay scales
over six years. He called it ``worse by far'' than the recent deal
struck by Guild employees at the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch.
   Supervisors worked on scaled-down editions of Thursday's paper
until union members returned at about 10:15 p.m., Brandt said.
   The union's original strike deadline was 4 p.m. Tuesday, but
that was extended to 4 p.m. Wednesday. As the deadline passed,
union negotiators said they were waiting for the company's response
to a new offer they had made.
   Other provisions of the tentative pact as described by Brandt
include:
   _Six employees would be removed from Guild jurisdiction, rather
than the 26 originally proposed by the company.
   _Mileage would increase 1 cent a mile, to 22 cents; the Guild
had sought an increase to 28 cents.
   Union members have been working without a contract since their
three-year pact expired July 31. The Minneapolis unit covers about
300 newsroom employees and about 60 circulation and promotion
workers.
   Under the old contract, top minimum weekly salaries for Star
Tribune Guild members have been $315.50 for copy aides; $742.50 for
circulation district managers; $812 for reporters, photographers,
copy editors and promotion personnel; and $895.75 for some editors,
the Guild said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
